const CONCEPTS={Biology:{color:"var(--green)",icon:"🧬",items:[{term:"Mitochondria",def:"Double-membraned organelle that produces ATP via aerobic cellular respiration. The Krebs cycle runs in the matrix; the electron transport chain runs on the inner membrane (cristae). Contains its own circular DNA, evidence of endosymbiotic origin.",keywords:["mitochondri","krebs","cristae"]},{term:"Mitosis",def:"Nuclear division producing two genetically identical diploid daughter cells. Phases (PMAT): Prophase (chromatin condenses), Metaphase (chromosomes align at cell plate), Anaphase (sister chromatids separate), Telophase (nuclei reform). Used for growth and repair.",keywords:["mitosis","metaphase","anaphase","prophase","telophase","sister chromatid"]},{term:"Meiosis",def:"Two-stage division producing four haploid gametes with genetic variation. Crossing over (recombination) occurs during Prophase I. Meiosis I separates homologous pairs; Meiosis II separates sister chromatids. Results in genetic diversity.",keywords:["meiosis","haploid","gamete","crossing over","homologous"]},{term:"Central Dogma",def:"DNA → RNA → Protein. Transcription: RNA polymerase reads the template DNA strand to produce mRNA in the nucleus. Translation: ribosomes read mRNA codons and tRNA anticodons to assemble polypeptides. rRNA is synthesized in the nucleolus.",keywords:["transcription","translation","mrna","trna","rna polymerase","codon","nucleolus"]},{term:"Enzymes",def:"Protein catalysts that lower activation energy without being consumed. Substrates bind at the active site. Classes: oxidoreductase (redox), hydrolase (water addition), transferase (group transfer), lyase (bond breaking without water), isomerase, ligase.",keywords:["enzyme","catalyst","active site","substrate","hydrolase","oxidoreductase","transferase","lyase"]},{term:"Photosynthesis",def:"Converts light energy to chemical energy in chloroplasts. Light reactions (thylakoid membranes): split water, produce ATP and NADPH, release O₂. Calvin cycle (stroma): fixes CO₂ into G3P using ATP and NADPH. Net: 6CO₂ + 6H₂O → C₆H₁₂O₆ + 6O₂.",keywords:["photosynthes","chloroplast","calvin cycle","thylakoid","stroma","chlorophyll"]},{term:"Cellular Respiration",def:"Breaks down glucose to ATP: Glycolysis (cytoplasm, 2 net ATP), Krebs/Citric Acid Cycle (matrix, 2 ATP), Electron Transport Chain (inner membrane, ~32 ATP). Anaerobic fermentation produces lactic acid (animals) or ethanol + CO₂ (yeast).",keywords:["glycolysis","krebs cycle","electron transport","fermentation","pyruvate","nadh","lactic acid"]},{term:"Mendelian Genetics",def:"Dominant alleles mask recessive ones in heterozygotes. F2 monohybrid cross: 3:1 phenotype ratio. Dihybrid cross (F2): 9:3:3:1 ratio. Law of Segregation: allele pairs separate during gamete formation. Law of Independent Assortment: genes on different chromosomes assort independently.",keywords:["dominant","recessive","allele","phenotype","genotype","heterozygous","homozygous"]},{term:"Ecological Relationships",def:"Mutualism (+/+): both benefit. Commensalism (+/0): one benefits, other unaffected. Parasitism (+/−): parasite benefits, host is harmed. Competition (−/−): both harmed. Predation (+/−): predator benefits. Niche: the ecological role of an organism in its community.",keywords:["mutualism","commensalism","parasitism","symbiosis","predation","competition","niche"]},{term:"Domains & Classification",def:"Three domains: Bacteria (no nucleus, peptidoglycan cell walls, single RNA polymerase), Archaea (no nucleus, no peptidoglycan, multiple RNA polymerases, can have introns), Eukarya (nucleus, complex organelles). Six-kingdom system places Monera, Protista, Fungi, Plantae, and Animalia under domains.",keywords:["archaea","bacteria","domain","eubacteri","prokaryote","eukaryote","peptidoglycan"]},{term:"Cell Organelles",def:"Nucleus: DNA storage and transcription. Ribosome: protein synthesis (80S in eukaryotes, 70S in prokaryotes). Rough ER: protein folding with ribosomes. Smooth ER: lipid synthesis. Golgi: modifies and packages proteins. Lysosome: hydrolytic digestion. Vacuole: storage (large in plant cells).",keywords:["golgi","lysosome","endoplasmic reticulum","ribosom","vacuol","cell wall"]},{term:"Nervous System",def:"CNS (brain + spinal cord) processes information. PNS: sensory (afferent) carries signals to CNS; motor (efferent) carries signals away. Neurons transmit via action potentials (all-or-nothing); neurotransmitters cross the synaptic cleft. Reflex arcs bypass the brain for fast responses.",keywords:["neuron","neurotransmitter","synapse","axon","dendrite","reflex","action potential"]},{term:"Cell Membrane",def:"Fluid mosaic model: phospholipid bilayer with embedded proteins. Hydrophilic heads face outward; hydrophobic tails face inward. Selectively permeable — small nonpolar molecules pass freely, large or charged molecules require transport proteins. Cholesterol stabilizes membrane fluidity.",keywords:["fluid mosaic","phospholipid","membrane","selectively permeable","cholesterol","transport protein"]},{term:"Osmosis & Diffusion",def:"Diffusion: net movement of molecules from high to low concentration (passive, no energy). Osmosis: diffusion of water across a semipermeable membrane toward higher solute concentration. Hypertonic solution: cell loses water (crenation in animals, plasmolysis in plants). Hypotonic: cell gains water.",keywords:["osmosis","diffusion","hypertonic","hypotonic","isotonic","concentration gradient","plasmolysis"]},{term:"Circulatory System",def:"Heart has 4 chambers: right atrium → right ventricle → lungs (pulmonary circuit) → left atrium → left ventricle → body (systemic circuit). Oxygenated blood enters the left atrium via pulmonary veins. Arteries carry blood away from heart; veins return blood to heart.",keywords:["heart","atrium","ventricle","circulatory","artery","vein","pulmonary","systemic"]},{term:"Immune System",def:"Innate immunity: non-specific (skin barrier, phagocytes, inflammation). Adaptive immunity: specific responses. B cells produce antibodies (humoral immunity). T cells: helper T cells (CD4+) coordinate response; cytotoxic T cells (CD8+) kill infected cells. Memory cells enable faster secondary responses.",keywords:["immune","antibody","b cell","t cell","antigen","phagocyte","lymphocyte","adaptive","innate"]},{term:"Endocrine System",def:"Glands secrete hormones into the bloodstream. Hypothalamus controls the pituitary (master gland). Key glands: thyroid (thyroxine — metabolism), adrenal (epinephrine, cortisol — stress), pancreas (insulin lowers blood glucose; glucagon raises it), gonads (sex hormones).",keywords:["hormone","endocrine","pituitary","thyroid","insulin","glucagon","adrenal","hypothalamus"]},{term:"Digestive System",def:"Mechanical and chemical breakdown of food. Mouth (amylase), esophagus, stomach (pepsin, HCl, pH ~2), small intestine (site of most absorption; villi and microvilli increase surface area), large intestine (water reabsorption). Liver produces bile; pancreas secretes digestive enzymes and bicarbonate.",keywords:["digestive","stomach","small intestine","bile","pancreas","amylase","pepsin","liver","villi"]},{term:"Respiratory System",def:"Oxygen enters via nose/mouth → trachea → bronchi → bronchioles → alveoli (site of gas exchange). CO₂ diffuses out; O₂ diffuses into capillaries. Hemoglobin in red blood cells carries O₂ as oxyhemoglobin. Diaphragm contraction increases lung volume (inhalation = active process).",keywords:["lung","alveoli","bronchi","trachea","hemoglobin","respiratory","diaphragm","gas exchange"]},{term:"Excretory System",def:"Kidneys filter blood to produce urine. Functional unit: nephron. Glomerulus (capillary ball in Bowman's capsule) filters blood by pressure. Loop of Henle concentrates filtrate. Collecting duct reabsorbs water (regulated by ADH). Nitrogenous wastes: urea (mammals), uric acid (birds/reptiles), ammonia (fish).",keywords:["kidney","nephron","glomerulus","urea","excretory","bowman","loop of henle","filtration"]},{term:"Viruses",def:"Non-living infectious agents consisting of nucleic acid (DNA or RNA) surrounded by a protein coat (capsid); some have a lipid envelope. Lytic cycle: virus hijacks host, replicates, lyses cell (releases new viruses). Lysogenic cycle: viral DNA integrates into host genome (prophage) and replicates with host.",keywords:["virus","capsid","lytic","lysogenic","bacteriophage","retrovirus","rna virus","viral"]},{term:"Population Genetics",def:"Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium: allele frequencies stable if no mutation, migration, genetic drift, natural selection, or non-random mating. Equations: p + q = 1; p² + 2pq + q² = 1. Natural selection acts on phenotypes (determined by genotypes). Genetic drift: random allele frequency change in small populations.",keywords:["hardy-weinberg","allele frequency","genetic drift","natural selection","population genetics","gene pool"]},{term:"Plant Structure & Reproduction",def:"Vascular plants have xylem (water/minerals upward) and phloem (sugars bidirectionally). Angiosperms (flowering plants) produce seeds in fruit; gymnosperms produce naked seeds (cones). Monocots: parallel leaf veins, fibrous roots; dicots: branching veins, taproot. Bryophytes (mosses) lack vascular tissue.",keywords:["xylem","phloem","angiosperm","gymnosperm","monocot","dicot","bryophyte","vascular","stamen","pistil"]},{term:"Muscle Tissue",def:"Skeletal muscle: striated, voluntary, attached to bones via tendons, multinucleated. Smooth muscle: non-striated, involuntary, found in organ walls and blood vessels. Cardiac muscle: striated, involuntary, found only in the heart, connected by intercalated discs. Sarcomere is the basic contractile unit.",keywords:["skeletal muscle","smooth muscle","cardiac muscle","sarcomere","actin","myosin","muscle tissue"]},{term:"Homeostasis",def:"Maintenance of stable internal conditions despite external changes. Negative feedback: response opposes the stimulus (e.g., insulin lowers high blood glucose). Positive feedback: response amplifies the stimulus (e.g., oxytocin during childbirth, blood clotting). Temperature, pH, and blood glucose are key regulated variables.",keywords:["homeostasis","negative feedback","positive feedback","thermoregulation","blood glucose","pH regulation"]},{term:"DNA Structure",def:"Double helix: two antiparallel strands of nucleotides. Each nucleotide: deoxyribose sugar, phosphate group, nitrogenous base. Complementary base pairing: A–T (2 hydrogen bonds), G–C (3 hydrogen bonds). 5'→3' directionality. Chargaff's rule: %A = %T and %G = %C in any organism.",keywords:["dna structure","double helix","base pair","adenine","thymine","guanine","cytosine","nucleotide","chargaff"]},{term:"Evolution & Natural Selection",def:"Natural selection: heritable variation + differential reproductive success = adaptation over generations. Darwin's observations: overproduction, variation, heritability, differential survival. Speciation: allopatric (geographic isolation) vs sympatric. Evidence: fossil record, homologous structures, molecular phylogenetics.",keywords:["natural selection","evolution","speciation","adaptation","fitness","darwin","allopatric","homologous structure"]},{term:"ATP & Energy Currency",def:"ATP (adenosine triphosphate) is the universal energy currency of cells. Structure: adenine base + ribose sugar + three phosphate groups. Hydrolysis of ATP → ADP + Pᵢ releases ~7.3 kcal/mol. ATP is regenerated by substrate-level phosphorylation (glycolysis, Krebs) and oxidative phosphorylation (ETC). The cell maintains a high ATP:ADP ratio to drive endergonic reactions.",keywords:["atp","adp","energy currency","phosphorylation","adenosine triphosphate","hydrolysis atp"]},{term:"Signal Transduction",def:"Process by which cells respond to external signals. Steps: ligand binds receptor → second messenger generated → cascade of phosphorylation events → cellular response. Types: G-protein coupled receptors (GPCRs) use cAMP or IP₃/Ca²⁺ as second messengers; receptor tyrosine kinases (RTKs) phosphorylate proteins directly. Amplification: one ligand triggers many downstream effectors.",keywords:["signal transduction","receptor","second messenger","camp","g-protein","kinase","ligand","phosphorylation cascade"]},{term:"Cell Cycle & Cancer",def:"Phases: G1 (cell growth), S (DNA replication), G2 (preparation for division), M (mitosis + cytokinesis). Checkpoints: G1/S (DNA damage), G2/M (replication complete), spindle checkpoint (chromosomes attached). Cyclins and CDKs drive progression. p53 is a tumor suppressor that halts the cycle at damage. Mutations disabling checkpoints or activating proto-oncogenes lead to cancer.",keywords:["cell cycle","g1","g2","s phase","checkpoint","cyclin","cdk","tumor suppressor","p53","oncogene","cancer"]},{term:"Apoptosis",def:"Programmed cell death — an orderly, energy-dependent process essential for development and homeostasis. Intrinsic pathway: mitochondria release cytochrome c in response to DNA damage → activates caspase cascade. Extrinsic pathway: death receptors (e.g., Fas) activated by external signals. Apoptosis eliminates damaged, infected, or unneeded cells without triggering inflammation. Defective apoptosis → cancer or autoimmune disease.",keywords:["apoptosis","programmed cell death","caspase","cytochrome c","intrinsic pathway","extrinsic pathway","cell death"]},{term:"Stem Cells",def:"Undifferentiated cells capable of self-renewal and differentiation into specialized cell types. Totipotent: can form any cell (fertilized egg). Pluripotent: most cell types (embryonic stem cells, iPSCs). Multipotent: limited types (bone marrow stem cells → blood cells). Induced pluripotent stem cells (iPSCs): adult cells reprogrammed to pluripotency by Yamanaka factors (Oct4, Sox2, Klf4, c-Myc).",keywords:["stem cell","totipotent","pluripotent","multipotent","ipsc","differentiation","embryonic stem cell","yamanaka"]},{term:"Biotechnology & CRISPR",def:"PCR (polymerase chain reaction): amplifies DNA exponentially using primers and Taq polymerase. Gel electrophoresis: separates DNA fragments by size. Restriction enzymes cut DNA at specific sequences; ligase joins fragments (recombinant DNA). CRISPR-Cas9: guide RNA directs Cas9 nuclease to cut target DNA; allows precise gene editing. Southern blot: detects specific DNA sequences; Northern: RNA; Western: proteins.",keywords:["pcr","gel electrophoresis","restriction enzyme","crispr","cas9","recombinant dna","gene editing","southern blot","cloning"]},{term:"Protein Structure",def:"Primary: sequence of amino acids linked by peptide bonds (determined by DNA). Secondary: local folding into α-helices and β-sheets via hydrogen bonds between backbone atoms. Tertiary: overall 3-D shape stabilized by hydrophobic interactions, disulfide bonds, ionic bonds, H-bonds between R groups. Quaternary: multiple polypeptide subunits (e.g., hemoglobin has 4). Denaturation disrupts 3-D structure without breaking peptide bonds.",keywords:["protein structure","primary structure","secondary structure","tertiary structure","quaternary structure","alpha helix","beta sheet","denaturation","peptide bond"]},{term:"Lipids",def:"Hydrophobic biomolecules. Triglycerides: glycerol + 3 fatty acids; energy storage (9 kcal/g). Saturated fats: no double bonds, solid at room temp. Unsaturated (mono/poly): one or more double bonds, liquid at room temp. Phospholipids: form cell membranes (hydrophilic head, hydrophobic tails). Steroids: four-ring structure; cholesterol is membrane component and precursor to steroid hormones (testosterone, estrogen, cortisol).",keywords:["lipid","triglyceride","fatty acid","saturated","unsaturated","phospholipid","steroid","cholesterol","hydrophobic"]},{term:"Carbohydrates",def:"Monosaccharides: simplest sugars (glucose, fructose, galactose — C₆H₁₂O₆). Disaccharides: two monosaccharides joined by glycosidic bond (sucrose = glucose + fructose; lactose = glucose + galactose; maltose = glucose + glucose). Polysaccharides: starch and glycogen (branched glucose polymers for energy storage); cellulose (β-1,4 linkages; structural; humans cannot digest); chitin (structural in fungi/arthropods).",keywords:["carbohydrate","glucose","monosaccharide","disaccharide","polysaccharide","starch","glycogen","cellulose","sucrose","glycosidic bond"]},{term:"Nitrogen Cycle",def:"Nitrogen fixation: N₂ → NH₃ by Rhizobium (in legume root nodules) and free-living bacteria (Azotobacter). Nitrification: NH₃ → NO₂⁻ (Nitrosomonas) → NO₃⁻ (Nitrobacter). Assimilation: plants absorb NH₄⁺ or NO₃⁻ to make amino acids and nucleic acids. Ammonification: decomposers convert organic N back to NH₄⁺. Denitrification: NO₃⁻ → N₂ by anaerobic bacteria (Pseudomonas). Humans disrupt the cycle via fertilizers and combustion.",keywords:["nitrogen cycle","nitrogen fixation","nitrification","denitrification","ammonification","rhizobium","nitrate","ammonia"]},{term:"Ecological Succession",def:"The gradual process of community change over time. Primary succession: begins on bare rock with no soil (volcanic island, glacier retreat); pioneer species (lichens, mosses) weather rock and build soil. Secondary succession: disturbance of an existing ecosystem (fire, flood); soil remains so recovery is faster. Climax community: stable endpoint determined by climate. Facilitation: early species modify the environment enabling later species.",keywords:["succession","primary succession","secondary succession","pioneer species","climax community","lichen","facilitation","disturbance ecology"]},{term:"Animal Behavior",def:"Innate (fixed action patterns, FAPs): genetically determined, triggered by specific stimuli (releaser). Learned: habituation (decreased response to repeated stimulus), classical conditioning (Pavlov), operant conditioning (Skinner), imprinting (Lorenz — critical period), insight learning. Altruism explained by kin selection (Hamilton's rule: rb > c, where r = relatedness, b = benefit, c = cost). Foraging theory: optimal energy gain per unit time.",keywords:["innate behavior","learned behavior","imprinting","habituation","classical conditioning","operant conditioning","kin selection","hamilton's rule","altruism"]},{term:"Fungi",def:"Heterotrophic decomposers with cell walls of chitin. Body plan: hyphae (filaments) forming a mycelium. Reproduction: asexual (conidia spores) and sexual (zygospores, ascospores, basidiospores). Major phyla: Zygomycota (bread molds), Ascomycota (yeasts, morels, Penicillium), Basidiomycota (mushrooms, rusts, smuts). Mycorrhizae: mutualistic symbiosis with plant roots (provide phosphorus; receive sugars). Lichens: mutualism with algae/cyanobacteria.",keywords:["fungi","hyphae","mycelium","chitin","ascomycota","basidiomycota","mycorrhizae","lichen","decomposer","spore"]},{term:"Protists",def:"Paraphyletic group of mostly unicellular eukaryotes. Algae (photoautotrophic): diatoms (silica shells), dinoflagellates (red tides, bioluminescence), green algae (ancestor of plants). Animal-like protozoa: amoeba (pseudopods), paramecium (cilia), trypanosoma (flagella, causes sleeping sickness), Plasmodium (causes malaria — transmitted by Anopheles mosquito). Slime molds: form multicellular fruiting bodies for reproduction.",keywords:["protist","algae","protozoa","diatom","dinoflagellate","amoeba","paramecium","plasmodium","malaria","slime mold"]},{term:"Plant Hormones",def:"Auxin (IAA): cell elongation, phototropism (shoots toward light), apical dominance (suppresses lateral buds); made in shoot tips. Gibberellins: stem elongation, seed germination, fruit development (seedless fruits). Cytokinins: promote cell division, delay senescence; synthesized in roots. Ethylene (gas): fruit ripening, leaf/flower/fruit abscission, response to mechanical stress. Abscisic acid (ABA): stomatal closure during drought, seed dormancy, stress response.",keywords:["auxin","gibberellin","cytokinin","ethylene","abscisic acid","aba","phototropism","apical dominance","plant hormone","senescence"]},{term:"Plant Reproduction",def:"Angiosperms (flowering plants): flowers contain stamens (anther produces pollen = male gametophyte) and pistil (stigma, style, ovary with ovules). Pollination: transfer of pollen to stigma (wind, insects, birds). Double fertilization (unique to angiosperms): one sperm + egg → zygote (2n); second sperm + polar nuclei → endosperm (3n, nutrient tissue). Fruit = mature ovary. Seed dispersal: wind, water, animals (ingestion or attachment).",keywords:["angiosperm","stamen","pistil","pollen","double fertilization","endosperm","ovary","fruit","seed dispersal","pollination"]},{term:"Osmoregulation",def:"Regulation of water and solute balance. Kidney nephron: glomerular filtration (pressure-driven), tubular reabsorption (glucose, amino acids, Na⁺ reabsorbed; loop of Henle concentrates filtrate), tubular secretion (H⁺, K⁺ added). ADH (vasopressin): increases water permeability of collecting duct → concentrated urine. Aldosterone: increases Na⁺ reabsorption → retains water. Freshwater fish: hypotonic environment; lose salts, gain water — excrete dilute urine.",keywords:["osmoregulation","nephron","adh","aldosterone","loop of henle","filtration","reabsorption","secretion","aquaporin"]},{term:"Thermoregulation",def:"Ectotherms (poikilotherms): body temperature varies with environment; rely on behavioral regulation (basking, burrowing). Endotherms (homeotherms): maintain constant core temperature via metabolic heat; include birds and mammals. Mechanisms: shivering (muscle thermogenesis), sweating/panting (evaporative cooling), vasodilation (radiates heat) vs. vasoconstriction (conserves heat). Brown adipose tissue (BAT): non-shivering thermogenesis. Countercurrent heat exchange in extremities.",keywords:["thermoregulation","ectotherm","endotherm","homeotherm","shivering","vasodilation","vasoconstriction","countercurrent","brown adipose"]},{term:"Reproductive Strategies",def:"External fertilization: sperm and eggs released into water (fish, amphibians); requires aquatic environment. Internal fertilization: sperm deposited inside female; required for terrestrial life. Oviparous: eggs develop outside (birds, reptiles, fish). Ovoviviparous: eggs retained internally (some sharks, snakes). Viviparous: live birth with placenta (most mammals). r-strategy: many small offspring, little parental care (insects). K-strategy: few offspring, heavy parental investment (elephants, humans).",keywords:["external fertilization","internal fertilization","oviparous","viviparous","placenta","r-strategy","k-strategy","parental care"]},{term:"Gene Regulation",def:"Prokaryotes — operons: lac operon (glucose absent + lactose present → CAP activates; lac repressor inactivated → transcription on). Eukaryotes: transcription factors bind enhancers/promoters; histone acetylation opens chromatin (active); methylation silences genes; RNA processing (alternative splicing → multiple proteins from one gene); miRNA: small RNAs that base-pair with mRNA → degradation or translation inhibition. Epigenetics: heritable changes in gene expression without DNA sequence change.",keywords:["gene regulation","lac operon","transcription factor","enhancer","histone","epigenetics","alternative splicing","mirna","methylation","chromatin"]},{term:"Biotechnology Applications",def:"Transgenic organisms: GMO crops (Bt toxin gene from Bacillus thuringiensis inserted into corn/soy). Gene therapy: correcting defective genes (e.g., AAV vectors for SCID, hemophilia). Monoclonal antibodies: produced by hybridoma cells; used in cancer treatment (trastuzumab) and diagnostics. DNA fingerprinting: uses STR (short tandem repeat) analysis; used in forensics and paternity testing. Human Genome Project (completed 2003): sequenced ~3 billion base pairs across 23 chromosome pairs.",keywords:["transgenic","gmo","gene therapy","monoclonal antibody","dna fingerprinting","str","human genome project","hybridoma"]},{term:"Sensory Systems",def:"Mechanoreceptors: detect pressure/vibration (Meissner's, Pacinian corpuscles in skin; hair cells in cochlea for hearing). Photoreceptors: rods (dim light, monochromatic, peripheral) and cones (color vision, S/M/L for blue/green/red, fovea for acuity). Chemoreceptors: olfactory neurons (smell, ~400 receptor types) and taste buds (sweet, salty, sour, bitter, umami). Nociceptors: pain. Vestibular system: semicircular canals detect rotational acceleration; utricle/saccule detect linear acceleration.",keywords:["mechanoreceptor","photoreceptor","rod","cone","chemoreceptor","nociceptor","hair cell","cochlea","fovea","vestibular","sensory"]},{term:"Hardy-Weinberg Principle",def:"Allele frequencies remain stable in a population across generations when: no mutation, no migration (gene flow), no genetic drift, random mating, no natural selection. Equations: p + q = 1 (allele frequencies); p² + 2pq + q² = 1 (genotype frequencies). Hardy-Weinberg is used as a null model to detect evolution: any deviation from expected frequencies indicates one of the five forces is acting on the population.",keywords:["hardy-weinberg","allele frequency","genotype frequency","population genetics","null model","gene flow","random mating"]},{level:"MS",term:"Cell Theory",def:"Three principles: (1) All living things are made of cells. (2) The cell is the basic unit of life. (3) All cells come from pre-existing cells. Proposed by Schleiden (plants), Schwann (animals), and Virchow (cell division). Prokaryotic cells (bacteria) lack a membrane-bound nucleus; eukaryotic cells (animals, plants, fungi) have a nucleus.",keywords:["cell theory","schleiden","schwann","virchow","prokaryote","eukaryote"]},{level:"MS",term:"Cell Structure",def:"Cell membrane: controls what enters and exits. Nucleus: contains DNA and directs cell activities. Cytoplasm: jelly-like fluid inside cell. Mitochondria: produce energy (ATP). Ribosomes: make proteins. Plant cells also have: cell wall (rigid support), chloroplasts (photosynthesis), and a large central vacuole (water storage).",keywords:["cell membrane","nucleus","cytoplasm","mitochondria","ribosome","chloroplast","cell wall","vacuole"]},{level:"MS",term:"Photosynthesis (Basic)",def:"Process by which plants, algae, and some bacteria convert sunlight, water, and carbon dioxide into glucose and oxygen. Occurs in the chloroplasts. Equation: 6CO₂ + 6H₂O + light energy → C₆H₁₂O₆ + 6O₂. Chlorophyll is the green pigment that absorbs light. Plants use glucose for energy and to build plant matter.",keywords:["photosynthesis","chlorophyll","chloroplast","glucose","carbon dioxide","sunlight"]},{level:"MS",term:"Cellular Respiration (Basic)",def:"Process that breaks down glucose to release energy (ATP) that cells can use. Aerobic respiration requires oxygen: C₆H₁₂O₆ + 6O₂ → 6CO₂ + 6H₂O + ATP. Occurs in the mitochondria. Anaerobic respiration (fermentation) occurs without oxygen and produces less ATP. Animals, plants, and most organisms use aerobic respiration.",keywords:["cellular respiration","aerobic","anaerobic","fermentation","atp","glucose","mitochondria"]},{level:"MS",term:"Ecosystems & Food Webs",def:"Producers (plants) make their own food via photosynthesis. Primary consumers (herbivores) eat producers. Secondary consumers eat herbivores. Tertiary consumers are top predators. Decomposers (bacteria, fungi) break down dead matter and recycle nutrients. Only about 10% of energy transfers between each trophic level.",keywords:["producer","consumer","herbivore","carnivore","decomposer","food web","trophic","ecosystem","food chain"]},{level:"MS",term:"Genetics Basics",def:"Traits are controlled by genes, which are segments of DNA. Each organism has two copies of each gene (alleles), one from each parent. Dominant alleles (capital letter) are expressed when present; recessive alleles (lowercase) are only expressed when two copies exist. Punnett squares predict the probability of offspring traits.",keywords:["gene","allele","dominant","recessive","punnett square","trait","heredity","dna"]},{level:"MS",term:"Classification of Organisms",def:"Organisms are classified into a hierarchy: Domain → Kingdom → Phylum → Class → Order → Family → Genus → Species. Three domains: Bacteria, Archaea, Eukarya. Six kingdoms: Archaebacteria, Eubacteria, Protista, Fungi, Plantae, Animalia. Scientific names use two-part (binomial) nomenclature: Genus species (e.g., Homo sapiens).",keywords:["classification","taxonomy","kingdom","domain","binomial nomenclature","genus","species","phylum"]},{level:"MS",term:"Human Body Systems",def:"Skeletal (support/protection), muscular (movement), nervous (signal coordination), circulatory (blood transport), respiratory (gas exchange), digestive (nutrient absorption), excretory (waste removal), endocrine (hormone regulation), immune (disease defense), integumentary (skin barrier). Each system works with others to maintain homeostasis.",keywords:["body system","skeletal","muscular","nervous","circulatory","respiratory","digestive","excretory","immune","homeostasis"]},{level:"MS",term:"DNA & Heredity",def:"DNA (deoxyribonucleic acid) carries genetic information in the nucleus. DNA is made of nucleotides with four bases: adenine (A), thymine (T), guanine (G), cytosine (C). A pairs with T; G pairs with C. Genes on chromosomes code for proteins. Mutations are changes in DNA sequence. Humans have 46 chromosomes (23 pairs).",keywords:["dna","nucleotide","base pair","chromosome","mutation","gene","heredity","adenine","thymine"]},{level:"MS",term:"Natural Selection",def:"Process by which individuals with favorable traits survive and reproduce more than others, passing those traits to offspring. Four conditions: (1) variation exists in a population, (2) traits are heritable, (3) more offspring are produced than can survive, (4) some traits increase survival. Over time, adaptations accumulate in a population.",keywords:["natural selection","adaptation","variation","survival","darwin","evolution","fitness","inherit"]},{level:"MS",term:"Mitosis (Basic)",def:"Cell division that produces two identical daughter cells with the same number of chromosomes as the parent cell. Used for growth, repair, and asexual reproduction. Phases: Prophase (chromatin condenses into chromosomes), Metaphase (chromosomes line up in the middle), Anaphase (chromosomes pulled to opposite poles), Telophase (nuclear membranes reform). Cytokinesis: division of the cytoplasm. Result: 2 genetically identical diploid cells.",keywords:["mitosis","prophase","metaphase","anaphase","telophase","cell division","chromosome","cytokinesis","diploid"]},{level:"MS",term:"Osmosis & Diffusion (Basic)",def:"Diffusion: movement of particles from high concentration to low concentration (passive transport; no energy needed). Osmosis: diffusion of water across a semipermeable membrane from a region of low solute concentration to high solute concentration. Hypotonic solution: cell gains water and may burst (lysis). Hypertonic solution: cell loses water and shrinks (crenation in animals; plasmolysis in plants). Isotonic: no net water movement.",keywords:["osmosis","diffusion","semipermeable","hypertonic","hypotonic","isotonic","concentration gradient","passive transport"]},{level:"MS",term:"Biomes",def:"Large regions of Earth characterized by similar climate, vegetation, and wildlife. Major terrestrial biomes: tropical rainforest (hot, wet, high biodiversity), savanna (warm, seasonal rainfall, grassland), desert (low rainfall, hot or cold), temperate forest (seasonal, deciduous trees), taiga/boreal forest (cold, conifers), tundra (very cold, permafrost, treeless), grassland/prairie. Aquatic biomes: freshwater (lakes, rivers, wetlands) and marine (ocean, coral reef, estuary).",keywords:["biome","tropical rainforest","savanna","desert","temperate forest","taiga","tundra","grassland","aquatic biome"]},{level:"MS",term:"Adaptations",def:"Traits that increase an organism's ability to survive and reproduce in its environment. Structural adaptations: physical features (thick fur for cold climates, webbed feet for swimming, camouflage coloring). Behavioral adaptations: actions that aid survival (migration, hibernation, nocturnal behavior). Physiological adaptations: internal processes (producing antifreeze proteins, efficient water retention in desert animals). Adaptations evolve through natural selection over many generations.",keywords:["adaptation","structural adaptation","behavioral adaptation","physiological adaptation","camouflage","mimicry","natural selection","survival"]},{level:"MS",term:"Symbiosis",def:"Long-term interactions between two different species living in close association. Mutualism: both species benefit (clownfish and sea anemone; bees and flowers; nitrogen-fixing bacteria in legume roots). Commensalism: one species benefits, the other is unaffected (barnacles on whales; birds eating insects stirred up by cattle). Parasitism: one species (parasite) benefits at the expense of the other (host) (tapeworms, fleas, mistletoe). Endoparasites live inside the host; ectoparasites live outside.",keywords:["symbiosis","mutualism","commensalism","parasitism","parasite","host","endoparasite","ectoparasite","coevolution"]},{level:"MS",term:"Bacteria",def:"Single-celled prokaryotes (no membrane-bound nucleus). Shapes: cocci (spherical), bacilli (rod-shaped), spirilla (spiral). Reproduce by binary fission (asexual). Some cause disease (pathogens): Streptococcus (strep throat), Salmonella (food poisoning), Mycobacterium tuberculosis. Most are beneficial: decomposers, nitrogen fixers, used to make yogurt and cheese. Antibiotics target bacterial cell walls, ribosomes, or DNA replication. Bacteria can develop antibiotic resistance.",keywords:["bacteria","prokaryote","binary fission","cocci","bacilli","pathogen","antibiotic","antibiotic resistance","nitrogen fixing"]},{level:"MS",term:"Viruses (Basic)",def:"Non-living particles consisting of genetic material (DNA or RNA) surrounded by a protein coat (capsid). Not cells — cannot reproduce on their own; must infect a host cell. Lytic cycle: virus injects DNA into host, hijacks cell machinery to make new viruses, lyses (bursts) cell to release them. Examples: influenza (RNA virus), HIV (retrovirus, uses reverse transcriptase), chickenpox, COVID-19. Vaccines stimulate immune system to recognize viral proteins without causing disease.",keywords:["virus","capsid","lytic cycle","dna virus","rna virus","retrovirus","vaccine","host cell","influenza","hiv"]},{level:"MS",term:"Fungi (Basic)",def:"Eukaryotic organisms with cell walls made of chitin. Heterotrophs: absorb nutrients from decomposing organic matter (decomposers). Not plants — they do not photosynthesize. Body made of thread-like hyphae forming a mycelium. Reproduce by spores. Types: mushrooms (Basidiomycota), molds (Zygomycota, Ascomycota), yeasts (unicellular Ascomycota). Useful fungi: yeast (bread, beer), Penicillium (penicillin antibiotic). Harmful: athlete's foot, ringworm (actually fungi, not worms).",keywords:["fungi","chitin","hyphae","mycelium","decomposer","spore","yeast","mushroom","mold","penicillin"]},{level:"MS",term:"Protists (Basic)",def:"Mostly unicellular eukaryotes that don't fit neatly into other kingdoms. Three types: animal-like (protozoa), plant-like (algae), and fungus-like (slime molds). Amoeba: moves with pseudopods, engulfs food. Paramecium: moves with cilia. Euglena: has chloroplasts (photosynthesize) AND a flagellum (can move). Algae: produce much of Earth's oxygen via photosynthesis. Plasmodium: protist that causes malaria, transmitted by Anopheles mosquito.",keywords:["protist","protozoa","algae","amoeba","paramecium","euglena","pseudopod","cilia","flagella","plasmodium","malaria"]},{level:"MS",term:"Plant Kingdom",def:"Multicellular, photosynthetic eukaryotes with cell walls of cellulose. Major groups: non-vascular plants (bryophytes: mosses, liverworts — lack xylem/phloem, need moisture to reproduce), seedless vascular plants (ferns — have xylem/phloem but reproduce by spores), gymnosperms (conifers, produce naked seeds in cones), angiosperms (flowering plants, produce seeds in fruits — most diverse and widespread). Xylem transports water up; phloem transports sugars.",keywords:["plant kingdom","bryophyte","moss","fern","gymnosperm","angiosperm","xylem","phloem","vascular","non-vascular","seed"]},{level:"MS",term:"Animal Kingdom",def:"Multicellular, heterotrophic eukaryotes without cell walls. Two major groups: invertebrates (no backbone; ~97% of animal species) and vertebrates (have a backbone/vertebral column; includes fish, amphibians, reptiles, birds, mammals). Key features: movement, nervous system for sensing/responding, reproduce sexually. Major invertebrate phyla: Porifera (sponges), Cnidaria (jellyfish), Platyhelminthes (flatworms), Annelida (earthworms), Mollusca (snails, clams, squid), Arthropoda, Echinodermata (sea stars).",keywords:["animal kingdom","invertebrate","vertebrate","backbone","porifera","cnidaria","arthropoda","mollusca","echinodermata","annelida"]},{level:"MS",term:"Fish & Amphibians",def:"Fish: aquatic vertebrates; breathe through gills; ectothermic. Cartilaginous fish (Chondrichthyes): sharks, rays — skeleton of cartilage, no swim bladder. Bony fish (Osteichthyes): most fish — swim bladder for buoyancy, scales, lateral line. Amphibians: first terrestrial vertebrates; ectothermic; moist, glandular skin (no scales); breathe through gills (larvae) and lungs/skin (adults); must return to water to reproduce (external fertilization, jelly-coated eggs). Examples: frogs, salamanders, caecilians.",keywords:["fish","amphibian","gill","ectotherm","cartilaginous fish","bony fish","swim bladder","frog","salamander","external fertilization"]},{level:"MS",term:"Reptiles & Birds",def:"Reptiles: ectothermic; dry, scaly skin (waterproof); breathe with lungs; internal fertilization; amniotic eggs (leathery shell; can be laid on land). Examples: snakes, lizards, turtles, crocodilians. Birds (Aves): endothermic (warm-blooded); feathers; hollow bones; wings; four-chambered heart; hard-shelled amniotic eggs; descended from theropod dinosaurs. Adaptations for flight: keeled sternum (muscle attachment), fused clavicles (wishbone), air sacs for efficient respiration.",keywords:["reptile","bird","ectotherm","endotherm","amniotic egg","scale","feather","hollow bone","warm blooded","cold blooded"]},{level:"MS",term:"Mammals",def:"Endothermic vertebrates with hair or fur; females produce milk from mammary glands to feed young; most have a diaphragm for breathing; four-chambered heart. Three groups: monotremes (egg-laying; platypus, echidna), marsupials (young born early, develop in pouch; kangaroo, opossum), eutherians/placental mammals (young develop in uterus via placenta; most mammals). Adaptations: homeothermy allows activity in cold, specialized teeth (incisors, canines, premolars, molars).",keywords:["mammal","mammary gland","endotherm","monotreme","marsupial","placental","eutherian","hair","fur","four chambered heart"]},{level:"MS",term:"Arthropods",def:"Largest animal phylum (~1 million+ species). Characteristics: exoskeleton (chitin), jointed appendages, segmented body, open circulatory system. Must molt (ecdysis) to grow. Classes: Insecta (6 legs, 3 body segments, wings; bees, beetles, butterflies), Arachnida (8 legs, 2 body segments; spiders, scorpions, ticks), Crustacea (2 pairs antennae; crabs, lobsters, shrimp), Myriapoda (many legs; centipedes, millipedes). Insects are the most diverse group of animals on Earth.",keywords:["arthropod","exoskeleton","insect","arachnid","crustacean","chitin","molting","ecdysis","jointed","segmented"]},{level:"MS",term:"Human Circulatory System",def:"Closed double-loop system. Pulmonary circuit: right heart → lungs (gas exchange) → left heart. Systemic circuit: left heart → body → right heart. Heart: four chambers (right/left atria and ventricles); valves prevent backflow; sinoatrial (SA) node is the pacemaker. Arteries carry blood away from heart (oxygenated, except pulmonary); veins carry blood toward heart; capillaries are site of gas/nutrient exchange. Blood components: red blood cells (oxygen transport), white blood cells (immune), platelets (clotting), plasma.",keywords:["circulatory system","heart","artery","vein","capillary","pulmonary","systemic","red blood cell","plasma","sa node","pacemaker"]},{level:"MS",term:"Human Respiratory System",def:"Brings oxygen into the body and removes carbon dioxide. Air path: nose/mouth → trachea (windpipe) → bronchi → bronchioles → alveoli. Alveoli: tiny air sacs surrounded by capillaries; site of gas exchange (O₂ in, CO₂ out) by diffusion. Diaphragm: dome-shaped muscle below lungs; contracts to inhale (lung volume increases, pressure decreases). Breathing rate increases with exercise. Hemoglobin in red blood cells carries oxygen as oxyhemoglobin.",keywords:["respiratory system","trachea","bronchi","alveoli","diaphragm","gas exchange","oxygen","carbon dioxide","hemoglobin","lung"]},{level:"MS",term:"Human Digestive System",def:"Breaks food down mechanically and chemically for absorption. Path: mouth (chewing + amylase breaks starch) → esophagus (peristalsis) → stomach (pepsin + HCl breaks proteins; churning) → small intestine (most digestion and absorption; villi increase surface area; bile from liver, enzymes from pancreas) → large intestine (water reabsorption; bacteria produce vitamins) → rectum/anus. Liver: produces bile, detoxifies blood. Pancreas: produces digestive enzymes and bicarbonate.",keywords:["digestive system","stomach","small intestine","large intestine","villi","liver","pancreas","bile","amylase","pepsin","peristalsis"]},{level:"MS",term:"Human Skeletal System",def:"206 bones in adult human body. Functions: support, protection of organs, movement (with muscles), blood cell production (red bone marrow), mineral storage (calcium, phosphorus). Bone composition: compact bone (dense outer layer) and spongy bone (inner lattice). Types of joints: ball-and-socket (hip, shoulder — full rotation), hinge (knee, elbow — one plane), pivot (neck — rotation), gliding (wrist). Cartilage: flexible connective tissue at joint surfaces; no blood supply. Ligaments: bone to bone. Tendons: muscle to bone.",keywords:["skeletal system","bone","joint","cartilage","ligament","tendon","bone marrow","compact bone","spongy bone","hinge joint","ball socket"]},{level:"MS",term:"Human Nervous System",def:"CNS: brain + spinal cord; processes information. PNS: all nerves outside CNS; sensory (carries signals to CNS) and motor (carries signals from CNS to muscles/glands). Neurons: basic unit; dendrites receive signals, cell body integrates, axon transmits, synapse releases neurotransmitters. Reflex arc: stimulus → sensory neuron → interneuron (spinal cord) → motor neuron → response; bypasses brain for speed. Somatic: voluntary muscle control. Autonomic: involuntary (sympathetic = fight-or-flight; parasympathetic = rest-and-digest).",keywords:["nervous system","cns","pns","neuron","axon","dendrite","synapse","reflex arc","autonomic","sympathetic","parasympathetic"]},{level:"MS",term:"Human Immune System (Basic)",def:"First line of defense: physical barriers (skin, mucus, cilia in respiratory tract, stomach acid). Second line: nonspecific innate responses (phagocytes engulf pathogens, inflammation, fever — higher temperature slows bacterial growth, interferons signal neighboring cells). Third line: specific adaptive immunity. B cells produce antibodies (proteins that bind specific antigens). T cells: helper T cells coordinate response; cytotoxic T cells destroy infected cells. Memory cells enable faster secondary immune response (basis of vaccination).",keywords:["immune system","pathogen","antibody","antigen","b cell","t cell","phagocyte","inflammation","innate immunity","adaptive immunity","vaccination"]},{level:"MS",term:"Biodiversity & Extinction",def:"Biodiversity: variety of life — genetic diversity (variation within species), species diversity (number of species), ecosystem diversity (variety of habitats). Biodiversity hotspots: regions with exceptionally high species richness and endemism. Extinction: permanent disappearance of a species; background extinction rate vs. mass extinctions (five major events; sixth ongoing due to human activities). Threatened species: vulnerable, endangered, critically endangered. IUCN Red List classifies species by extinction risk. Habitat loss is the primary cause.",keywords:["biodiversity","extinction","endangered species","habitat loss","iucn","species richness","endemic","biodiversity hotspot","mass extinction"]},{level:"MS",term:"Population Dynamics",def:"Population size changes due to: births, deaths, immigration, emigration. Exponential growth: occurs when resources are unlimited (J-shaped curve). Logistic growth: population growth slows as it approaches carrying capacity K (S-shaped curve). Limiting factors: food, space, disease, predation (density-dependent) or floods, fires (density-independent). Predator-prey cycles: as prey increases, predator population rises; predator overhunts prey → prey drops → predator drops (e.g., lynx-snowshoe hare). Invasive species disrupt native population dynamics.",keywords:["population growth","exponential growth","logistic growth","carrying capacity","limiting factor","predator prey cycle","invasive species","birth rate","death rate"]},{level:"MS",term:"Transpiration & Plant Transport",def:"Transpiration: evaporation of water from plant leaves through stomata; creates a tension (negative pressure) that pulls water up from roots through xylem (cohesion-tension theory). Stomata: pores on leaf surface controlled by guard cells; open in light (CO₂ enters, O₂ exits, water exits); close in drought. Xylem transports water and minerals upward (passive). Phloem transports sugars (sucrose) bidirectionally via pressure-flow (source to sink). Root hairs increase surface area for water/mineral absorption.",keywords:["transpiration","stomata","guard cell","xylem","phloem","cohesion tension","root hair","water transport plant","sugar transport"]},{level:"MS",term:"Enzymes (Basic)",def:"Biological catalysts (usually proteins) that speed up chemical reactions without being consumed. Enzymes are specific: each enzyme has an active site that fits only certain substrates (lock-and-key model; induced fit model). Temperature: enzyme activity increases with temperature until the optimal temperature; above this, the enzyme denatures (shape changes, active site lost). pH: each enzyme has an optimal pH (stomach enzymes work best at ~pH 2; intestinal enzymes at ~pH 7–8). Inhibitors can slow enzyme activity.",keywords:["enzyme","catalyst","active site","substrate","lock and key","denaturation","optimal temperature","ph enzyme","inhibitor","specificity"]},{level:"MS",term:"Carbon & Nitrogen Cycles",def:"Carbon cycle: CO₂ removed from air by photosynthesis → stored in biomass → released by respiration, decomposition, combustion. Fossil fuel burning increases atmospheric CO₂. Nitrogen cycle: N₂ in atmosphere → fixed to ammonia by bacteria (Rhizobium in legume roots) → converted to nitrates by nitrification → absorbed by plants → returned to atmosphere by denitrification. Both cycles are essential for life; human activities (fertilizers, combustion) disrupt natural balances.",keywords:["carbon cycle","nitrogen cycle","nitrogen fixation","nitrification","denitrification","photosynthesis carbon","decomposition","fossil fuel carbon","rhizobium"]},{level:"MS",term:"Blood & Circulatory Fluids",def:"Blood components: red blood cells (RBCs/erythrocytes — carry O₂ via hemoglobin; no nucleus in mammals), white blood cells (WBCs/leukocytes — immune defense), platelets (thrombocytes — blood clotting), plasma (55% of blood; water, proteins, hormones, nutrients, waste). Blood types: ABO system (A, B, AB, O) and Rh factor (+/−). Universal donor: O−. Universal recipient: AB+. Clotting cascade: platelets + fibrin form clot; vitamin K is required. Lymph: fluid that returns from tissues to blood via lymphatic system.",keywords:["blood","red blood cell","white blood cell","platelet","plasma","hemoglobin","blood type","abo","clotting","lymph","erythrocyte"]},{level:"MS",term:"Environmental Pollution",def:"Water pollution: sewage, fertilizer runoff (eutrophication → algal blooms → oxygen depletion → dead zones), heavy metals, oil spills. Air pollution: particulate matter, SO₂, NOₓ, CO, ozone (ground level — bad), VOCs. Soil pollution: pesticides, heavy metals, industrial waste. Bioaccumulation: toxins increase in concentration in organism's tissue. Biomagnification: toxin concentration increases up the food chain (e.g., DDT in birds → thin eggshells). Point source pollution: specific location. Non-point source: runoff from large areas.",keywords:["pollution","water pollution","eutrophication","bioaccumulation","biomagnification","ddt","air pollution","runoff","algal bloom","dead zone"]},{level:"MS",term:"Biotic & Abiotic Factors",def:"Biotic factors: living components of an ecosystem (producers, consumers, decomposers, competitors, predators, pathogens). Abiotic factors: non-living physical and chemical components (temperature, light, water/precipitation, soil type, pH, salinity, dissolved oxygen, wind, humidity). Biotic and abiotic factors interact to determine what organisms can survive in an ecosystem. Tolerance range: range of abiotic conditions an organism can survive; optimal range for best growth; limits of tolerance define distribution.",keywords:["biotic","abiotic","ecosystem","tolerance range","limiting factor","temperature","light","water","soil","salinity","habitat"]},{level:"MS",term:"Decomposition & Nutrient Cycling",def:"Decomposers (bacteria and fungi) break down dead organic matter into simpler inorganic molecules, returning nutrients to the soil. Without decomposers, nutrients would remain locked in dead organisms and ecosystems would collapse. Detritivores (earthworms, millipedes, pill bugs) shred dead material, increasing surface area for decomposers. Decomposition rate depends on temperature, moisture, and oxygen availability (fastest in warm, moist, aerobic conditions). Composting uses decomposers to recycle organic waste.",keywords:["decomposer","decomposition","detritivore","nutrient cycling","bacteria fungi decompose","compost","organic matter","inorganic nutrient","earthworm"]},{level:"MS",term:"Phototropism & Plant Responses",def:"Plants respond to environmental stimuli. Phototropism: growth toward light (positive) or away from light (negative); caused by unequal distribution of auxin — more auxin on shaded side → faster growth → bending toward light. Gravitropism: roots grow toward gravity (positive); shoots grow away (negative). Thigmotropism: growth in response to touch (climbing plants, tendrils). Photoperiodism: response to day length — short-day plants flower when nights are long; long-day plants flower when nights are short.",keywords:["phototropism","gravitropism","thigmotropism","photoperiodism","auxin","tropism","plant response","stimulus","growth toward light"]}]},Chemistry:{color:"var(--cyan)",icon:"⚗️",items:[{term:"Atomic Structure",def:"Protons (+) and neutrons (neutral) in nucleus; electrons (−) in orbitals. Atomic number = protons; mass number = protons + neutrons. Isotopes: same element, different neutron count. Ions: gained electrons = anion (−); lost electrons = cation (+). Electron configuration follows Aufbau principle.",keywords:["proton","neutron","electron","isotope","atomic number","atomic mass","orbital","valence"]},{term:"Periodic Trends",def:"Atomic radius decreases across a period (more protons pull electrons in) and increases down a group (more electron shells). Electronegativity and ionization energy increase across a period, decrease down a group. Electron affinity follows similar trends. Noble gases have the highest ionization energies per period.",keywords:["electronegativity","ionization energy","atomic radius","periodic trend","electron affinity","noble gas"]},{term:"Chemical Bonding",def:"Ionic: metal + nonmetal, electron transfer, forms crystal lattice. Covalent: nonmetal + nonmetal, electron sharing. Polar covalent: unequal sharing. Metallic: delocalized electron sea. Bond strength order (single < double < triple). Octet rule: atoms gain/lose/share electrons to achieve 8 valence electrons.",keywords:["ionic bond","covalent bond","polar","metallic bond","octet rule","valence electron"]},{term:"Gas Laws",def:"Boyle's Law: P₁V₁ = P₂V₂ (constant T). Charles' Law: V₁/T₁ = V₂/T₂ (constant P). Gay-Lussac's: P₁/T₁ = P₂/T₂ (constant V). Ideal Gas Law: PV = nRT (R = 8.314 J/mol·K). Avogadro's: at same T and P, equal volumes contain equal numbers of moles.",keywords:["boyle","charles","ideal gas","avogadro","gas law","pv=nrt","gay-lussac"]},{term:"Acids & Bases",def:"Arrhenius: acid produces H⁺, base produces OH⁻. Brønsted-Lowry: acid donates proton, base accepts proton. Lewis: acid accepts electron pair. pH = −log[H⁺]; strong acids fully dissociate (HCl, HNO₃, H₂SO₄, HBr, HI, HClO₄). Conjugate acid-base pairs differ by one H⁺.",keywords:["acid","base","ph","proton","hydroxide","neutralization","bronsted","arrhenius","titration"]},{term:"Thermochemistry",def:"Enthalpy (ΔH): heat at constant pressure; exothermic ΔH < 0, endothermic ΔH > 0. Entropy (ΔS): disorder. Gibbs free energy: ΔG = ΔH − TΔS; spontaneous if ΔG < 0. Hess's Law: enthalpy is path-independent (state function). Standard enthalpy of formation: ΔHf° for 1 mol from elements in standard state.",keywords:["enthalpy","entropy","gibbs","exothermic","endothermic","hess","spontaneous","calorimetry"]},{term:"Reaction Kinetics",def:"Rate depends on concentration, temperature, surface area, and catalysts. Activation energy (Eₐ): minimum energy for reaction. Arrhenius equation: k = Ae^(−Eₐ/RT). Rate law: rate = k[A]^m[B]^n (determined experimentally). Half-life (t½): time for half of reactant to be consumed; constant for first-order reactions.",keywords:["activation energy","catalyst","reaction rate","kinetics","rate law","half-life","arrhenius equation"]},{term:"Electrochemistry",def:"OIL RIG: Oxidation Is Loss, Reduction Is Gain of electrons. Galvanic (voltaic) cell: spontaneous redox; anode (oxidation, −) and cathode (reduction, +). Electrolytic cell: non-spontaneous, driven by external current. EMF (cell potential) measured in volts. Nernst equation relates EMF to concentration.",keywords:["oxidation","reduction","redox","anode","cathode","galvanic","electrolysis","oxidation state"]},{term:"Chemical Equilibrium",def:"Dynamic state where forward = reverse reaction rate. Le Chatelier's Principle: system shifts to oppose any stress. Kc = [products]/[reactants] (excludes solids and pure liquids). Kp relates to partial pressures of gases. Q vs K: Q < K → shifts right; Q > K → shifts left.",keywords:["equilibrium","le chatelier","equilibrium constant","kc","kp","reversible reaction","q vs k"]},{term:"Solutions & Concentration",def:"Molarity (M) = moles solute / liters solution. Molality (m) = moles / kg solvent. Dilution: M₁V₁ = M₂V₂. Solubility rules: all nitrates soluble; most chlorides soluble (except Ag⁺, Pb²⁺, Hg₂²⁺). Like dissolves like: polar solvents dissolve polar/ionic solutes; nonpolar solvents dissolve nonpolar solutes.",keywords:["molarity","molality","solubility","dilution","concentration","dissolve"]},{term:"Stoichiometry",def:"Mole concept: 1 mol = 6.022×10²³ particles (Avogadro's number). Molar mass: sum of atomic masses in g/mol. Balanced equations give mole ratios. Limiting reagent: reactant completely consumed first; determines maximum product yield. Percent yield = (actual yield / theoretical yield) × 100%.",keywords:["stoichiometry","mole","avogadro","limiting reagent","percent yield","molar mass","theoretical yield"]},{term:"Nuclear Chemistry",def:"Radioactive decay types: alpha (α, ²⁴He nucleus emitted, penetration lowest), beta-minus (β⁻, neutron → proton + electron), beta-plus (positron emission), gamma (γ, high-energy photon, no mass/charge change). Half-life: constant for each isotope. Fission splits heavy nuclei; fusion combines light nuclei.",keywords:["radioactive","alpha decay","beta decay","gamma radiation","half-life","nuclear decay","isotope decay"]},{term:"Organic Chemistry",def:"Hydrocarbons: alkanes (single bonds, CₙH₂ₙ₊₂), alkenes (double bond, CₙH₂ₙ), alkynes (triple bond, CₙH₂ₙ₋₂), benzene (aromatic). Functional groups: hydroxyl (−OH, alcohols), carbonyl (C=O), carboxyl (−COOH, acids), amino (−NH₂), ester (−COO−). IUPAC naming by longest carbon chain.",keywords:["organic","alkane","alkene","alkyne","functional group","hydrocarbon","benzene","carboxyl","hydroxyl"]},{term:"Intermolecular Forces",def:"London dispersion forces (van der Waals): weakest; in all molecules; increase with molecular mass and surface area. Dipole-dipole: between polar molecules. Hydrogen bonds: strongest intermolecular; N–H, O–H, or F–H with electronegative atom on adjacent molecule. IMF strength determines boiling point and vapor pressure.",keywords:["intermolecular","van der waals","london dispersion","dipole-dipole","hydrogen bond","boiling point","polar molecule"]},{term:"Molecular Geometry (VSEPR)",def:"VSEPR theory: electron pairs repel to maximize separation. Shapes by electron pairs: 2 = linear, 3 = trigonal planar, 4 = tetrahedral, 5 = trigonal bipyramidal, 6 = octahedral. Lone pairs compress bond angles. Water (2 lone pairs): bent (~104.5°). NH₃ (1 lone pair): trigonal pyramidal (~107°).",keywords:["vsepr","molecular geometry","bond angle","lone pair","tetrahedral","trigonal","bent","linear geometry"]},{term:"Quantum Numbers",def:"Four quantum numbers describe each electron: n (principal, energy level, 1,2,3…), l (angular momentum, subshell: 0=s, 1=p, 2=d, 3=f), mₗ (magnetic, orbital orientation), mₛ (spin, +½ or −½). Pauli exclusion: no two electrons can share all four quantum numbers. Aufbau and Hund's rules fill orbitals.",keywords:["quantum number","principal quantum","subshell","orbital","aufbau","pauli exclusion","hund","electron configuration"]},{term:"Types of Chemical Reactions",def:"Synthesis (combination): A + B → AB. Decomposition: AB → A + B. Single displacement: A + BC → AC + B. Double displacement (metathesis): AB + CD → AD + CB. Combustion: fuel + O₂ → CO₂ + H₂O. Acid-base neutralization: acid + base → salt + water.",keywords:["synthesis reaction","decomposition","single displacement","double displacement","combustion reaction","neutralization reaction"]},{term:"Colligative Properties",def:"Properties that depend only on the number of solute particles, not their identity. Adding a non-volatile solute: raises boiling point (ΔTb = Kb·m·i), lowers freezing point (ΔTf = Kf·m·i), lowers vapor pressure (Raoult's Law), and increases osmotic pressure (π = MRT·i). i = van 't Hoff factor.",keywords:["colligative","boiling point elevation","freezing point depression","osmotic pressure","raoult","van hoff"]},{term:"Phase Diagrams",def:"Graph of pressure vs temperature showing solid, liquid, and gas regions. Triple point: all three phases coexist. Critical point: above this T and P, liquid and gas are indistinguishable (supercritical fluid). Sublimation: solid → gas directly (CO₂ at 1 atm). Normal boiling/melting points are at 1 atm.",keywords:["phase diagram","triple point","critical point","sublimation","melting point","boiling point","supercritical"]},{term:"Buffers",def:"Resist changes in pH when small amounts of acid or base are added. Composed of a weak acid and its conjugate base (or weak base and its conjugate acid). Henderson-Hasselbalch equation: pH = pKa + log([A⁻]/[HA]). Most effective buffering at pH = pKa ± 1. Blood is buffered by H₂CO₃/HCO₃⁻ at pH ≈ 7.4.",keywords:["buffer","henderson-hasselbalch","pka","conjugate base","weak acid","resist ph"]},{term:"Oxidation States",def:"Assign oxidation numbers: free elements = 0; monatomic ions = charge; O usually −2 (except peroxides: −1); H usually +1 (except metal hydrides: −1); sum = charge of species. In redox reactions, the oxidizing agent is reduced (gains electrons); the reducing agent is oxidized (loses electrons).",keywords:["oxidation state","oxidation number","oxidizing agent","reducing agent","redox","assign oxidation"]},{term:"Coordination Compounds",def:"Metal ion (Lewis acid) surrounded by ligands (Lewis bases donating electron pairs). Coordination number: number of ligand bonds to metal. Ligand types: monodentate (one bond, e.g., NH₃, Cl⁻), bidentate (two bonds, e.g., en), polydentate (chelate). Complex ion charge = metal oxidation state + ligand charges.",keywords:["coordination","ligand","complex ion","chelate","coordination number","bidentate","lewis acid base"]},{term:"Isomers",def:"Structural isomers: same molecular formula, different connectivity (e.g., butane vs isobutane). Geometric (cis-trans) isomers: same connectivity, different spatial arrangement around a double bond or ring. Optical isomers (enantiomers): non-superimposable mirror images; differ at chiral carbon; rotate plane-polarized light oppositely.",keywords:["isomer","structural isomer","cis-trans","geometric isomer","enantiomer","optical isomer","chiral","stereoisomer"]},{term:"Spectroscopy",def:"Emission spectra: atoms emit characteristic photons when electrons fall to lower energy levels (Bohr model). Absorption spectra: atoms absorb specific wavelengths, leaving dark lines. Beer-Lambert Law: A = εlc (absorbance = molar absorptivity × path length × concentration). NMR, IR, and mass spectrometry identify organic compounds.",keywords:["spectroscopy","emission spectrum","absorption spectrum","beer-lambert","bohr","wavelength absorbed"]},{term:"Polymer Chemistry",def:"Polymers: large molecules made of repeating monomer units. Addition polymers (e.g., polyethylene): monomers with double bonds add without losing atoms. Condensation polymers (e.g., nylon, polyester): monomers join by losing small molecules (H₂O). Proteins are natural polymers (amino acid monomers joined by peptide bonds).",keywords:["polymer","monomer","addition polymer","condensation polymer","polyethylene","nylon","peptide bond"]},{term:"Reaction Mechanisms",def:"Elementary steps that show how reactants become products. Rate-determining step: slowest step; controls overall reaction rate. Intermediates: formed in one step, consumed in a later step. Transition state (activated complex): highest-energy point in an elementary step. SN1 and SN2 are common substitution mechanisms in organic chemistry.",keywords:["mechanism","rate-determining step","intermediate","transition state","elementary step","sn1","sn2"]},{term:"Titration & Indicators",def:"Titration: technique to determine unknown concentration by reacting with a standard solution. Equivalence point: moles of acid = moles of base. Endpoint: indicator changes color. Common indicators: phenolphthalein (colorless → pink at pH ~8.2–10), methyl orange (red → yellow at pH ~3.1–4.4). Back titration: excess reagent is titrated to find original amount. Neutralization: strong acid + strong base → salt + water; pH at equivalence = 7.",keywords:["titration","equivalence point","endpoint","indicator","phenolphthalein","standard solution","neutralization titration"]},{term:"Solubility Product (Ksp)",def:"Equilibrium constant for dissolution of sparingly soluble ionic compound. For AgCl: AgCl(s) ⇌ Ag⁺ + Cl⁻; Ksp = [Ag⁺][Cl⁻]. Common ion effect: adding a shared ion reduces solubility (Le Chatelier). Precipitation occurs when Q > Ksp. Selective precipitation separates ions by exploiting different Ksp values. Molar solubility s relates to Ksp (e.g., for AB type: Ksp = s²).",keywords:["solubility product","ksp","common ion effect","precipitation","molar solubility","sparingly soluble","dissolution equilibrium"]},{term:"Electron Configuration",def:"Electrons fill orbitals by Aufbau principle (lowest energy first), Hund's rule (one electron per orbital before pairing), and Pauli exclusion (no two electrons with same four quantum numbers). Orbital filling order: 1s 2s 2p 3s 3p 4s 3d 4p 5s 4d... Exceptions: Cr ([Ar]3d⁵4s¹) and Cu ([Ar]3d¹⁰4s¹) for half-filled/full-d stability. Valence electrons: outermost shell electrons; determine chemical behavior.",keywords:["electron configuration","aufbau","hund's rule","pauli exclusion","valence electron","orbital filling","subshell","noble gas configuration"]},{term:"Lewis Structures",def:"Dot diagrams showing valence electrons. Steps: count total valence electrons, place least electronegative atom in center, form single bonds, complete octets of outer atoms, place remaining electrons on central atom, convert lone pairs to double/triple bonds if needed. Formal charge = (valence e⁻) − (lone pair e⁻) − ½(bonding e⁻). Resonance structures: multiple valid Lewis structures; actual molecule is a hybrid (e.g., benzene, O₃, NO₃⁻).",keywords:["lewis structure","formal charge","resonance","lone pair","double bond","triple bond","octet","valence electrons"]},{term:"Acid-Base Equilibria",def:"Weak acid equilibrium: HA ⇌ H⁺ + A⁻; Ka = [H⁺][A⁻]/[HA]. Weak base: B + H₂O ⇌ BH⁺ + OH⁻; Kb. Relationship: Ka × Kb = Kw = 10⁻¹⁴. pKa = −log(Ka); lower pKa = stronger acid. For weak acid solutions: [H⁺] ≈ √(Ka × C). Buffer: pH = pKa + log([A⁻]/[HA]) (Henderson-Hasselbalch). Amphoteric species (like water, amino acids) can act as both acid and base.",keywords:["ka","kb","weak acid","weak base","pka","acid dissociation","kw","amphoteric","henderson-hasselbalch"]},{term:"Hybridization",def:"Mixing of atomic orbitals to form new hybrid orbitals with equivalent energy. sp: linear geometry (180°); two sp orbitals + two unhybridized p (e.g., BeCl₂, alkynes). sp²: trigonal planar (120°); three sp² + one p (e.g., BF₃, alkenes, benzene). sp³: tetrahedral (109.5°); four sp³ (e.g., CH₄, NH₃, H₂O). sp³d: trigonal bipyramidal. sp³d²: octahedral. Lone pairs occupy hybrid orbitals and compress bond angles.",keywords:["hybridization","sp","sp2","sp3","hybrid orbital","sigma bond","pi bond","geometry hybridization","tetrahedral hybridization"]},{term:"Redox Balancing",def:"Half-reaction method: split into oxidation and reduction half-reactions; balance atoms (add H₂O for O, H⁺ for H in acidic; OH⁻ and H₂O in basic); balance charge by adding electrons; multiply half-reactions so electrons cancel; add half-reactions together. Oxidation number method: identify changes, multiply to equalize electron gain/loss, balance remaining atoms. Always confirm atoms and charge balance.",keywords:["redox balancing","half-reaction","oxidation number","electron transfer","acidic solution","basic solution","balance redox"]},{term:"Thermodynamic Spontaneity",def:"ΔG = ΔH − TΔS (Gibbs free energy). Spontaneous if ΔG < 0. Four cases: ΔH < 0 and ΔS > 0 → always spontaneous; ΔH > 0 and ΔS < 0 → never spontaneous; ΔH < 0 and ΔS < 0 → spontaneous at low T; ΔH > 0 and ΔS > 0 → spontaneous at high T. Standard ΔG° = −RT ln K; relates equilibrium constant to thermodynamics. ΔG° < 0 means K > 1 (products favored).",keywords:["gibbs free energy","spontaneous","delta g","delta h","delta s","thermodynamic","equilibrium constant","enthalpy entropy"]},{term:"Colloidal Systems",def:"Colloids: mixtures with particles 1–1000 nm dispersed in a medium (between solution and suspension). Types: aerosol (liquid/solid in gas — fog, smoke), foam (gas in liquid), emulsion (liquid in liquid — milk, mayonnaise), sol (solid in liquid), gel (liquid in solid). Tyndall effect: colloids scatter light (distinguishes from true solutions). Coagulation: colloid particles aggregate and settle. Surfactants stabilize emulsions.",keywords:["colloid","tyndall effect","emulsion","aerosol","suspension","sol","gel","foam","surfactant","colloidal dispersion"]},{term:"Naming Inorganic Compounds",def:"Binary ionic: cation name first, then anion with -ide suffix (NaCl = sodium chloride). Transition metals: use Roman numerals for charge (FeCl₃ = iron(III) chloride). Polyatomic ions: memorize common ones (SO₄²⁻ = sulfate, NO₃⁻ = nitrate, PO₄³⁻ = phosphate, CO₃²⁻ = carbonate, NH₄⁺ = ammonium). Binary covalent: use Greek prefixes (mono-, di-, tri-…); less electronegative element named first (N₂O₄ = dinitrogen tetroxide). Acids: HCl = hydrochloric; H₂SO₄ = sulfuric.",keywords:["naming compounds","ionic compound","covalent naming","polyatomic ion","roman numeral","binary compound","acid naming","nomenclature"]},{term:"Amino Acids & Proteins (Biochem)",def:"Twenty standard amino acids; structure: central α-carbon bonded to amino group (−NH₂), carboxyl group (−COOH), H, and variable R-group (side chain). Classified by R-group: nonpolar, polar uncharged, acidic (Asp, Glu), basic (Lys, Arg, His). Peptide bond formation: condensation reaction between −COOH and −NH₂; water is released. Isoelectric point (pI): pH at which net charge = 0. Essential amino acids must be obtained from diet.",keywords:["amino acid","peptide bond","r-group","alpha carbon","isoelectric point","essential amino acid","condensation","polypeptide"]},{term:"Enzyme Kinetics (Michaelis-Menten)",def:"Reaction rate v = Vmax[S] / (Km + [S]). Km (Michaelis constant): substrate concentration at half-maximal velocity; low Km = high enzyme affinity. Vmax: maximum rate when all enzyme active sites are saturated. Lineweaver-Burk (double reciprocal) plot linearizes the data. Competitive inhibition: raises apparent Km, same Vmax (overcome by high [S]). Noncompetitive inhibition: lowers Vmax, same Km (cannot be overcome).",keywords:["michaelis-menten","km","vmax","enzyme kinetics","competitive inhibition","noncompetitive inhibition","lineweaver-burk","substrate concentration"]},{term:"Nuclear Chemistry (Advanced)",def:"Binding energy = mass defect × c². Iron-56 has the highest binding energy per nucleon — fusing lighter nuclei or fissioning heavier nuclei toward iron releases energy. Radioactive decay law: N = N₀e^(−λt); λ = ln2/t½. Activity A = λN (measured in Becquerels or Curies). Mass spectrometry separates ions by mass-to-charge ratio. Radiocarbon dating (C-14, t½ = 5730 yr) used for organic material up to ~50,000 years.",keywords:["binding energy","mass defect","radioactive decay law","activity","becquerel","mass spectrometry","carbon dating","decay constant lambda"]},{term:"Chromatography",def:"Technique separating mixtures based on differential migration through a stationary phase with a mobile phase. Paper chromatography: Rf = distance traveled by compound / distance traveled by solvent; separates pigments by polarity. Thin-layer chromatography (TLC): similar, uses silica on glass/plastic. Gas chromatography (GC): volatile compounds separated by boiling point and polarity. HPLC: high-pressure liquid chromatography for complex mixtures. Column chromatography: gravity-fed separation.",keywords:["chromatography","rf value","paper chromatography","tlc","gas chromatography","hplc","mobile phase","stationary phase","separation technique"]},{level:"MS",term:"Atoms & Elements",def:"Atoms are the smallest units of an element that retain its chemical properties. Atoms consist of a nucleus (protons and neutrons) surrounded by electrons. Atomic number = number of protons (identifies the element). Mass number = protons + neutrons. An element is a pure substance made of only one type of atom. There are 118 known elements on the periodic table.",keywords:["atom","element","proton","neutron","electron","atomic number","mass number","nucleus"]},{level:"MS",term:"States of Matter",def:"Solid: definite shape and volume; particles vibrate in place. Liquid: definite volume, no definite shape; particles slide past each other. Gas: no definite shape or volume; particles move freely and rapidly. Plasma: high-energy ionized gas (stars, lightning). Changes of state: melting (solid→liquid), freezing, evaporation, condensation, sublimation (solid→gas), deposition.",keywords:["solid","liquid","gas","plasma","state of matter","melting","evaporation","condensation","sublimation"]},{level:"MS",term:"Physical vs Chemical Changes",def:"Physical change: alters the form or appearance of matter but not its chemical composition (cutting, melting, dissolving). Chemical change: produces new substances with different properties (combustion, rusting, cooking). Evidence of chemical change: color change, gas production, precipitate formation, temperature change, light emission. Chemical changes are generally harder to reverse.",keywords:["physical change","chemical change","chemical reaction","combustion","rusting","reversible","properties"]},{level:"MS",term:"Elements, Compounds & Mixtures",def:"Element: pure substance made of one type of atom (oxygen, gold). Compound: pure substance formed when two or more elements chemically combine in fixed ratios (H₂O, NaCl); properties differ from its elements. Mixture: two or more substances combined physically; can be separated (salt water, air). Homogeneous mixture (solution): uniform composition; heterogeneous: non-uniform.",keywords:["element","compound","mixture","solution","homogeneous","heterogeneous","pure substance","separation"]},{level:"MS",term:"Acids & Bases (Basic)",def:"Acids taste sour, turn blue litmus red, and have pH below 7 (examples: vinegar, lemon juice, stomach acid). Bases taste bitter, feel slippery, turn red litmus blue, and have pH above 7 (examples: baking soda, soap, ammonia). Neutral substances have pH = 7 (pure water). Neutralization: acid + base → salt + water.",keywords:["acid","base","ph","litmus","neutral","neutralization","indicator","sour","bitter"]},{level:"MS",term:"Periodic Table",def:"Organizes 118 elements by atomic number. Periods (rows): elements across a row have the same number of electron shells. Groups/families (columns): elements share similar properties. Metals (left side): shiny, conduct heat/electricity. Nonmetals (right side): poor conductors. Metalloids (along the staircase): intermediate properties. Noble gases (Group 18): very unreactive.",keywords:["periodic table","period","group","metal","nonmetal","metalloid","noble gas","element symbol"]},{level:"MS",term:"Chemical Reactions & Equations",def:"Chemical reactions rearrange atoms to form new substances. Reactants (left side) → Products (right side). Law of Conservation of Mass: mass is conserved; atoms are neither created nor destroyed, so equations must be balanced. Coefficients show the ratio of molecules. Types: synthesis, decomposition, single replacement, double replacement, combustion.",keywords:["chemical reaction","reactant","product","balanced equation","conservation of mass","coefficient","synthesis","decomposition"]},{level:"MS",term:"Density",def:"Density = mass / volume (D = m/V). Units: g/cm³ or g/mL. Water density = 1 g/cm³. Objects denser than the liquid they are placed in sink; less dense objects float. Density is an intensive property — it does not change with sample size. Temperature affects density: most substances become less dense as they are heated (water is an exception near 4°C).",keywords:["density","mass","volume","float","sink","buoyancy","intensive property","d=m/v"]},{level:"MS",term:"Chemical Bonding (Basic)",def:"Atoms bond to achieve stable electron configurations (usually 8 valence electrons — the octet rule). Ionic bonds: metal transfers electrons to nonmetal; forms ions (charged atoms). The opposite charges attract. Covalent bonds: two nonmetals share electrons. Metallic bonds: metal atoms share a sea of electrons. Bond type determines the properties of the compound formed.",keywords:["ionic bond","covalent bond","valence electron","octet rule","ion","metal","nonmetal","chemical bond"]},{level:"MS",term:"Atomic Models",def:"Dalton (1803): atoms are indivisible solid spheres; different elements have different atoms. Thomson (1897): discovered electron; 'plum pudding' model — electrons embedded in positive sphere. Rutherford (1911): gold foil experiment — most of atom is empty space; dense positive nucleus. Bohr (1913): electrons orbit nucleus in fixed energy levels; electrons absorb/emit photons when changing levels. Modern quantum mechanical model: electrons exist in probability clouds (orbitals), not fixed paths.",keywords:["atomic model","dalton","thomson","rutherford","bohr model","gold foil experiment","electron cloud","nucleus discovery","plum pudding"]},{level:"MS",term:"Ion Formation",def:"Ions are atoms or groups of atoms with a net electrical charge. Cations: positive ions formed when an atom loses electrons (metals; e.g., Na → Na⁺). Anions: negative ions formed when an atom gains electrons (nonmetals; e.g., Cl → Cl⁻). Ionic compounds form when cations and anions attract each other. Common polyatomic ions: OH⁻ (hydroxide), SO₄²⁻ (sulfate), NO₃⁻ (nitrate), NH₄⁺ (ammonium), CO₃²⁻ (carbonate). Ions in solution conduct electricity (electrolytes).",keywords:["ion","cation","anion","electron gain","electron loss","ionic compound","polyatomic ion","electrolyte","charge"]},{level:"MS",term:"Chemical Formulas & Equations",def:"Chemical formula shows types and numbers of atoms in a compound (H₂O: 2 hydrogen + 1 oxygen). Subscripts show number of atoms; coefficients show number of molecules. Balancing equations: must have equal numbers of each atom on both sides (Law of Conservation of Mass). Steps: write unbalanced equation, count atoms, add coefficients to balance (never change subscripts). Diatomic elements: H₂, N₂, O₂, F₂, Cl₂, Br₂, I₂ — always appear as pairs in their elemental form.",keywords:["chemical formula","balanced equation","subscript","coefficient","conservation of mass","diatomic","balancing","reactant product"]},{level:"MS",term:"Solubility & Solutions",def:"Solution: homogeneous mixture of solute (substance being dissolved) and solvent (substance doing the dissolving). Solubility: maximum amount of solute that dissolves in a given amount of solvent at a specific temperature. 'Like dissolves like': polar solvents (water) dissolve polar and ionic solutes; nonpolar solvents dissolve nonpolar solutes. Temperature: increases solubility of most solids; decreases solubility of gases. Saturated: holds maximum solute; unsaturated: can dissolve more; supersaturated: holds more than maximum (unstable).",keywords:["solubility","solution","solute","solvent","saturated","unsaturated","supersaturated","like dissolves like","polar solvent"]},{level:"MS",term:"Oxidation & Reduction (Basic)",def:"Oxidation: loss of electrons (OIL — Oxidation Is Loss). Reduction: gain of electrons (RIG — Reduction Is Gain). Redox reactions involve simultaneous oxidation and reduction. Oxidizing agent: gains electrons and is reduced. Reducing agent: loses electrons and is oxidized. Examples: rusting (iron oxidized by oxygen), combustion (fuel oxidized), photosynthesis/respiration (electron transfers in cells). Electrochemical cells use redox reactions to produce electricity (batteries).",keywords:["oxidation","reduction","redox","oil rig","oxidizing agent","reducing agent","electron transfer","rusting","combustion","battery"]},{level:"MS",term:"Types of Chemical Reactions (Basic)",def:"Synthesis: two or more substances combine to form one product (A + B → AB; e.g., 2H₂ + O₂ → 2H₂O). Decomposition: one compound breaks down into simpler substances (AB → A + B; e.g., H₂O₂ → H₂O + O₂). Single replacement: one element replaces another in a compound (A + BC → AC + B). Double replacement: ions exchange between two compounds in solution. Combustion: substance reacts with oxygen, releasing heat and light; produces CO₂ and H₂O (complete combustion).",keywords:["synthesis","decomposition","single replacement","double replacement","combustion","chemical reaction type","reaction type"]},{level:"MS",term:"Separation Techniques",def:"Filtration: separates insoluble solid from liquid using filter paper (e.g., sand from water). Evaporation: removes liquid solvent, leaves solid solute (e.g., salt from saltwater). Distillation: separates liquids by boiling point differences; liquid boils, vapor rises, condenses in cooler tube. Chromatography: separates mixtures based on how far components travel through a medium with a solvent (different Rf values). Magnetism: separates magnetic materials (iron filings from sand). Centrifugation: dense particles settle faster under centrifugal force.",keywords:["filtration","evaporation","distillation","chromatography","centrifugation","separation","mixture separation","rf value basic"]},{level:"MS",term:"Properties of Metals & Nonmetals",def:"Metals (left and center of periodic table): shiny luster, good conductors of heat and electricity, malleable (can be hammered into sheets), ductile (drawn into wire), high melting points (except mercury), tend to lose electrons and form cations. Nonmetals (upper right): dull, poor conductors (except graphite), brittle in solid form, lower melting points, tend to gain electrons and form anions. Metalloids (boron, silicon, germanium, arsenic, antimony, tellurium): properties intermediate between metals and nonmetals; used as semiconductors.",keywords:["metal","nonmetal","metalloid","conductor","malleable","ductile","luster","semiconductor","cation","anion"]},{level:"MS",term:"Energy in Chemical Reactions",def:"Exothermic reactions: release energy (usually as heat) to surroundings; products have lower energy than reactants; ΔH < 0 (examples: combustion, rusting, hand warmers). Endothermic reactions: absorb energy from surroundings; products have higher energy than reactants; ΔH > 0 (examples: photosynthesis, cold packs, cooking an egg). Activation energy: minimum energy needed to start a reaction; catalysts lower activation energy. Bond breaking requires energy; bond forming releases energy.",keywords:["exothermic","endothermic","activation energy","heat of reaction","enthalpy","catalyst energy","bond energy","energy diagram"]},{level:"MS",term:"Carbon Chemistry (Basic)",def:"Carbon is the basis of all organic (living) chemistry. Carbon has 4 valence electrons → forms 4 covalent bonds → can bond with itself to form long chains, rings, and branched structures. Hydrocarbons: compounds containing only C and H. Methane (CH₄, natural gas), ethane (C₂H₆), propane (C₃H₈), butane (C₄H₁₀). Carbon dioxide (CO₂) and carbonate ions (CO₃²⁻) are inorganic carbon compounds. Organic compounds include fats, sugars, proteins, and DNA.",keywords:["carbon chemistry","organic","hydrocarbon","methane","propane","covalent carbon","carbon chain","organic compound"]},{level:"MS",term:"Water Chemistry",def:"Water (H₂O): polar molecule (slight negative charge near O, slight positive near H). Hydrogen bonds between water molecules give it unique properties: high specific heat capacity (resists temperature change), high surface tension (insects can walk on water), cohesion (water sticks to water) and adhesion (water sticks to other surfaces). Water expands when it freezes (ice less dense than liquid → ice floats → aquatic life can survive under ice). Universal solvent for polar and ionic compounds.",keywords:["water","polar molecule","hydrogen bond","specific heat water","surface tension","cohesion","adhesion","universal solvent","ice density"]},{level:"MS",term:"Reaction Rates (Basic)",def:"Rate of reaction: how quickly reactants are converted to products. Factors that increase reaction rate: higher temperature (particles have more kinetic energy, collide more often and with more energy), higher concentration (more particles per volume → more collisions), greater surface area (smaller particles expose more surface for collisions), addition of a catalyst (lowers activation energy without being consumed). Collision theory: for reaction to occur, particles must collide with sufficient energy and correct orientation.",keywords:["reaction rate","temperature effect","concentration effect","surface area","catalyst","collision theory","activation energy","kinetics basic"]},{level:"MS",term:"Radioactivity (Basic)",def:"Some atomic nuclei are unstable and emit particles or energy (radioactive decay). Alpha particles (α): 2 protons + 2 neutrons (helium nucleus); stopped by paper; least penetrating. Beta particles (β): fast-moving electron; stopped by thin metal. Gamma rays (γ): high-energy electromagnetic radiation; most penetrating; requires lead or thick concrete shielding. Half-life: time for half of radioactive atoms to decay. Carbon-14 dating: used to date organic materials (t½ = 5,730 years). Uses: medicine (PET scan), power generation, food irradiation.",keywords:["radioactivity","alpha particle","beta particle","gamma ray","half-life","radioactive decay","carbon-14","nuclear radiation","penetrating power"]},{level:"MS",term:"Isotopes",def:"Atoms of the same element with the same number of protons but different numbers of neutrons. They have the same atomic number but different mass numbers. Examples: carbon-12 (6p, 6n) and carbon-14 (6p, 8n); hydrogen (1p, 0n), deuterium (1p, 1n), tritium (1p, 2n). Most elements exist as a mixture of isotopes; atomic mass on the periodic table is a weighted average. Radioactive isotopes (radioisotopes) have unstable nuclei. Stable isotopes are used in medical imaging and archaeological dating.",keywords:["isotope","proton","neutron","mass number","atomic mass","carbon-12","carbon-14","radioactive isotope","deuterium","weighted average mass"]},{level:"MS",term:"Gases (Basic Properties)",def:"Gas particles move rapidly and randomly in all directions; fill any container; spread to occupy available volume (diffusion). Gas pressure: force per unit area exerted by gas particles hitting container walls; measured in Pascals, atm, or mmHg (1 atm = 101,325 Pa = 760 mmHg). Boyle's Law: pressure and volume are inversely proportional at constant temperature (P₁V₁ = P₂V₂). Charles' Law: volume and temperature (Kelvin) are directly proportional at constant pressure (V₁/T₁ = V₂/T₂). STP: 0°C and 1 atm.",keywords:["gas","gas pressure","boyle's law","charles' law","volume temperature gas","pressure volume","diffusion gas","stp","ideal gas basic"]},{level:"MS",term:"Electrochemistry (Basic)",def:"Electrolytes: substances that dissolve in water to produce ions that conduct electricity (salts, acids, bases). Electrolysis: using electrical current to drive a non-spontaneous chemical reaction. Electroplating: using electrolysis to coat an object with a thin layer of metal (e.g., chrome plating). Batteries (galvanic/voltaic cells): chemical reactions produce electricity spontaneously. In a battery: anode (negative terminal, where oxidation occurs) and cathode (positive terminal, where reduction occurs).",keywords:["electrolyte","electrolysis","electroplating","battery basic","galvanic cell","anode cathode basic","electric current chemistry","ions conduct electricity"]},{level:"MS",term:"pH Scale & Indicators",def:"pH measures how acidic or basic a solution is on a scale from 0 to 14. pH 7 = neutral (pure water). pH < 7 = acidic (more H⁺ ions). pH > 7 = basic/alkaline (more OH⁻ ions). Each whole number represents a 10× change in concentration. Strong acids have very low pH (hydrochloric acid ~1); strong bases have very high pH (sodium hydroxide ~14). Indicators change color at different pH values (litmus: red in acid, blue in base; universal indicator shows full range of colors).",keywords:["ph scale","acidic","basic","alkaline","neutral","hydrogen ion","hydroxide","indicator","litmus","universal indicator"]},{level:"MS",term:"Conservation of Mass & Moles (Basic)",def:"Law of Conservation of Mass: mass is neither created nor destroyed in chemical reactions; total mass of reactants = total mass of products (Lavoisier, 1789). Mole: a counting unit for chemistry; 1 mole = 6.022 × 10²³ particles (Avogadro's number). Molar mass: mass of one mole of a substance in grams (equals atomic/formula mass in grams). Example: water (H₂O) molar mass = 18 g/mol. Allows converting between mass, moles, and number of particles.",keywords:["conservation of mass","lavoisier","mole","avogadro's number","molar mass","counting atoms","formula mass","particle count"]},{level:"MS",term:"Combustion (Basic)",def:"Combustion is a rapid chemical reaction between a fuel and oxygen that releases heat and light. Complete combustion: fuel reacts with plentiful oxygen → carbon dioxide + water vapor (e.g., methane: CH₄ + 2O₂ → CO₂ + 2H₂O). Incomplete combustion (limited oxygen): produces carbon monoxide (CO, toxic) and soot (unburned carbon). Fire triangle: fuel + oxygen + heat — remove any one to extinguish fire. Common fuels: hydrocarbons (natural gas, gasoline, wood). Burning is an exothermic oxidation reaction.",keywords:["combustion","complete combustion","incomplete combustion","carbon monoxide","fire triangle","fuel oxygen heat","exothermic combustion","methane combustion"]},{level:"MS",term:"Alloys & Material Properties",def:"Alloy: a mixture of two or more metals (or a metal and a nonmetal) with properties superior to the pure metals. Steel: iron + carbon (stronger and harder than iron). Stainless steel: iron + carbon + chromium + nickel (corrosion-resistant). Bronze: copper + tin. Brass: copper + zinc. Solder: tin + lead (low melting point for joining metals). Properties of materials: conductivity, strength, hardness, flexibility/ductility, melting point, corrosion resistance. Ceramics: hard, brittle, good insulators. Polymers: flexible, low density, electrical insulators.",keywords:["alloy","steel","bronze","brass","corrosion","material property","conductivity material","hardness","ductility material","ceramic polymer"]},{level:"MS",term:"Flame Tests & Metal Identification",def:"Flame tests: technique to identify metal ions based on the color of light they emit when heated. When atoms are heated, electrons jump to higher energy levels; as they fall back, they emit photons of specific wavelengths (colors). Characteristic colors: lithium (red), sodium (yellow-orange), potassium (lilac/violet), copper (blue-green), barium (pale green), calcium (brick red), strontium (crimson). Used in fireworks to produce colors. More precise identification uses a spectroscope to analyze emission spectra.",keywords:["flame test","metal identification","emission spectrum","sodium yellow","copper blue green","potassium lilac","fireworks color","spectroscope"]},{level:"MS",term:"Polymers (Basic)",def:"Polymers are large molecules made of many repeating units (monomers) linked together. Natural polymers: DNA (nucleotide monomers), proteins (amino acid monomers), cellulose and starch (glucose monomers), rubber (isoprene monomers). Synthetic polymers: polyethylene (plastic bags, from ethylene monomers), nylon (clothing, from diamine + diacid), PVC, Teflon, polystyrene. Addition polymers: monomers add together directly. Condensation polymers: monomers join releasing a small molecule (usually water). Plastics are synthetic polymers and are largely non-biodegradable.",keywords:["polymer","monomer","natural polymer","synthetic polymer","polyethylene","nylon","plastic","addition polymer","condensation polymer basic"]},{level:"MS",term:"Corrosion & Rusting",def:"Corrosion: deterioration of metals due to chemical reactions with their environment. Rusting: specific to iron; iron reacts with oxygen and water → iron oxide (rust; Fe₂O₃·nH₂O). Conditions needed: iron, oxygen, and water (electrolyte accelerates corrosion). Rusting is an electrochemical process — iron loses electrons (oxidizes). Prevention methods: painting or coating (barrier), galvanizing (coating with zinc — zinc oxidizes sacrificially instead of iron), stainless steel (chromium forms protective oxide layer), cathodic protection (attaches more reactive metal).",keywords:["corrosion","rusting","iron oxide","oxidation metal","galvanizing","zinc","sacrificial anode","cathodic protection","prevention corrosion"]},{level:"MS",term:"Naming Compounds (Basic)",def:"Binary ionic compounds: name cation, then anion with -ide suffix (NaCl = sodium chloride; CaCl₂ = calcium chloride; MgO = magnesium oxide). When metal has multiple possible charges: use Roman numerals in parentheses (FeCl₂ = iron(II) chloride; FeCl₃ = iron(III) chloride). Binary covalent compounds (nonmetal + nonmetal): use Greek prefixes for number of atoms (CO₂ = carbon dioxide; N₂O₄ = dinitrogen tetroxide). Acids ending in -ic and -ous. Common bases end in -hydroxide.",keywords:["naming ionic","naming covalent","binary compound naming","roman numeral compound","greek prefix","ide suffix","compound name","chemical nomenclature basic"]},{level:"MS",term:"Natural vs Synthetic Materials",def:"Natural materials: wood, cotton, wool, silk, leather, stone, clay, rubber — come from living organisms or the environment. Synthetic (man-made) materials: nylon, polyester, plastic, Kevlar, fiberglass, synthetic rubber — made from chemical processes, often from petroleum. Advantages of synthetic: can be engineered for specific properties (strength, flexibility, durability). Disadvantages: often non-biodegradable, petroleum-based. Composite materials: combine materials (fiberglass = glass fibers in plastic resin; concrete = cement + aggregate; carbon fiber composites).",keywords:["natural material","synthetic material","composite","plastic","cotton wool","nylon polyester","biodegradable","fiberglass","carbon fiber"]},{level:"MS",term:"Environmental Chemistry",def:"Greenhouse gases: CO₂, CH₄, N₂O, water vapor, ozone — absorb infrared radiation and warm the planet. Combustion of fossil fuels is the main source of CO₂ increase. Ozone: stratospheric ozone (good — blocks UV) vs. ground-level ozone (bad — component of smog). Acid rain: SO₂ and NOₓ from burning fossil fuels react with water → H₂SO₄ and HNO₃; damages ecosystems and infrastructure. Water treatment: coagulation, filtration, disinfection (chlorination or UV). Plastic pollution: non-degradable polymers accumulate in ocean (microplastics).",keywords:["greenhouse gas","acid rain","ozone good bad","co2 emissions","water treatment","plastic pollution","microplastics","so2 nox"]},{level:"MS",term:"Percentage Composition & Empirical Formulas",def:"Percentage composition: mass of each element / molar mass of compound × 100%. Example: H₂O — H: (2×1)/18 × 100% = 11.1%; O: 16/18 × 100% = 88.9%. Empirical formula: simplest whole-number ratio of atoms in a compound. To find: convert percentage to grams, divide by molar mass to get moles, divide by smallest mole value, round to whole numbers. Molecular formula = empirical formula × n, where n = molecular mass / empirical formula mass. Example: empirical CH₂O, molecular C₆H₁₂O₆ (n=6).",keywords:["percentage composition","empirical formula","molecular formula","mole ratio","simplest ratio","formula mass","percent by mass"]}]},Physics:{color:"var(--magenta)",icon:"⚡",items:[{term:"Newton's Laws",def:"1st (Inertia): object stays at rest or in uniform motion without net force. 2nd: F = ma — net force equals mass × acceleration. 3rd: every action has an equal and opposite reaction. Weight W = mg (g ≈ 9.8 m/s²). Normal force is perpendicular to a surface.",keywords:["newton","inertia","f=ma","action reaction","newton's law"]},{term:"Kinematics",def:"Equations (constant acceleration): v = v₀ + at; x = v₀t + ½at²; v² = v₀² + 2ax. Free fall: a = g = 9.8 m/s² downward. Projectile motion: horizontal velocity is constant; vertical component experiences g independently.",keywords:["kinematics","velocity","displacement","free fall","projectile","acceleration"]},{term:"Work, Energy & Power",def:"Work W = Fd·cosθ (Joules). Kinetic energy KE = ½mv². Gravitational PE = mgh. Work-energy theorem: net work = ΔKE. Conservation of mechanical energy (no friction): KE + PE = constant. Power P = W/t = Fv (Watts). 1 hp = 746 W.",keywords:["work","kinetic energy","potential energy","conservation of energy","power","joule","watt"]},{term:"Momentum & Impulse",def:"Momentum p = mv (kg·m/s). Impulse J = FΔt = Δp. Conservation of momentum: total momentum conserved in closed system. Elastic collision: KE conserved. Inelastic: KE not conserved. Perfectly inelastic: objects stick together.",keywords:["momentum","impulse","collision","elastic","inelastic"]},{term:"Waves",def:"Transverse: displacement perpendicular to propagation (light, EM). Longitudinal: displacement parallel (sound). Wave speed v = fλ. Amplitude: maximum displacement. Constructive interference: in phase. Destructive: out of phase. Standing waves: nodes (zero displacement) and antinodes (max displacement).",keywords:["wave","frequency","wavelength","amplitude","transverse","longitudinal","interference","resonance"]},{term:"Electromagnetic Spectrum",def:"Increasing frequency (decreasing λ): Radio → Microwave → Infrared → Visible (ROY G BIV) → UV → X-ray → Gamma. All travel at c = 3×10⁸ m/s in a vacuum. Photon energy E = hf. Higher frequency = more energy = more ionizing radiation.",keywords:["electromagnetic","spectrum","infrared","ultraviolet","gamma ray","x-ray","visible light","photon"]},{term:"Electric Circuits",def:"Ohm's Law: V = IR. Series: same current, voltages add, R_total = ΣRᵢ. Parallel: same voltage, currents add, 1/R_total = Σ(1/Rᵢ). Power P = IV = I²R = V²/R. Kirchhoff's junction rule: currents in = currents out. Loop rule: sum of voltages around a closed loop = 0.",keywords:["ohm","voltage","current","resistance","circuit","series","parallel","kirchhoff"]},{term:"Thermodynamics",def:"0th Law: thermal equilibrium is transitive. 1st Law: ΔU = Q − W. 2nd Law: entropy of isolated system never decreases; heat flows from hot to cold. 3rd Law: entropy → 0 as T → 0 K. Carnot efficiency (maximum): η = 1 − Tc/Th.",keywords:["thermodynamics","entropy","carnot","heat engine","first law","second law","absolute zero"]},{term:"Magnetism & Induction",def:"Magnetic force on charge: F = qv×B. Right-hand rule for current direction and field. Faraday's Law: ε = −ΔΦ/Δt (changing flux induces EMF). Lenz's Law: induced current opposes flux change. Transformer: Vp/Vs = Np/Ns. AC generation via rotating coils in magnetic fields.",keywords:["magnetic field","faraday","lenz","magnetic force","induction","transformer","flux","electromagnet"]},{term:"Modern Physics",def:"Photoelectric effect (Einstein): E = hf − work function; proved light's particle nature. de Broglie: matter wavelength λ = h/p. Heisenberg uncertainty: Δx·Δp ≥ ℏ/2. Special relativity: E = mc²; time dilation t' = t/√(1−v²/c²); length contraction. Nuclear binding energy from mass defect.",keywords:["photoelectric","quantum","de broglie","heisenberg","relativity","planck","wave-particle","e=mc2"]},{term:"Circular Motion & Gravitation",def:"Centripetal acceleration: aₓ = v²/r (directed toward center). Centripetal force: Fc = mv²/r. Newton's Law of Universal Gravitation: F = Gm₁m₂/r². Kepler's Laws: 1st (elliptical orbits), 2nd (equal areas in equal times), 3rd (T² ∝ r³ — orbital period vs semi-major axis).",keywords:["centripetal","centrifugal","gravitation","orbital","kepler","circular motion","universal gravitation"]},{term:"Simple Harmonic Motion",def:"Oscillation where restoring force ∝ displacement (F = −kx). Period of spring: T = 2π√(m/k). Period of pendulum: T = 2π√(L/g) — independent of amplitude (for small angles). At equilibrium: max velocity, zero PE stored. At extremes: zero velocity, max PE. Total energy E = ½kA² (constant).",keywords:["simple harmonic","oscillation","spring constant","pendulum","period","restoring force","amplitude"]},{term:"Fluid Mechanics",def:"Pressure P = F/A; in a fluid P = ρgh. Archimedes' Principle: buoyant force = weight of displaced fluid. Pascal's Law: pressure applied to enclosed fluid transmits equally. Bernoulli's Equation: P + ½ρv² + ρgh = constant (faster flow → lower pressure). Continuity: A₁v₁ = A₂v₂.",keywords:["buoyancy","archimedes","bernoulli","pascal","fluid pressure","continuity equation","density","viscosity"]},{term:"Optics",def:"Law of reflection: angle of incidence = angle of reflection. Snell's Law (refraction): n₁sinθ₁ = n₂sinθ₂. Total internal reflection: when angle exceeds critical angle (n₁ > n₂). Lenses: converging (convex) focuses light; diverging (concave) spreads light. Mirror equation: 1/f = 1/dₒ + 1/dᵢ.",keywords:["reflection","refraction","snell","lens","mirror","focal length","total internal reflection","optic"]},{term:"Sound",def:"Longitudinal mechanical wave; requires medium. Speed in air ≈ 343 m/s (20°C). Intensity measured in decibels (dB): logarithmic scale, 10 dB increase = 10× intensity. Doppler effect: source moving toward observer → higher frequency (pitch). Standing waves in pipes/strings produce harmonics.",keywords:["sound","decibel","doppler","pitch","acoustic","longitudinal","speed of sound","harmonic"]},{term:"Electrostatics",def:"Coulomb's Law: F = kq₁q₂/r² (k = 9×10⁹ N·m²/C²). Electric field E = F/q = kq/r² (points away from + charges, toward − charges). Electric potential energy U = kq₁q₂/r. Electric potential V = kq/r (volts). Work done moving charge: W = qΔV. Field lines perpendicular to equipotential surfaces.",keywords:["coulomb","electric field","electrostatics","electric potential","charge","electric force"]},{term:"Rotational Motion",def:"Angular velocity ω = Δθ/Δt (rad/s). Torque τ = rF·sinθ (N·m). Moment of inertia I: resistance to angular acceleration. Newton's 2nd Law for rotation: τ = Iα. Angular momentum L = Iω; conserved when net torque = 0 (explains spinning figure skater). Rolling without slipping: v = rω.",keywords:["torque","angular momentum","angular velocity","moment of inertia","rotational","angular acceleration"]},{term:"Nuclear Physics",def:"Nucleus held together by strong nuclear force (overcomes Coulomb repulsion). Binding energy: energy released when nucleons combine (mass defect × c²). Iron-56 has highest binding energy per nucleon. Radioactive decay: alpha (A−4, Z−2), beta-minus (Z+1), beta-plus (Z−1), gamma (no change in A or Z).",keywords:["nuclear force","binding energy","mass defect","radioactive decay","alpha particle","beta particle","nuclear physics"]},{term:"Capacitors",def:"Store electrical energy in an electric field between two conducting plates. Capacitance C = Q/V (Farads). Energy stored: U = ½CV² = Q²/2C. Parallel plate capacitor: C = ε₀A/d. Adding a dielectric increases capacitance. Series: 1/C_total = Σ(1/Cᵢ). Parallel: C_total = ΣCᵢ.",keywords:["capacitor","capacitance","dielectric","farad","energy stored","electric field capacitor"]},{term:"Dimensional Analysis",def:"Checking and converting units using known equivalences. SI base units: meter (length), kilogram (mass), second (time), ampere (current), kelvin (temperature), mole (amount), candela (luminous intensity). Derived units: Newton = kg·m/s², Joule = N·m = kg·m²/s², Pascal = N/m², Watt = J/s.",keywords:["si unit","dimensional analysis","unit conversion","base unit","derived unit","newton unit","pascal unit"]},{term:"Pressure",def:"Force per unit area: P = F/A (Pascals). Atmospheric pressure at sea level ≈ 101,325 Pa = 1 atm = 760 mmHg = 760 torr. Gauge pressure = absolute pressure − atmospheric pressure. Vacuum gauge reads relative to atmosphere. Manometers and barometers measure pressure differences.",keywords:["pressure","pascal","atmosphere","atmospheric pressure","barometer","manometer","gauge pressure"]},{term:"Doppler Effect",def:"Apparent change in frequency due to relative motion between source and observer. Source moving toward observer: higher observed frequency. Source moving away: lower frequency. f_obs = f_source × (v ± v_obs)/(v ∓ v_source). Applies to sound and light; redshift (galaxies moving away) is the Doppler effect for light.",keywords:["doppler","redshift","blueshift","frequency shift","apparent frequency","doppler effect"]},{term:"Electric Power & Energy",def:"Electrical power P = IV = I²R = V²/R (Watts). Energy E = Pt (Joules or kWh). Transformers change voltage for efficient long-distance transmission (high V, low I reduces resistive losses P = I²R). AC voltage is described by RMS values: V_rms = V_peak/√2.",keywords:["electric power","kilowatt hour","rms voltage","power dissipation","energy consumption","electrical energy"]},{term:"Light & Photons",def:"Light exhibits wave-particle duality. As a wave: interference, diffraction, polarization. As a particle (photon): energy E = hf = hc/λ. Photoelectric effect confirms particle nature. Double-slit experiment demonstrates wave nature. Photons carry momentum p = h/λ. Speed of light c = 3×10⁸ m/s in vacuum.",keywords:["photon","light","double slit","interference light","polarization","wave-particle duality","hf","hc/lambda"]},{term:"Special Relativity",def:"Einstein's postulates: laws of physics same in all inertial frames; speed of light c is constant for all observers. Consequences: time dilation (moving clocks run slow), length contraction (moving objects shorter in direction of motion), mass-energy equivalence E = mc². Nothing with mass can reach c.",keywords:["special relativity","time dilation","length contraction","e=mc2","lorentz","relativistic","speed of light constant"]},{term:"Gravitational Fields",def:"Gravitational field strength g = GM/r² (N/kg or m/s²). Near Earth's surface, g ≈ 9.8 m/s². Gravitational potential energy: U = −GMm/r (negative, bound system). Escape velocity: v_esc = √(2GM/r). Orbital velocity: v_orb = √(GM/r). Black holes have escape velocity ≥ c.",keywords:["gravitational field","escape velocity","orbital velocity","gravitational potential","gravity","GM/r"]},{term:"Friction",def:"Static friction: force preventing stationary objects from sliding; fₛ ≤ μₛN. Kinetic friction: force opposing sliding motion; fₖ = μₖN. Rolling friction: much less than sliding. μₛ > μₖ (harder to start motion than sustain it). Normal force N: perpendicular contact force. On inclined plane: N = mg·cosθ; friction force = μmg·cosθ; net force along plane = mg·sinθ − μmg·cosθ. Air resistance is a velocity-dependent drag force.",keywords:["friction","static friction","kinetic friction","coefficient of friction","normal force","air resistance","drag","inclined plane"]},{term:"Projectile Motion",def:"Two-dimensional motion under gravity; horizontal and vertical components are independent. Horizontal: uniform motion, vₓ = v₀cosθ, x = v₀cosθ · t. Vertical: uniform acceleration, vᵧ = v₀sinθ − gt, y = v₀sinθ · t − ½gt². Range R = v₀²sin(2θ)/g (maximum at 45°). At maximum height: vᵧ = 0. Time of flight: t = 2v₀sinθ/g. Neglects air resistance.",keywords:["projectile motion","range","trajectory","horizontal velocity","vertical velocity","angle of projection","time of flight","maximum height"]},{term:"Torque & Rotational Equilibrium",def:"Torque τ = r × F = rF sinθ (N·m); the rotational equivalent of force. For static equilibrium: ΣF = 0 (translational) AND Στ = 0 (rotational). Torque is positive (counterclockwise) or negative (clockwise) about a chosen pivot. Lever arm: perpendicular distance from pivot to line of action of force. Center of mass: point where gravity effectively acts. A uniform rod's center of mass is at its midpoint.",keywords:["torque","rotational equilibrium","lever arm","center of mass","static equilibrium","moment","pivot","clockwise counterclockwise"]},{term:"Heat & Specific Heat Capacity",def:"Temperature measures average kinetic energy of particles (K = −273.15°C). Heat Q = mcΔT where c = specific heat capacity (J/kg·K). Water: c = 4186 J/kg·K (highest of common substances — moderates climate). Latent heat: Q = mL; energy for phase change at constant temperature. Lf (fusion) for water = 334 kJ/kg; Lv (vaporization) = 2260 kJ/kg. Calorimetry: heat lost by hot object = heat gained by cold (Q_lost = Q_gained).",keywords:["specific heat","heat capacity","latent heat","calorimetry","fusion","vaporization","temperature","thermal mass","q=mcdeltaT"]},{term:"Diffraction & Interference",def:"Diffraction: bending of waves around obstacles or through slits; significant when slit width ≈ wavelength. Single-slit diffraction: minima at a sinθ = mλ. Double-slit (Young's experiment): constructive interference at d sinθ = mλ; bright fringes spaced Δy = λL/d. Thin film interference: path difference = 2t; phase shift on reflection from denser medium. Diffraction gratings: d sinθ = mλ; bright spots at each order m.",keywords:["diffraction","interference","double slit","young's experiment","thin film","diffraction grating","constructive interference","destructive interference","wavelength"]},{term:"Magnetic Flux & Faraday's Law",def:"Magnetic flux Φ = BA cosθ (Weber). Faraday's Law: induced EMF ε = −ΔΦ/Δt (rate of flux change). Lenz's Law: induced current opposes the change that caused it (−sign). EMF can be induced by: changing B, changing area, or changing angle. Motional EMF: ε = BLv (conductor of length L moving at speed v through field B). Generators: rotating loop in B field produces sinusoidal AC. Transformers: Vp/Vs = Np/Ns; IpNp = IsNs.",keywords:["magnetic flux","faraday's law","lenz's law","induced emf","motional emf","generator","transformer","flux change"]},{term:"Resonance & Standing Waves",def:"Standing wave: superposition of two identical waves traveling in opposite directions; produces nodes (zero displacement) and antinodes (max displacement). String (fixed both ends): fundamental f₁ = v/2L; harmonics fₙ = nv/2L. Open pipe (open both ends): same as string. Closed pipe (one end closed): only odd harmonics; f₁ = v/4L; fₙ = nv/4L (n = 1, 3, 5…). Resonance: driving frequency matches natural frequency → maximum amplitude.",keywords:["standing wave","node","antinode","fundamental frequency","harmonic","resonance","string vibration","open pipe","closed pipe","overtone"]},{term:"RC & LR Circuits",def:"RC circuit (resistor + capacitor): charging — V_C = V₀(1 − e^(−t/RC)); discharging — V_C = V₀e^(−t/RC). Time constant τ = RC; after one τ, capacitor charges to ~63% of final voltage. Impedance in AC circuits: capacitive reactance Xc = 1/(2πfC); inductive reactance XL = 2πfL. At resonance in LC circuit: f = 1/(2π√(LC)). Phase relationships: current leads voltage in capacitor; lags in inductor.",keywords:["rc circuit","time constant","capacitor charging","impedance","reactance","inductive","capacitive","ac circuit","lc resonance"]},{term:"Bohr Model & Atomic Spectra",def:"Bohr model (1913): electrons orbit nucleus at fixed radii; energy quantized. Energy levels: Eₙ = −13.6 eV/n² for hydrogen. Electron absorbs photon → jumps to higher level (absorption spectrum). Electron falls to lower level → emits photon of energy E = hf = ΔE (emission spectrum). Lyman series: transitions to n=1 (UV). Balmer series: to n=2 (visible). Paschen: to n=3 (IR). Rydberg equation: 1/λ = R(1/n₁² − 1/n₂²).",keywords:["bohr model","energy level","emission spectrum","absorption spectrum","lyman","balmer","rydberg","photon emission","hydrogen spectrum"]},{term:"Particle Physics",def:"Standard Model: matter made of fermions (quarks + leptons). Quarks: up (u), down (d), charm (c), strange (s), top (t), bottom (b). Proton = uud; neutron = udd. Leptons: electron, muon, tau and their neutrinos. Forces carried by bosons: photon (electromagnetic), W/Z bosons (weak), gluons (strong), graviton (hypothetical, gravity). Antimatter: opposite charge/quantum numbers. Pair production: γ → e⁻ + e⁺.",keywords:["quark","lepton","standard model","boson","gluon","photon","antimatter","proton quark","fermion","particle physics"]},{term:"Vectors & Scalars",def:"Scalar: magnitude only (mass, speed, temperature, energy). Vector: magnitude + direction (velocity, force, acceleration, displacement, momentum). Vector addition: tip-to-tail or parallelogram method. Component method: break into x/y components, add separately. Resultant magnitude: R = √(Rₓ² + Rᵧ²); angle: θ = arctan(Rᵧ/Rₓ). Dot product (scalar): A·B = AB cosθ. Cross product (vector): A×B, magnitude AB sinθ, direction by right-hand rule.",keywords:["vector","scalar","component","resultant","dot product","cross product","vector addition","magnitude direction"]},{term:"Thermal Expansion",def:"Most materials expand when heated. Linear expansion: ΔL = αL₀ΔT (α = coefficient of linear expansion). Volume expansion: ΔV = βV₀ΔT; β ≈ 3α. Water anomaly: maximum density at 4°C; expands on freezing (ice less dense than liquid water — important for aquatic life). Bimetallic strips: two metals with different α bonded together; bend on heating (used in thermostats). Thermal stress: if expansion is constrained, large forces develop.",keywords:["thermal expansion","coefficient of expansion","linear expansion","volume expansion","water anomaly","bimetallic strip","thermal stress","density of water"]},{term:"Buoyancy & Archimedes",def:"Archimedes' Principle: buoyant force = weight of fluid displaced (F_b = ρ_fluid · V_submerged · g). Object floats if F_b ≥ weight (density of object ≤ density of fluid). Fully submerged: F_b = ρ_fluid · V_object · g (independent of depth). Apparent weight = actual weight − F_b. Applications: ships (large volume displaces much water), submarines (change buoyancy by flooding/emptying ballast tanks), hot air balloons (less dense than cool air).",keywords:["buoyancy","archimedes","buoyant force","displaced fluid","float","sink","apparent weight","density fluid","submarine"]},{term:"Angular Momentum Conservation",def:"Angular momentum L = Iω; conserved when net external torque = 0. Moment of inertia I depends on mass distribution (I = mr² for point mass; I = ½mr² for solid disk; I = ⅔mr² for hollow sphere). Spinning figure skater: pulls arms in → I decreases → ω increases (L constant). Gyroscope: resists changes in orientation. Precession: gyroscope axis rotates due to gravity torque. Conservation of L explains planetary orbits (Kepler's 2nd Law — equal areas in equal times).",keywords:["angular momentum","conservation","moment of inertia","angular velocity","precession","gyroscope","figure skater","torque angular"]},{level:"MS",term:"Motion & Speed",def:"Speed = distance / time (m/s). Velocity includes both speed and direction (a vector). Acceleration = change in velocity / time; can mean speeding up, slowing down, or changing direction. Distance-time graphs: slope = speed. Velocity-time graphs: slope = acceleration, area = displacement. Average speed = total distance / total time.",keywords:["speed","velocity","acceleration","distance","time","motion","distance-time graph","average speed"]},{level:"MS",term:"Forces",def:"A force is a push or pull measured in Newtons (N). Net force is the sum of all forces on an object. Balanced forces: net force = 0; object stays at rest or moves at constant velocity. Unbalanced forces cause acceleration. Types: gravity, normal force, friction (opposes motion), tension, applied force. Weight = mass × gravity (W = mg).",keywords:["force","newton","net force","friction","gravity","normal force","balanced","unbalanced","weight"]},{level:"MS",term:"Newton's Laws (Basic)",def:"1st Law (Inertia): an object at rest stays at rest, and an object in motion stays in motion unless acted on by a net force. 2nd Law: F = ma (force = mass × acceleration). 3rd Law: for every action, there is an equal and opposite reaction. Inertia is the resistance to change in motion; greater mass = greater inertia.",keywords:["newton's law","inertia","f=ma","action reaction","first law","second law","third law","mass"]},{level:"MS",term:"Work & Energy (Basic)",def:"Work = Force × distance × cos(angle) (Joules). Work is done only when a force moves an object in the direction of the force. Energy is the ability to do work. Kinetic energy (KE = ½mv²): energy of motion. Potential energy: stored energy (gravitational PE = mgh; elastic PE in springs). Energy can change forms but is always conserved.",keywords:["work","energy","kinetic energy","potential energy","joule","conservation","gravity","elastic"]},{level:"MS",term:"Simple Machines",def:"Six types: lever, wheel and axle, pulley, inclined plane, wedge, and screw. All reduce the force needed to do work by increasing distance. Mechanical advantage (MA) = output force / input force. Levers have three classes based on the positions of the fulcrum, effort, and load. Pulleys and compound machines combine simple machines.",keywords:["simple machine","lever","pulley","inclined plane","wedge","screw","mechanical advantage","fulcrum"]},{level:"MS",term:"Waves (Basic)",def:"Waves transfer energy without transferring matter. Transverse waves: particles vibrate perpendicular to wave direction (light, water surface). Longitudinal (compressional) waves: particles vibrate parallel to wave direction (sound). Wavelength (λ): distance between identical points. Frequency (f): waves per second (Hz). Wave speed = frequency × wavelength.",keywords:["wave","transverse","longitudinal","wavelength","frequency","amplitude","hertz","speed of wave"]},{level:"MS",term:"Electricity (Basic)",def:"Electric current: flow of electrons through a conductor, measured in amperes (A). Voltage: the 'push' that drives current, measured in volts (V). Resistance: opposition to current flow, measured in ohms (Ω). Ohm's Law: V = IR. Series circuits: one path; all components share the same current. Parallel circuits: multiple paths; voltage is the same across each branch.",keywords:["current","voltage","resistance","ohm","series circuit","parallel circuit","conductor","battery","electric"]},{level:"MS",term:"Light (Basic)",def:"Light is a form of electromagnetic radiation that travels in a straight line at about 3×10⁸ m/s in a vacuum. Reflection: light bounces off a surface (angle of incidence = angle of reflection). Refraction: light bends when it passes from one medium to another (lens, prism). White light can be separated into the visible spectrum (ROY G BIV). Opaque objects block light; transparent objects transmit light.",keywords:["light","reflection","refraction","visible spectrum","opaque","transparent","electromagnetic","prism","lens"]},{level:"MS",term:"Sound (Basic)",def:"Sound is a longitudinal mechanical wave that requires a medium (solid, liquid, or gas) to travel through. Speed of sound in air ≈ 343 m/s; faster in solids and liquids. Pitch depends on frequency (high pitch = high frequency). Volume (loudness) depends on amplitude. Echoes are reflections of sound. Sound cannot travel in a vacuum.",keywords:["sound","longitudinal","pitch","frequency","amplitude","echo","medium","vibration","vacuum"]},{level:"MS",term:"Distance vs Displacement",def:"Distance: total path length traveled; scalar quantity (has magnitude only, no direction). Displacement: straight-line change in position from start to finish; vector quantity (has both magnitude and direction). Example: walking 3 m east then 3 m west → distance = 6 m, displacement = 0 m. Speed = distance / time. Velocity = displacement / time (includes direction). Average speed uses total distance; instantaneous speed is speed at a specific moment.",keywords:["distance","displacement","scalar","vector","speed","velocity","path length","position change","average speed"]},{level:"MS",term:"Gravity (Basic)",def:"Gravity is a force of attraction between all objects with mass. On Earth, gravity pulls objects downward toward Earth's center at g ≈ 9.8 m/s² (acceleration due to gravity). Weight = mass × gravity (W = mg); measured in Newtons. Mass: amount of matter in an object; does not change with location. Weight: force due to gravity; changes with location (you weigh less on the Moon). All objects fall at the same rate in a vacuum (Galileo) — gravity accelerates them equally regardless of mass.",keywords:["gravity","weight","mass","acceleration due to gravity","g","newton gravity","free fall","galileo","mass vs weight"]},{level:"MS",term:"Types of Forces",def:"Contact forces: act through physical contact. Applied force: push or pull. Tension: pulling force through a rope or string. Compression: squeezing force. Friction: opposes relative motion between surfaces. Normal force: perpendicular support force from surface. Non-contact forces: act at a distance. Gravity: attraction between masses. Magnetic force: between magnets or magnetic materials. Electrostatic force: between charged objects. Net force: vector sum of all forces; determines acceleration (F_net = ma).",keywords:["applied force","tension","normal force","friction force","gravity force","magnetic force","electrostatic","contact force","non-contact force","net force"]},{level:"MS",term:"Air Resistance & Terminal Velocity",def:"Air resistance (drag): force opposing motion through air; depends on speed, shape, and surface area. As an object falls faster, air resistance increases until it equals the gravitational force → net force = 0 → acceleration = 0 → constant speed (terminal velocity). Skydivers reach terminal velocity ~195 km/h spread-eagle; parachute increases surface area → greater air resistance → much lower terminal velocity (~20 km/h). Streamlined shapes reduce air resistance (cars, aircraft, birds).",keywords:["air resistance","drag","terminal velocity","skydiver","parachute","streamlined","net force zero","constant speed fall","surface area drag"]},{level:"MS",term:"Work & Power (Basic)",def:"Work is done when a force moves an object in the direction of the force. Work = Force × distance (W = Fd); unit = Joule (J). No work is done if: no movement occurs, or force is perpendicular to motion. Power: rate at which work is done. Power = Work / time = Force × velocity (P = W/t); unit = Watt (W). 1 Watt = 1 Joule per second. A more powerful machine does the same work in less time. 1 horsepower = 746 Watts.",keywords:["work","power","joule","watt","force distance","rate of work","horsepower","w=fd","p=w/t","perpendicular force"]},{level:"MS",term:"Mechanical Energy",def:"Mechanical energy = kinetic energy + potential energy. Kinetic energy (KE): energy of motion; KE = ½mv². Gravitational potential energy (GPE): stored energy due to height; GPE = mgh. As an object falls: PE converts to KE (speed increases); as it rises: KE converts to PE. Conservation of mechanical energy (no friction): total mechanical energy stays constant. Examples: pendulum (PE at top, KE at bottom), roller coaster (PE at top of hill, KE at bottom). Energy is measured in Joules.",keywords:["mechanical energy","kinetic energy","potential energy","conservation","ke=1/2mv2","gpe=mgh","pendulum","roller coaster","energy conversion"]},{level:"MS",term:"Heat & Temperature (Basic)",def:"Temperature: average kinetic energy of particles in a substance; measured in °C, °F, or K. Heat: thermal energy transferred from a hotter to a cooler object due to temperature difference; measured in Joules or calories (1 cal = 4.18 J). Specific heat capacity: amount of heat needed to raise 1 kg by 1°C (water = 4,186 J/kg·°C — high specific heat stabilizes Earth's climate). Thermal equilibrium: when two objects reach the same temperature and heat transfer stops. Temperature conversions: K = °C + 273; °F = (°C × 9/5) + 32.",keywords:["heat","temperature","specific heat","thermal energy","thermal equilibrium","celsius kelvin","joule calorie","kinetic energy temperature"]},{level:"MS",term:"Pressure & Fluids (Basic)",def:"Pressure = Force / Area (P = F/A); unit = Pascal (Pa). A small force over a small area can create high pressure (e.g., sharp knife). Atmospheric pressure at sea level = 101,325 Pa = 1 atm. Water pressure increases with depth: P = ρgh (density × gravity × depth). Pascal's Law: pressure applied to an enclosed fluid is transmitted equally in all directions (basis of hydraulics — car brakes, hydraulic lifts). Archimedes' Principle: buoyant force = weight of fluid displaced; objects float if buoyant force ≥ weight.",keywords:["pressure","pascal","atmospheric pressure","water pressure","hydraulics","pascal's law","archimedes basic","buoyancy basic","fluid pressure"]},{level:"MS",term:"Electricity & Static Charge",def:"Electric charge: property of matter (positive or negative). Like charges repel; opposite charges attract (Coulomb's Law). Neutral objects have equal positive and negative charges. Static electricity: buildup of electric charge on an insulating surface (rubbing balloon transfers electrons). Conductor: allows electrons to flow freely (metals). Insulator: prevents electron flow (rubber, plastic, glass). Grounding: allows excess charge to flow into Earth. Lightning: static charge buildup in clouds discharges to ground.",keywords:["electric charge","static electricity","conductor","insulator","coulomb","like charges repel","grounding","lightning","electron transfer","positive negative charge"]},{level:"MS",term:"Magnets & Electromagnetism",def:"Magnets: have north and south poles; opposite poles attract, like poles repel. Magnetic field: invisible force field around a magnet (field lines from N to S outside magnet). Earth acts as a giant magnet (geographic north pole is near magnetic south). All magnets are dipoles — you cannot separate poles. Electromagnets: magnetic field created by electric current flowing through a wire coil; stronger with more coils, more current, or an iron core. Used in electric motors, generators, MRI machines, speakers, and doorbells.",keywords:["magnet","magnetic field","north south pole","electromagnet","magnetic force","earth magnetic field","electric motor","generator magnet","field line"]},{level:"MS",term:"Circuits (Detail)",def:"Series circuit: components connected in a single loop; same current flows through all; one component fails → all fail; total resistance adds up (R_total = R₁ + R₂ + …); voltage divides among components. Parallel circuit: components connected in multiple branches; same voltage across all branches; one component fails → others continue; total resistance decreases (1/R_total = 1/R₁ + 1/R₂ + …); current divides among branches. Power P = IV = I²R = V²/R. Fuses and circuit breakers protect against excess current.",keywords:["series circuit","parallel circuit","current","voltage","resistance","ohm's law circuit","circuit breaker","fuse","total resistance"]},{level:"MS",term:"Momentum (Basic)",def:"Momentum = mass × velocity (p = mv); unit = kg·m/s. Momentum is a vector (has direction). The more massive or faster an object, the more momentum it has. Impulse: change in momentum = force × time (J = FΔt = Δp). Law of Conservation of Momentum: in a closed system (no external forces), total momentum before collision = total momentum after. Applications: car airbags (increase time of impact → reduce force), rocket propulsion, sports (catching a ball, billiards).",keywords:["momentum","p=mv","impulse","conservation of momentum","collision momentum","mass velocity","closed system","airbag","kg m/s"]},{level:"MS",term:"Energy Sources & Power Plants",def:"Most power plants generate electricity by spinning a turbine connected to a generator. Coal/natural gas plants: burn fuel to heat water → steam → turbine → generator. Nuclear plants: fission heats water → steam → turbine. Hydroelectric: falling water spins turbine directly. Wind: wind spins turbine blades. Solar: photovoltaic cells convert light directly to electricity (no turbine). Geothermal: steam from Earth's heat. All electricity from turbine-based plants involves: chemical/nuclear/mechanical energy → thermal energy → kinetic energy → electrical energy.",keywords:["power plant","turbine","generator","coal plant","nuclear plant","hydroelectric","energy conversion chain","steam turbine","electricity generation basic"]},{level:"MS",term:"Thermal Expansion (Basic)",def:"Most materials expand when heated and contract when cooled. This happens because particles vibrate more at higher temperatures and push each other farther apart. Applications: thermometers (liquid expands in a narrow tube), bimetallic strips in thermostats (two metals expand at different rates, causing bending), gaps in railroad tracks and bridges (allow for expansion without buckling). Water is unusual: it expands when freezing (ice is less dense than water → ice floats). Gases expand much more than liquids or solids when heated.",keywords:["thermal expansion","expand heat","contract cool","thermometer","bimetallic strip","bridge gap","water expands freezing","ice density less","particle vibration"]},{level:"MS",term:"Circular Motion (Basic)",def:"An object moving in a circle is constantly changing direction → it is accelerating even at constant speed. Centripetal acceleration: directed toward the center of the circle. Centripetal force: net inward force keeping object in circular path; provided by tension (ball on string), gravity (planets), normal force (roller coaster loop), or friction (car turning). Common misconception: there is no outward 'centrifugal force' — the feeling of being pushed outward is inertia (tendency to continue in straight line). Larger speed or smaller radius → greater centripetal force needed.",keywords:["circular motion","centripetal force","centripetal acceleration","center of circle","inertia circular","centrifugal myth","satellite orbit basic","rotation"]},{level:"MS",term:"Mirrors & Lenses (Basic)",def:"Plane (flat) mirror: image is virtual, upright, same size, appears as far behind mirror as object is in front. Concave (converging) mirror: curves inward; can produce real or virtual images depending on object position; used in telescopes, flashlights, satellite dishes. Convex (diverging) mirror: curves outward; always produces smaller, virtual, upright image; wider field of view — used in store security mirrors and car side mirrors. Converging (convex) lens: focuses parallel rays to focal point. Diverging (concave) lens: spreads rays apart. Glasses correct vision by adjusting where image forms on retina.",keywords:["mirror","lens","concave mirror","convex mirror","converging lens","diverging lens","focal point","virtual image","real image","refraction lens"]},{level:"MS",term:"Color & Electromagnetic Waves",def:"White light is a mixture of all visible colors (ROY G BIV: red, orange, yellow, green, blue, indigo, violet). A prism separates white light into its spectrum by refraction (different wavelengths bend at different angles). The color of an opaque object is the color of light it reflects (a red apple reflects red, absorbs others). Mixing light colors (additive): red + green + blue = white. Mixing pigments/paints (subtractive): yellow + cyan + magenta = black. Electromagnetic waves include (in order of increasing frequency): radio, microwave, infrared, visible, UV, X-ray, gamma.",keywords:["color","white light","spectrum","prism","reflection color","additive mixing","subtractive mixing","electromagnetic spectrum basic","roygbiv","wavelength color"]},{level:"MS",term:"Projectile Motion (Basic)",def:"A projectile is any object launched into the air that then moves under gravity alone (no engine force). Horizontal and vertical motions are independent. Horizontal: constant velocity (no air resistance). Vertical: constant acceleration downward due to gravity (g ≈ 9.8 m/s²). The path (trajectory) is a parabola. Maximum range achieved at 45° launch angle. At maximum height, vertical velocity = 0. Time in air depends only on vertical component. Examples: kicked soccer ball, bullet fired horizontally, thrown ball.",keywords:["projectile motion basic","trajectory","parabola","horizontal velocity","vertical gravity","launch angle","45 degrees","independent motion"]},{level:"MS",term:"Energy in Waves",def:"Waves transfer energy from one place to another without transferring matter. Amount of energy carried by a wave depends on its amplitude (larger amplitude → more energy). Frequency also relates to energy (higher frequency → more energy per photon for electromagnetic waves). Wave reflection: bounces off a barrier. Refraction: changes speed (and direction) when entering a new medium. Absorption: wave energy is absorbed by material and converted to heat. Resonance: object vibrates at its natural frequency when driven by an external frequency matching it (can cause bridges to oscillate dangerously).",keywords:["wave energy","amplitude energy","reflection wave","refraction wave","absorption wave","resonance basic","energy transfer wave","natural frequency"]},{level:"MS",term:"Machines & Mechanical Advantage",def:"Machines change the size or direction of a force. Mechanical advantage (MA) = output force / input force. MA > 1: machine multiplies force (requires moving input through larger distance). MA < 1: machine multiplies speed/distance (requires larger input force). Efficiency = (work output / work input) × 100%; always < 100% due to friction. Lever classes: Class 1 (fulcrum between effort and load — seesaw); Class 2 (load between fulcrum and effort — wheelbarrow); Class 3 (effort between fulcrum and load — tweezers). Pulleys: fixed (changes direction only), movable (doubles force), block-and-tackle (multiple pulleys).",keywords:["mechanical advantage","efficiency machine","lever class","fulcrum","pulley","work input output","force multiplier","inclined plane ma","class 1 2 3 lever"]},{level:"MS",term:"Nuclear Energy (Basic)",def:"Nuclear energy comes from changes in the nucleus of atoms. Fission: splitting a heavy nucleus (like uranium-235) into smaller nuclei + 2–3 neutrons + large amount of energy. Chain reaction: neutrons released split more nuclei. Used in nuclear power plants (controlled chain reaction; heat produces steam to turn turbines) and nuclear bombs (uncontrolled). Fusion: combining light nuclei (hydrogen isotopes) to form helium → even more energy released; powers the Sun and stars; scientists are working to achieve controlled fusion on Earth. No CO₂ emissions from nuclear power.",keywords:["nuclear energy basic","fission basic","chain reaction basic","fusion basic","uranium","nuclear power plant basic","nuclear bomb","no co2 nuclear"]},{level:"MS",term:"Transfer of Thermal Energy",def:"Conduction: heat transfer through direct contact; atoms/molecules pass kinetic energy to neighbors; best in solids (metals are best conductors; wood, air are good insulators). Convection: heat transfer by movement of a fluid (liquid or gas); warm fluid rises (less dense), cool fluid sinks → creates convection currents; responsible for ocean currents, wind, boiling water. Radiation: heat transfer by electromagnetic waves (infrared); does not need a medium; how the Sun warms Earth; dark surfaces absorb more radiation than light/shiny surfaces.",keywords:["conduction","convection","radiation","thermal energy transfer","convection current","insulator conductor","infrared radiation","dark light surface"]},{level:"MS",term:"Density & Floating/Sinking",def:"Density = mass / volume (D = m/V); units g/cm³ or g/mL. An object floats if it is less dense than the fluid it is placed in; sinks if it is denser. Density of water = 1 g/cm³. Ice (0.92 g/cm³) floats on water. A ship made of steel floats because its average density (including air inside) is less than water. Archimedes' principle: buoyant force = weight of displaced fluid. Liquids of different densities can be layered (e.g., oil floats on water). Gases are much less dense than liquids or solids.",keywords:["density","floating","sinking","buoyancy","archimedes basic","mass volume","ice float","average density","displaced fluid basic","d=m/v"]},{level:"MS",term:"Wave Properties (Detail)",def:"Wavelength (λ): distance between two consecutive crests (or troughs). Frequency (f): number of complete waves passing a point per second; unit = Hertz (Hz). Amplitude: maximum displacement from rest position (related to energy). Wave speed (v): v = fλ (wave speed = frequency × wavelength). Period (T): time for one complete wave; T = 1/f. Crest: highest point; trough: lowest point. For electromagnetic waves (light, radio, etc.): all travel at speed of light (c = 3 × 10⁸ m/s) in a vacuum.",keywords:["wavelength","frequency","amplitude","wave speed","period","crest","trough","hertz","v=f lambda","wave properties detail"]},{level:"MS",term:"Gravity & Orbits (Basic)",def:"Gravity is a long-range attractive force between all masses. Strength of gravity depends on the masses of the objects and the distance between them (greater mass → stronger gravity; greater distance → weaker gravity). Orbit: a planet's curved path around the Sun is caused by gravity pulling it continuously inward while its inertia carries it forward. Satellites orbit Earth the same way. The Moon is in orbit around Earth; Earth orbits the Sun. Without gravity, an orbiting body would travel in a straight line. Orbital speed must be just right — too slow → falls; too fast → escapes.",keywords:["gravity orbit","orbital motion","satellite orbit basic","centripetal gravity","moon orbit","earth orbit sun","orbital speed","escape basic","inertia orbit"]},{level:"MS",term:"Latent Heat (Basic)",def:"Latent heat: energy absorbed or released during a phase change at constant temperature. Melting (solid → liquid): absorbs latent heat of fusion. Freezing (liquid → solid): releases latent heat of fusion. Evaporation/boiling (liquid → gas): absorbs latent heat of vaporization (largest). Condensation (gas → liquid): releases latent heat of vaporization. For water: latent heat of vaporization = 2,260 kJ/kg (much larger than fusion = 334 kJ/kg). Latent heat explains why sweating cools the body and why steam burns are worse than boiling water burns.",keywords:["latent heat","phase change heat","latent heat fusion","latent heat vaporization","melting energy","evaporation energy","condensation heat","boiling constant temperature"]},{level:"MS",term:"Specific Heat & Calorimetry (Basic)",def:"Specific heat capacity (c): amount of heat required to raise 1 kg of a substance by 1°C (or 1 K). Q = mcΔT (heat = mass × specific heat × temperature change). Water has a very high specific heat (4,186 J/kg·°C) — it resists temperature changes; this moderates Earth's climate and body temperature. Metals have low specific heat (iron ≈ 450 J/kg·°C) — heat up and cool down quickly. Calorimetry: measuring heat transfer; in an insulated system, heat lost by hot = heat gained by cold (Q_lost = Q_gained). Used to find specific heat of unknown substances.",keywords:["specific heat","calorimetry","q=mcdeltaT","heat capacity basic","water high specific heat","metal low specific heat","heat lost gained","temperature change heat"]},{level:"MS",term:"Electrical Safety",def:"Short circuit: electricity takes an unintended low-resistance path (can cause overheating and fires). Fuse: thin wire that melts when too much current flows, breaking the circuit. Circuit breaker: switch that trips and opens circuit when current is too high; can be reset. Ground fault circuit interrupter (GFCI): detects tiny current differences and shuts off power in 1/40 second (used near water). Insulation: rubber/plastic coating on wires prevents accidental contact. Never use electrical devices near water (water + electricity → electrocution). High-voltage power lines are dangerous to approach.",keywords:["electrical safety","short circuit","fuse","circuit breaker","gfci","insulation electrical","overload","electrocution","ground fault"]}]},"Earth Science":{color:"var(--orange)",icon:"🌍",items:[{term:"Plate Tectonics",def:"Earth's lithosphere divided into plates driven by mantle convection. Convergent boundaries: subduction (oceanic under continental → volcanoes/trenches) or continent–continent collision (mountains). Divergent: plates separate (mid-ocean ridges). Transform: plates slide past (strike-slip faults, earthquakes).",keywords:["plate tectonic","subduction","divergent","convergent","transform","fault","lithosphere"]},{term:"Rock Cycle",def:"Igneous rocks: cooled magma/lava; intrusive (slow cooling, large crystals) = granite; extrusive (fast) = basalt. Sedimentary: compacted sediments (limestone, sandstone, shale). Metamorphic: heat + pressure transform existing rock (marble from limestone; quartzite from sandstone). All types can convert to others.",keywords:["igneous","sedimentary","metamorphic","rock cycle","magma","lava","granite","basalt","limestone"]},{term:"Atmosphere Layers",def:"Troposphere (0–12 km): weather; T decreases with altitude. Stratosphere (12–50 km): ozone layer; T increases. Mesosphere (50–80 km): coldest; meteors burn. Thermosphere: aurora borealis; ionosphere. Exosphere: outermost; merges with space. Tropopause/stratopause mark boundaries.",keywords:["troposphere","stratosphere","mesosphere","thermosphere","ozone","ionosphere","aurora"]},{term:"Earth's Interior",def:"Crust: oceanic (denser basaltic) and continental (granitic). Mantle (largest): silicate rock; partially molten asthenosphere allows plate movement. Outer core: liquid iron-nickel; convection generates Earth's magnetic field via dynamo effect. Inner core: solid iron-nickel despite high temperature (extreme pressure).",keywords:["crust","mantle","outer core","inner core","asthenosphere","earth interior","seismic"]},{term:"Geologic Time Scale",def:"Eons: Hadean, Archean, Proterozoic, Phanerozoic. Phanerozoic eras: Paleozoic (invertebrates, fish, amphibians), Mesozoic (Triassic/Jurassic/Cretaceous; dinosaurs, first mammals), Cenozoic (Paleogene/Neogene/Quaternary; mammals dominant, humans). Radiometric dating uses radioactive decay half-lives.",keywords:["geologic time","paleozoic","mesozoic","cenozoic","jurassic","cretaceous","radiometric","era"]},{term:"Water Cycle",def:"Evaporation + transpiration (evapotranspiration) move water into atmosphere. Condensation forms clouds. Precipitation returns water to surface. Infiltration recharges groundwater. Surface runoff flows to rivers and oceans. Solar energy drives the cycle; gravity pulls water downward.",keywords:["evaporation","condensation","precipitation","transpiration","water cycle","groundwater","runoff"]},{term:"Minerals",def:"Naturally occurring, inorganic, crystalline solids with definite chemical composition. Identified by hardness (Mohs scale: talc=1, gypsum=2, calcite=3, fluorite=4, apatite=5, feldspar=6, quartz=7, topaz=8, corundum=9, diamond=10), luster, streak, cleavage/fracture, and specific gravity.",keywords:["mineral","mohs","hardness","silicate","cleavage","luster","quartz","feldspar","streak"]},{term:"Earthquakes & Seismic Waves",def:"P-waves (primary, compressional): fastest; travel through solids and liquids. S-waves (shear): solids only; used to identify liquid outer core. Surface waves cause most structural damage. Hypocenter: underground origin. Epicenter: surface point above focus. Richter and moment magnitude scales measure size.",keywords:["earthquake","seismic","p-wave","s-wave","epicenter","richter","magnitude","focus"]},{term:"Ocean Circulation",def:"Surface currents driven by wind; gyres rotate clockwise in NH, counterclockwise in SH (Coriolis effect). Thermohaline circulation: deep ocean conveyor belt driven by density differences (cold, salty water sinks). Upwelling brings cold, nutrient-rich deep water to surface, supporting marine ecosystems.",keywords:["ocean current","thermohaline","gyre","upwelling","salinity","gulf stream","coriolis"]},{term:"Weather Systems",def:"High pressure (anticyclone): sinking air, clear skies. Low pressure (cyclone): rising air, clouds and precipitation. Cold front: dense cold air pushes warm air up rapidly (thunderstorms). Warm front: warm air rises gradually over cold (steady rain). Coriolis deflects winds; jet streams steer weather systems.",keywords:["weather","front","cyclone","anticyclone","air mass","cold front","warm front","coriolis"]},{term:"Volcanoes",def:"Shield volcanoes: broad, gently sloping; basaltic lava flows; low viscosity (e.g., Hawaiian). Composite/stratovolcanoes: steep, explosive; andesitic/rhyolitic magma; high viscosity (e.g., Mt. St. Helens). Cinder cone: steep, pyroclastic material. Hotspot volcanism: mantle plumes not at plate boundaries.",keywords:["volcano","shield volcano","composite volcano","stratovolcano","basalt","magma","lava flow","eruption","cinder cone"]},{term:"Glaciers & Ice Ages",def:"Glaciers form where snowfall exceeds melting; compressed snow becomes ice. Continental glaciers (ice sheets) covered much of North America during Pleistocene ice ages. Valley glaciers carve U-shaped valleys, cirques, horns, and fjords. Glacial till is unsorted sediment deposited by ice.",keywords:["glacier","ice age","pleistocene","ice sheet","glacial","till","moraine","ice core"]},{term:"Weathering & Erosion",def:"Mechanical weathering: breaks rock without changing composition (freeze-thaw, abrasion). Chemical weathering: alters minerals (oxidation, hydrolysis, carbonation — CO₂ + H₂O → carbonic acid dissolves limestone). Erosion: transport of weathered material by water, wind, ice, or gravity. Soil forms from weathered rock + organic matter.",keywords:["weathering","erosion","mechanical weathering","chemical weathering","soil","oxidation","carbonic acid"]},{term:"Tides",def:"Caused by gravitational pull of the Moon (primary) and Sun. High tide on the side facing the Moon and on the opposite side (inertia). Spring tides (highest range): Moon, Earth, and Sun aligned (new/full moon). Neap tides (lowest range): Moon and Sun at 90° (quarter moons).",keywords:["tide","spring tide","neap tide","lunar","tidal force","high tide","low tide"]},{term:"Solar System",def:"Inner rocky planets: Mercury, Venus, Earth, Mars. Outer gas giants: Jupiter, Saturn. Ice giants: Uranus, Neptune. Asteroid belt between Mars and Jupiter. Kuiper Belt beyond Neptune (contains Pluto). Oort Cloud: distant source of comets. Comets: icy bodies with tails pointing away from the Sun.",keywords:["solar system","planet","asteroid belt","kuiper belt","oort cloud","comet","dwarf planet","jupiter"]},{term:"Stellar Evolution",def:"Stars form in nebulae via gravitational collapse. Main sequence: hydrogen fusion in core. H-R diagram: luminosity vs temperature; main sequence is diagonal band. After H is exhausted: expands to red giant. Low-mass stars → white dwarf. High-mass stars → supernova → neutron star or black hole.",keywords:["star","main sequence","red giant","white dwarf","neutron star","black hole","supernova","h-r diagram","stellar evolution"]},{term:"Galaxies & Cosmology",def:"Milky Way: barred spiral galaxy; Sun is ~26,000 ly from center. Galaxy types: spiral, elliptical, irregular. Hubble's Law: v = H₀d (galaxies recede proportional to distance). Big Bang: universe ≈ 13.8 billion years old; supported by cosmic microwave background radiation and element abundances.",keywords:["galaxy","milky way","hubble","big bang","cosmology","universe","cosmic microwave background","redshift"]},{term:"Fossils & Paleontology",def:"Fossils form when organisms are buried in sediment and minerals replace organic material. Index fossils: widespread, short time span; used for correlation and dating. Relative dating: using rock layers (stratigraphy); law of superposition: lower layers are older. Absolute dating uses radioactive isotopes (C-14, U-238).",keywords:["fossil","index fossil","stratigraphy","superposition","relative dating","carbon-14","paleontology"]},{term:"Carbon Cycle",def:"Carbon moves between atmosphere (CO₂), biosphere (photosynthesis/respiration), hydrosphere (dissolved CO₂), and lithosphere (fossil fuels, limestone). Photosynthesis removes CO₂; respiration and combustion release it. Ocean is a major carbon sink. Human burning of fossil fuels increases atmospheric CO₂.",keywords:["carbon cycle","carbon dioxide","photosynthesis carbon","respiration carbon","carbon sink","greenhouse gas","fossil fuel carbon"]},{term:"El Niño & La Niña",def:"El Niño (ENSO warm phase): weakening of trade winds causes warm Pacific water to spread east → increased rainfall in South America, droughts in Australia/SE Asia. La Niña (cool phase): stronger trade winds → cooler eastern Pacific. Affects global weather patterns every 2–7 years.",keywords:["el nino","la nina","enso","trade wind","pacific","climate pattern","sea surface temperature"]},{term:"Cloud Formation & Precipitation",def:"Clouds form when moist air rises and cools to the dew point, condensing around condensation nuclei. Types: cirrus (high, wispy), stratus (low, layered, fog), cumulus (puffy, fair weather), cumulonimbus (thunderstorm). Precipitation types: rain, snow, sleet, hail. Orographic lift: mountains force air upward.",keywords:["cloud","condensation","dew point","cumulus","stratus","cumulonimbus","precipitation type","orographic"]},{term:"Groundwater",def:"Water stored in aquifers (permeable rock layers). Water table: upper surface of saturated zone. Recharge occurs where precipitation infiltrates permeable surface. Artesian wells: water under pressure; rises without pumping. Karst topography forms from dissolution of limestone by slightly acidic groundwater (sinkholes, caves).",keywords:["groundwater","aquifer","water table","artesian","karst","sinkhole","infiltration"]},{term:"Moon Phases",def:"The Moon orbits Earth in ~29.5 days (synodic period). Phases depend on the angle between the Moon, Earth, and Sun. New moon → waxing crescent → first quarter → waxing gibbous → full moon → waning gibbous → third quarter → waning crescent. Lunar eclipses: Earth's shadow on Moon (full moon). Solar eclipses: Moon between Earth and Sun (new moon).",keywords:["moon phase","full moon","new moon","lunar eclipse","solar eclipse","waxing","waning","synodic"]},{term:"Earth's Magnetic Field",def:"Generated by convection currents in the liquid outer core (geodynamo). Magnetic poles are not aligned with geographic poles (magnetic declination). Magnetosphere deflects solar wind (charged particles); protects life from radiation. Magnetic pole reversals are recorded in oceanic crust — evidence for seafloor spreading.",keywords:["magnetic field","geodynamo","magnetosphere","magnetic pole","magnetic declination","solar wind","seafloor spreading"]},{term:"Biomes & Climate Zones",def:"Biomes are large regions defined by climate and dominant vegetation. Tropical rainforest (high T, high rainfall), savanna (wet/dry seasons), desert (low rainfall, hot or cold), temperate forest (seasonal), taiga/boreal forest (cold, conifers), tundra (permafrost, treeless). Determined by latitude, altitude, and ocean currents.",keywords:["biome","tropical rainforest","tundra","desert biome","taiga","temperate forest","climate zone","permafrost"]},{term:"Seafloor Spreading",def:"New oceanic crust forms at mid-ocean ridges as magma rises and solidifies. Crust moves away from ridge, becomes older and denser, and eventually subducts at ocean trenches. Magnetic striping in oceanic crust records polarity reversals, providing key evidence. Explains why ocean floor is younger than continental crust.",keywords:["seafloor spreading","mid-ocean ridge","oceanic crust","magnetic striping","subduction","plate movement"]},{term:"Soil Formation & Types",def:"Soil forms from weathered parent rock + organic matter (humus) over thousands of years. Soil horizons: O (organic litter), A (topsoil, humus-rich), B (subsoil, leached minerals accumulate), C (partially weathered parent rock), R (bedrock). Soil texture: sand (coarse), silt (medium), clay (fine, holds water and nutrients). Loam (mixture of all three) is best for agriculture. Soil pH affects nutrient availability. Erosion and compaction degrade soil quality.",keywords:["soil","soil horizon","topsoil","humus","soil texture","loam","clay","silt","sand","soil formation","parent rock"]},{term:"Ocean Waves & Tsunamis",def:"Wind-driven surface waves: energy travels through water, not water itself; circular orbital motion of water decreases with depth. Wave height, period, and wavelength determined by wind speed, fetch, and duration. Tsunamis: generated by submarine earthquakes, landslides, or volcanic eruptions; long wavelength (~200 km), low amplitude in deep ocean, but slow and tall near shore (shoaling). Travel at speeds up to 800 km/h; warning systems detect via ocean buoys.",keywords:["ocean wave","tsunami","wavelength wave","shoaling","surface wave","earthquake wave","wave height","fetch","wave period"]},{term:"Climate Change Evidence",def:"Key evidence: rising global average temperatures (+1.1°C since pre-industrial); declining Arctic sea ice and glacial retreat; rising sea levels (thermal expansion + ice melt, ~3.6 mm/yr); ocean acidification (CO₂ + H₂O → H₂CO₃); shifting species ranges; earlier spring phenology. Ice cores from Greenland/Antarctica provide 800,000-year records of CO₂ and temperature. Attribution studies link warming to human GHG emissions (95%+ scientific consensus).",keywords:["climate change","global warming","co2 evidence","sea level rise","ice core","ocean acidification","arctic ice","greenhouse gas evidence"]},{term:"Milankovitch Cycles",def:"Long-term periodic variations in Earth's orbit and orientation that drive ice ages. Eccentricity (~100,000 yr cycle): changes in orbital ellipticity. Axial tilt/obliquity (~41,000 yr): tilt varies from 22.1° to 24.5°; greater tilt → more extreme seasons. Precession (~26,000 yr): wobble of Earth's rotation axis like a spinning top. Combinations of cycles control when ice sheets advance and retreat. Glacial-interglacial cycles correspond to Milankovitch periods confirmed by ocean sediment cores.",keywords:["milankovitch","eccentricity","obliquity","precession","ice age cycle","orbital cycle","glacial interglacial","earth orbit"]},{term:"Ozone Layer",def:"Ozone (O₃) in the stratosphere (15–35 km) absorbs harmful UV-B and UV-C radiation. Formation: O₂ + UV → 2O; O + O₂ → O₃. Depletion: chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs) release Cl radicals in stratosphere; Cl + O₃ → ClO + O₂ (catalytic destruction). Antarctic ozone hole forms each spring (polar stratospheric clouds + sunlight). Montreal Protocol (1987) phased out CFCs; ozone is slowly recovering. UV-B damage: skin cancer, cataracts, ecosystem harm.",keywords:["ozone","stratosphere","uv radiation","cfc","chlorofluorocarbon","ozone hole","montreal protocol","ozone depletion"]},{term:"River Systems & Hydrology",def:"Drainage basin (watershed): land area draining to a single river system. Stream discharge Q = A × v (cross-sectional area × velocity). Erosion: faster water in outer bends; deposition in inner bends → meanders develop. Oxbow lakes form when meanders are cut off. Floodplains: flat fertile areas beside rivers built by sediment deposition. Alluvial fans: fan-shaped deposits where streams enter flat areas. Deltas form where rivers slow and deposit sediment into standing water.",keywords:["river","watershed","drainage basin","meander","oxbow lake","floodplain","delta","alluvial fan","discharge","erosion river"]},{term:"Mass Wasting",def:"Downslope movement of rock, soil, and debris under gravity. Types by speed and water content: creep (slow, imperceptible soil movement), earthflow (saturated soil, slow), mudflow/lahar (volcanic mudflow; fast, fluid), debris avalanche (dry, rapid), rockslide/rockfall (sudden failure of bedrock). Triggers: heavy rainfall, earthquakes, undercutting, removal of vegetation, freeze-thaw. Angle of repose: maximum slope angle at which unconsolidated material is stable (~34° for dry sand).",keywords:["mass wasting","landslide","creep","mudflow","lahar","rockslide","debris flow","angle of repose","gravity erosion"]},{term:"Hadley Cells & Atmospheric Circulation",def:"Hadley cells: tropical convection cells where warm air rises at equator (ITCZ), spreads poleward, cools, and sinks at ~30° latitude → subtropical deserts. Ferrel cells: mid-latitudes (30°–60°), surface winds blow poleward. Polar cells: cold air sinks at poles, flows toward 60°. Trade winds: surface winds in Hadley cells blow toward equator (easterlies). Westerlies: dominant mid-latitude surface winds. Jet streams: fast upper-level winds at boundaries between cells.",keywords:["hadley cell","ferrel cell","polar cell","itcz","trade winds","westerlies","jet stream","atmospheric circulation","subtropical desert"]},{term:"Isostasy",def:"Principle that Earth's crust floats in gravitational equilibrium on the denser mantle (like an iceberg in water). Thick continental crust has a deep 'root' extending into mantle; mountains have deeper roots. Glacial isostatic rebound: land rises after removal of glacier weight (Scandinavia is still rising ~1 cm/yr since last ice age). Isostatic adjustment occurs because mantle behaves like a viscous fluid on long timescales.",keywords:["isostasy","isostatic rebound","crust mantle","continental root","glacial rebound","mantle viscosity","buoyancy crust"]},{term:"Coriolis Effect",def:"Apparent deflection of moving objects on a rotating Earth. In Northern Hemisphere: objects deflect to the right. In Southern Hemisphere: to the left. Caused by the difference in rotational speed at different latitudes. Affects: wind patterns (cyclones rotate counterclockwise in NH, clockwise in SH), ocean gyres, long-range projectiles, atmospheric jets. Does NOT significantly affect bathtub drains (too small scale). Coriolis acceleration: a = 2v × Ω.",keywords:["coriolis effect","coriolis force","deflection","rotation earth","cyclone direction","northern hemisphere","southern hemisphere","wind deflection"]},{term:"Remote Sensing & GPS",def:"Remote sensing: gathering information about Earth's surface from a distance (satellites, aircraft). Passive sensors detect reflected sunlight (multispectral, hyperspectral imagery). Active sensors emit their own energy: radar (uses microwave pulses; works through clouds), LiDAR (laser pulses; measures elevation precisely). GPS: 24+ satellites; receiver calculates position from time delays of signals from ≥4 satellites; accuracy to meters or centimeters (differential GPS).",keywords:["remote sensing","gps","satellite","radar","lidar","multispectral","passive sensor","active sensor","positioning"]},{term:"Nebular Hypothesis",def:"Theory of solar system formation: a rotating cloud (nebula) of gas and dust collapsed under gravity ~4.6 billion years ago. Conservation of angular momentum caused it to spin faster and flatten into a protoplanetary disk. Center accreted into the proto-Sun; heat ignited nuclear fusion. Rocky planets formed close to the Sun (high temperatures prevented gas/ice retention); gas giants formed farther out (abundant volatiles). Planetesimals grew by accretion; impacts during Late Heavy Bombardment (~3.8 Ga) shaped inner solar system.",keywords:["nebular hypothesis","protoplanetary disk","accretion","solar system formation","planetesimal","protostar","late heavy bombardment","angular momentum solar"]},{term:"Acid Rain & Air Pollution",def:"Acid rain: precipitation with pH < 5.6 due to SO₂ (from burning sulfur-rich coal, volcanoes) and NOₓ (combustion, lightning) reacting with water to form H₂SO₄ and HNO₃. Effects: acidifies lakes (harms aquatic life), leaches nutrients from soil, corrodes stone and metals. Smog: photochemical (NOₓ + VOCs + UV → ozone at ground level) or industrial (SO₂ + particulates). Clean Air Act (US) reduced acid rain by scrubbing SO₂ from power plant emissions.",keywords:["acid rain","sulfur dioxide","nitrogen oxides","so2","nox","smog","air pollution","photochemical smog","clean air act"]},{term:"Star Life Cycles",def:"Protostar → main sequence (hydrogen fusion, stable). Low/medium mass (like Sun): main sequence → red giant (H shell burning, He core) → planetary nebula → white dwarf (electron degeneracy pressure). High mass stars: main sequence → red supergiant → Type II supernova → neutron star (pulsar if rotating) or black hole (if >3 solar masses). H-R diagram: luminosity vs. surface temperature; main sequence is diagonal band; giants upper right; white dwarfs lower left.",keywords:["stellar evolution","main sequence","red giant","white dwarf","supernova","neutron star","black hole","h-r diagram","protostar","planetary nebula"]},{level:"MS",term:"Earth's Layers",def:"Crust: thin, rocky outer layer (oceanic crust is thinner and denser than continental crust). Mantle: largest layer; hot, solid rock that flows slowly (convection drives plate movement). Outer core: liquid iron-nickel; generates Earth's magnetic field. Inner core: solid iron-nickel; hottest part. Evidence from seismic waves (P and S waves).",keywords:["crust","mantle","outer core","inner core","earth layer","seismic wave","magnetic field","convection"]},{level:"MS",term:"Rock Cycle (Basic)",def:"Igneous rocks: formed when magma or lava cools (granite = slow cooling; basalt = fast cooling). Sedimentary rocks: formed from compacted and cemented sediments (sandstone, limestone, shale). Metamorphic rocks: changed by heat and pressure (marble from limestone; quartzite from sandstone). Any rock type can become another through the rock cycle.",keywords:["rock cycle","igneous","sedimentary","metamorphic","magma","lava","granite","limestone","marble"]},{level:"MS",term:"Plate Tectonics (Basic)",def:"Earth's crust is divided into large plates that move slowly (a few centimeters per year) driven by convection in the mantle. Convergent boundaries: plates collide (form mountains or trenches). Divergent boundaries: plates pull apart (form rift valleys or mid-ocean ridges). Transform boundaries: plates slide past each other (earthquakes). Evidence: fit of continents, fossil distribution, magnetic striping.",keywords:["plate tectonics","plate","convergent","divergent","transform","mantle convection","earthquake","volcano"]},{level:"MS",term:"Weather & Atmosphere",def:"Atmosphere: layers of gas held by gravity. Troposphere (lowest): where weather occurs; temperature decreases with altitude. Stratosphere: contains the ozone layer (absorbs UV radiation). Weather is the short-term state of the atmosphere; climate is the long-term average. Water vapor, clouds, and wind transfer energy in the atmosphere. Air masses and fronts cause weather changes.",keywords:["atmosphere","troposphere","stratosphere","ozone","weather","climate","air mass","front","humidity"]},{level:"MS",term:"Water Cycle",def:"The continuous movement of water through Earth's systems. Evaporation: liquid water becomes water vapor (heat from Sun drives this). Transpiration: plants release water vapor. Condensation: water vapor cools and forms clouds around condensation nuclei. Precipitation: water falls as rain, snow, sleet, or hail. Runoff and infiltration return water to oceans and groundwater.",keywords:["water cycle","evaporation","condensation","precipitation","transpiration","runoff","infiltration","groundwater"]},{level:"MS",term:"Solar System (Basic)",def:"The Sun (a star) is at the center. Eight planets in order: Mercury, Venus, Earth, Mars (inner, rocky), Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus, Neptune (outer, gas/ice giants). Asteroid belt between Mars and Jupiter. Comets are icy bodies with long orbits around the Sun. Pluto is a dwarf planet in the Kuiper Belt. Planets orbit the Sun due to gravity.",keywords:["solar system","planet","sun","mercury","venus","earth","mars","jupiter","saturn","asteroid","comet"]},{level:"MS",term:"Moon & Eclipses",def:"The Moon orbits Earth in about 29.5 days. Moon phases are caused by the relative positions of the Sun, Earth, and Moon: new moon → crescent → quarter → gibbous → full. Lunar eclipse: Earth's shadow falls on the Moon (full moon). Solar eclipse: Moon blocks the Sun's light from reaching Earth (new moon). The Moon's gravity causes tides.",keywords:["moon","lunar eclipse","solar eclipse","moon phase","new moon","full moon","tide","orbit","waxing","waning"]},{level:"MS",term:"Weathering & Erosion (Basic)",def:"Weathering: breaking down rocks. Mechanical weathering: rock breaks into smaller pieces without chemical change (freeze-thaw, root growth, abrasion). Chemical weathering: minerals in rock change (acid rain dissolves limestone, rusting of iron-rich rock). Erosion: transport of weathered material by water, wind, ice, or gravity. Deposition: sediment is dropped when the agent slows.",keywords:["weathering","erosion","mechanical","chemical weathering","deposition","sediment","acid rain","freeze thaw"]},{level:"MS",term:"Minerals & Rocks",def:"Minerals are naturally occurring, inorganic solids with a definite chemical composition and crystal structure. Identified by hardness (Mohs scale, 1–10), color, luster (shiny or dull), streak, cleavage, and specific gravity. Rocks are mixtures of minerals. Most common minerals: quartz, feldspar, mica. Diamond is the hardest mineral (10); talc is the softest (1).",keywords:["mineral","rock","mohs","hardness","quartz","feldspar","luster","cleavage","streak","crystal"]},{level:"MS",term:"Volcanoes (Basic)",def:"Volcanoes form where magma (molten rock) reaches Earth's surface. Most occur at plate boundaries or over hot spots (like Hawaii). Lava: magma that reaches the surface. Pyroclastic material: fragments of rock and ash ejected during eruption. Types: shield volcanoes (broad, gentle slopes, runny lava, less explosive — Hawaii); stratovolcanoes/composite (steep, explosive, thick lava — Mt. St. Helens, Mt. Fuji). Volcanic gases: steam, CO₂, SO₂. Lahars are dangerous volcanic mudflows. Volcanic ash can affect climate by blocking sunlight.",keywords:["volcano","magma","lava","eruption","shield volcano","stratovolcano","pyroclastic","lahar","hot spot","volcanic ash"]},{level:"MS",term:"Earthquakes (Basic)",def:"Earthquakes: sudden shaking of Earth's crust caused by the release of energy stored in rocks under stress. Fault: fracture in rock where movement occurs. Focus (hypocenter): underground point where earthquake originates. Epicenter: point on Earth's surface directly above the focus. Seismic waves: P-waves (compressional, fastest, travel through solids and liquids) and S-waves (shear, only through solids). Surface waves cause most damage. Richter scale (or moment magnitude): measures energy released. Most earthquakes occur at plate boundaries.",keywords:["earthquake","fault","epicenter","focus","seismic wave","p-wave","s-wave","richter scale","plate boundary earthquake","tectonic"]},{level:"MS",term:"Seasons & Earth's Tilt",def:"Seasons are caused by Earth's 23.5° axial tilt relative to its orbital plane, NOT by Earth's distance from the Sun. When the Northern Hemisphere tilts toward the Sun → summer (more direct sunlight, more hours of daylight, more energy per area). Tilted away → winter. Solstices: June 21 (summer in NH, winter in SH); December 21 (winter in NH, summer in SH). Equinoxes: ~March 20 and September 22 (equal day and night; neither hemisphere tilted toward Sun). Tropics of Cancer and Capricorn: 23.5°N and S.",keywords:["seasons","axial tilt","summer solstice","winter solstice","equinox","northern hemisphere","southern hemisphere","direct sunlight","23.5 degrees"]},{level:"MS",term:"Day, Night & Time Zones",def:"Day and night are caused by Earth's rotation on its axis (one rotation = 24 hours). The side facing the Sun experiences day; the opposite side experiences night. Earth rotates from west to east (counterclockwise viewed from north pole) → Sun appears to rise in the east and set in the west. Earth is divided into 24 time zones, each 15° of longitude wide (360° / 24 hours). The International Date Line (180° longitude) marks where the date changes. The prime meridian (0° longitude) passes through Greenwich, England.",keywords:["day night","rotation","time zone","international date line","prime meridian","sunrise sunset","24 hours rotation","longitude time"]},{level:"MS",term:"Ocean Layers & Zones",def:"Sunlight zone (epipelagic, 0–200 m): receives sunlight; most photosynthesis and marine life. Twilight zone (mesopelagic, 200–1000 m): dim light; bioluminescent organisms. Midnight zone (bathypelagic, 1000–4000 m): no light; cold, high pressure. Abyssal zone (4000–6000 m): near-freezing, extreme pressure; unique organisms at hydrothermal vents. Hadal zone: ocean trenches (>6000 m). The ocean covers 71% of Earth's surface; average depth ~3,800 m; deepest point: Mariana Trench (~11,000 m). Salinity: ~3.5% (mostly NaCl).",keywords:["ocean zone","epipelagic","mesopelagic","bathypelagic","abyssal","hadal","sunlight zone","hydrothermal vent","mariana trench","ocean depth"]},{level:"MS",term:"Rivers, Lakes & Wetlands",def:"Rivers: freshwater flowing downhill due to gravity; carry sediment; form canyons, valleys, deltas. Tributaries: smaller streams flowing into a larger river. Watershed/drainage basin: all land draining to a river. Lakes: inland bodies of standing water. Eutrophication: excess nutrients → algal blooms → oxygen depletion → dead zones. Wetlands (marshes, swamps, bogs): transitional between aquatic and terrestrial; extremely productive; filter pollutants, store floodwater, provide habitat. The Amazon is the world's largest river by discharge volume.",keywords:["river","lake","wetland","tributary","watershed","eutrophication","marsh","swamp","delta river","erosion deposition river"]},{level:"MS",term:"Deserts & Arid Regions",def:"Deserts receive less than 25 cm of precipitation per year. Hot deserts (Sahara, Arabian): extreme daytime heat, cold nights, sand dunes and rock formations. Cold deserts (Gobi, Antarctica): cold temperatures; Antarctica is the largest and driest desert on Earth. Desert organisms: adapted for water conservation (cacti: store water in thick stems, deep/wide roots; camels: fatty humps, water-efficient kidneys). Desertification: expansion of desert due to overgrazing, deforestation, and climate change. Oases: areas with water sources in deserts.",keywords:["desert","arid","sahara","hot desert","cold desert","desertification","cactus adaptation","oasis","sand dune","water conservation desert"]},{level:"MS",term:"Stars & the Sun (Basic)",def:"The Sun is a medium-sized star (yellow dwarf; spectral type G) about 150 million km from Earth. It is a giant ball of hot plasma held together by gravity. Energy produced by nuclear fusion in the core (hydrogen → helium). Layers: core, radiative zone, convective zone, photosphere (visible surface, ~5,500°C), chromosphere, corona (outermost, millions of °C). Sunspots: cooler dark regions on surface (magnetic activity). Solar flares and coronal mass ejections (CMEs) can disrupt Earth's magnetic field and communication systems.",keywords:["sun","star","nuclear fusion sun","photosphere","sunspot","solar flare","corona","yellow dwarf","stellar structure","plasma"]},{level:"MS",term:"Solar System Objects",def:"Planets: orbit the Sun, have cleared their orbital neighborhood. Rocky/terrestrial (inner): Mercury, Venus, Earth, Mars — small, dense, few moons. Gas giants (outer): Jupiter, Saturn — large, low density, many moons, ring systems. Ice giants: Uranus, Neptune — contain ices (water, ammonia, methane). Dwarf planets: Pluto, Eris, Ceres (in asteroid belt). Asteroid belt: between Mars and Jupiter; mostly rock and metal. Kuiper Belt: icy objects beyond Neptune. Comets: icy nuclei; form two tails (ion tail away from Sun; dust tail along orbit) when near Sun.",keywords:["solar system","terrestrial planet","gas giant","ice giant","dwarf planet","asteroid belt","kuiper belt","comet tail","pluto","saturn ring"]},{level:"MS",term:"Space Exploration",def:"Key missions: Sputnik (1957, first satellite, USSR), Yuri Gagarin (1961, first human in space, USSR), Apollo 11 (1969, first Moon landing, Neil Armstrong & Buzz Aldrin). Mars rovers: Curiosity, Perseverance. Hubble Space Telescope: launched 1990, orbits Earth, images deep space. James Webb Space Telescope (2021): infrared observations, images early universe. International Space Station (ISS): research laboratory in low Earth orbit. Voyager probes: now in interstellar space. Private companies (SpaceX, Blue Origin) advancing rocket technology.",keywords:["space exploration","sputnik","apollo 11","moon landing","mars rover","hubble telescope","iss","neil armstrong","voyager","satellite history"]},{level:"MS",term:"Atmosphere Composition & Air Pressure",def:"Earth's atmosphere is ~78% nitrogen (N₂), ~21% oxygen (O₂), ~0.93% argon (Ar), ~0.04% carbon dioxide (CO₂), plus trace gases and water vapor. Air has mass → exerts pressure on everything below it. Atmospheric pressure decreases with altitude (less air above). Measured with a barometer; standard pressure = 1 atm = 101,325 Pa = 760 mmHg. High pressure areas: air sinks → clear weather. Low pressure areas: air rises → clouds and precipitation. Isobars: lines of equal pressure on weather maps.",keywords:["atmosphere composition","nitrogen oxygen","air pressure","barometer","altitude pressure","high low pressure","isobar","atmospheric pressure"]},{level:"MS",term:"Wind & Pressure Systems",def:"Wind: movement of air from high pressure to low pressure areas. Local winds: sea breeze (land heats faster than water → air rises over land → sea air flows in; reverses at night as land breeze). Mountain and valley breezes. Global wind patterns: trade winds (blow from subtropical high-pressure zones toward equator), westerlies (mid-latitudes), polar easterlies. Beaufort scale: measures wind speed. Jet streams: fast high-altitude air currents that steer weather systems. Coriolis effect: deflects winds to the right in NH, left in SH.",keywords:["wind","pressure gradient","sea breeze","trade wind","westerlies","polar easterlies","jet stream","beaufort scale","coriolis basic","wind direction"]},{level:"MS",term:"Humidity & Clouds",def:"Humidity: amount of water vapor in air. Relative humidity: ratio of water vapor present to maximum possible at that temperature (expressed as %); 100% = saturated. Dew point: temperature at which air cools to saturation and condensation begins. Clouds form when rising air cools to the dew point, and water vapor condenses around tiny particles (condensation nuclei: dust, pollen). Cloud types: cumulus (puffy, fair weather), stratus (flat layers, overcast), cirrus (high, wispy, ice crystals), cumulonimbus (thunderstorm clouds — tall, dark, anvil-shaped).",keywords:["humidity","relative humidity","dew point","condensation nuclei","cumulus","stratus","cirrus","cumulonimbus","cloud formation basic","saturation air"]},{level:"MS",term:"Severe Weather",def:"Thunderstorms: form from cumulonimbus clouds; lightning (static discharge between clouds or cloud to ground) and thunder (shock wave from rapid air expansion). Hail: ice pellets formed in strong updrafts. Tornadoes: violently rotating column of air extending from cumulonimbus cloud to ground; most common in 'Tornado Alley' (central US); rated by Fujita/Enhanced Fujita scale (EF0–EF5). Hurricanes/typhoons: large rotating tropical storms (sustained winds >119 km/h); form over warm ocean water (≥26°C); rated Category 1–5 (Saffir-Simpson scale); lose strength over land.",keywords:["thunderstorm","lightning","tornado","hurricane","fujita scale","saffir-simpson","severe weather","cumulonimbus severe","tornado alley","tropical storm"]},{level:"MS",term:"Natural Resources",def:"Natural resources: materials from Earth used by humans. Renewable resources: naturally replenished on human timescales (solar energy, wind, water, biomass, soil). Non-renewable resources: form over millions of years; limited supply (fossil fuels — coal, oil, natural gas; mineral ores). Inexhaustible resources: essentially unlimited (sunlight, wind). Conservation: using resources wisely to prevent depletion. Recycling: reprocessing materials (aluminum, glass, plastic, paper) reduces need for new resources. Sustainable development: meets present needs without compromising future generations' ability to meet their needs.",keywords:["natural resources","renewable resource","non-renewable resource","conservation resource","recycling","sustainable development","fossil fuel resource","mineral ore"]},{level:"MS",term:"Fossils (Basic)",def:"Fossils: preserved remains or traces of ancient organisms. Types: body fossils (preserved hard parts: bones, shells, teeth), trace fossils (footprints, burrows, tracks), mold (cavity left by organism), cast (mold filled with minerals), amber (organism preserved in tree resin), petrification (minerals replace organic material). Index fossils: organisms that lived during short, well-defined time periods; used to date rock layers and correlate strata across regions. Law of Superposition: in undisturbed layers, lower layers are older. Relative vs absolute dating.",keywords:["fossil","body fossil","trace fossil","petrification","mold cast","index fossil","superposition law","relative dating basic","amber fossil","stratigraphy basic"]},{level:"MS",term:"Maps & Earth Science Tools",def:"Topographic maps: show elevation using contour lines (lines connecting points of equal elevation); closely spaced contour lines = steep slope; V-shaped contours pointing uphill indicate valleys. GPS: uses satellites to determine latitude, longitude, and altitude. Latitude: degrees north or south of equator (0°–90°). Longitude: degrees east or west of prime meridian (0°–180°). Seismographs detect and record seismic waves. Weather instruments: thermometer (temperature), barometer (pressure), anemometer (wind speed), rain gauge (precipitation), hygrometer (humidity).",keywords:["topographic map","contour line","latitude","longitude","gps basic","seismograph","weather instrument","anemometer","barometer basic","map reading"]},{level:"MS",term:"Soil Erosion & Conservation",def:"Soil erosion: removal of topsoil by water, wind, or ice. Water erosion: surface runoff carries soil; more severe on steep slopes without vegetation. Wind erosion: common in dry, barren areas (Dust Bowl, 1930s USA). Loss of topsoil reduces agricultural productivity. Conservation methods: contour plowing (plowing along hillside contour lines to slow runoff), terracing (cut flat steps into hillside), windbreaks (rows of trees block wind), cover crops (plants protect soil when fields are bare), no-till farming (leaving crop residues to hold soil), reforestation.",keywords:["soil erosion","topsoil","runoff erosion","wind erosion","dust bowl","contour plowing","terracing","windbreak","cover crop","conservation farming"]},{level:"MS",term:"Deforestation & Habitat Loss",def:"Deforestation: large-scale removal of forests. Causes: agriculture (mainly for cattle and soybeans in Amazon), logging, urban expansion, road building. Consequences: loss of biodiversity (forests contain ~50% of all species), increased carbon dioxide (trees store carbon; burning/decomposing releases CO₂), soil erosion and flooding (tree roots hold soil, absorb water), disruption of water cycle (less transpiration → less rainfall in some regions). Amazon rainforest: largest tropical forest; major carbon sink; often called 'lungs of the Earth'.",keywords:["deforestation","habitat loss","amazon rainforest","biodiversity loss","carbon sink forest","logging","slash burn","reforestation","carbon storage trees"]},{level:"MS",term:"Global Warming (Basic)",def:"Global warming: long-term increase in Earth's average surface temperature. Caused by enhanced greenhouse effect: burning fossil fuels (coal, oil, natural gas) → releases CO₂ → traps more heat. Evidence: rising global temperatures, melting glaciers and Arctic ice, rising sea levels, extreme weather events becoming more frequent. Effects: more intense hurricanes, droughts, heat waves, flooding of coastal cities, coral bleaching, shifts in species ranges. Solutions: reducing fossil fuel use, switching to renewable energy, reforestation, energy efficiency improvements.",keywords:["global warming basic","climate change basic","greenhouse effect basic","co2 temperature","fossil fuel warming","melting ice","sea level rise basic","coral bleaching"]},{level:"MS",term:"Geologic Time (Basic)",def:"Earth is approximately 4.6 billion years old. Geologic time is divided into eons, eras, periods, and epochs. Major eras: Paleozoic (541–252 million years ago — invertebrates, fish, amphibians, reptiles, forests), Mesozoic (252–66 Mya — dinosaurs, first birds and mammals; ended with mass extinction), Cenozoic (66 Mya–present — mammals dominant, eventually humans). Relative dating: using rock layers to determine order of events (older layers below). Absolute dating: using radioactive decay to determine actual age in years (radiometric dating).",keywords:["geologic time","paleozoic","mesozoic","cenozoic","era","dinosaur era","mass extinction basic","relative dating","absolute dating","4.6 billion years"]},{level:"MS",term:"Continental Drift",def:"Alfred Wegener (1912) proposed that continents were once joined in a supercontinent called Pangaea and have since drifted apart. Evidence: fit of continents (South America and Africa fit together), matching fossils on different continents (Mesosaurus found in both South America and Africa), matching rock formations across oceans, glacial striations in tropical regions. Mechanism (not understood in Wegener's time): seafloor spreading and plate tectonics driven by mantle convection. Pangaea began breaking apart ~175–200 million years ago.",keywords:["continental drift","pangaea","wegener","plate movement","matching fossils","mesosaurus","seafloor spreading basic","supercontinent","mantle convection basic"]},{level:"MS",term:"Tsunamis & Coastal Hazards",def:"Tsunamis: series of large ocean waves generated by sudden displacement of the ocean floor, usually by submarine earthquakes, landslides, or volcanic eruptions. In deep ocean: long wavelength (~200 km), low wave height (~1 m), travel at ~800 km/h. Near shore: wavelength decreases, height increases dramatically (shoaling). Warning signs: earthquake, then sea withdrawal before waves arrive. Coastal hazards: storm surge (hurricane pushes ocean inland), coastal erosion, sea level rise. Seawalls, mangrove forests, and early warning systems help protect coastlines.",keywords:["tsunami","submarine earthquake","shoaling","wave height increase","storm surge","coastal erosion","warning system","seismic sea wave","mangrove coastal"]},{level:"MS",term:"Mountain Formation",def:"Mountains form in several ways. Fold mountains: two continental plates collide, crust buckles and folds upward (Himalayas — India-Asia collision; Alps — Africa-Europe). Fault-block mountains: blocks of crust lifted or tilted along faults (Sierra Nevada). Dome mountains: magma pushes up crust without erupting (Black Hills). Volcanic mountains: lava builds up over hotspot or subduction zone (Cascade Range, Andes). Erosion by water, wind, and ice sculpts mountain shapes over millions of years. Highest peak: Mt. Everest (8,849 m), Himalayan range.",keywords:["fold mountain","fault block mountain","dome mountain","volcanic mountain","himalaya","collision mountain","mt everest","mountain formation","tectonic mountain"]},{level:"MS",term:"Ocean Circulation & Climate",def:"Surface ocean currents: driven by global winds; gyres rotate clockwise in NH, counterclockwise in SH (Coriolis effect). Warm currents (Gulf Stream) bring heat from tropics to higher latitudes, warming nearby land (Western Europe is warmer than equivalent latitude in North America). Cold currents bring nutrients upward (upwelling), supporting fisheries. Thermohaline circulation (ocean conveyor belt): driven by density differences (cold, salty water sinks in North Atlantic; drives global ocean mixing). El Niño: weakening of trade winds warms eastern Pacific, affecting global weather patterns.",keywords:["ocean current","gyre","gulf stream","thermohaline circulation","upwelling","el nino basic","surface current","warm current","cold current","ocean climate"]},{level:"MS",term:"Ozone & Atmosphere Protection",def:"The ozone layer in the stratosphere (15–35 km above Earth) absorbs most of the Sun's harmful ultraviolet (UV) radiation. UV-B causes sunburn, skin cancer, cataracts, and harms marine ecosystems. CFCs (chlorofluorocarbons — used in old refrigerators and aerosol sprays) destroy ozone catalytically. An 'ozone hole' forms over Antarctica each spring. Montreal Protocol (1987): international agreement that phased out CFC production; ozone layer is slowly recovering. Sunscreen blocks UV radiation from reaching skin.",keywords:["ozone layer","uv radiation basic","cfc basic","ozone hole basic","stratosphere ozone","montreal protocol basic","skin cancer uv","uv protection","ozone recovery"]},{level:"MS",term:"Geologic Features",def:"Canyon: deep, steep-sided valley carved by a river (Grand Canyon — carved by Colorado River over ~5-6 million years). Cave/cavern: underground opening formed by chemical weathering of limestone by slightly acidic groundwater (karst topography; stalactites hang from ceiling — 'c' for ceiling; stalagmites grow up from floor — 'g' for ground). Geyser: hot spring that periodically erupts with steam and water (Yellowstone; water heated by magma). Sinkhole: collapse of ground above a cave. Arch: erosion creates natural rock bridge.",keywords:["canyon","cave","stalactite","stalagmite","geyser","sinkhole","karst","grand canyon","yellowstone","natural arch","geologic feature"]},{level:"MS",term:"Latitude, Climate & Biomes",def:"Climate is primarily determined by latitude (distance from equator). Near equator (0°–23.5°): tropical climate — hot year-round, high solar energy input. Subtropical (~23.5°–35°): hot, dry — deserts (Sahara, Australian Outback). Mid-latitudes (35°–60°): temperate — four seasons; forests and grasslands. Subarctic (60°–66.5°): boreal forest (taiga) — cold winters, cool summers. Arctic/Antarctic circles (66.5°+): tundra and ice sheets — very cold, permafrost. Altitude also affects climate: higher elevation → colder, similar to higher latitude. Ocean proximity moderates temperatures.",keywords:["latitude climate","tropical climate","subtropical","temperate climate","subarctic","arctic","altitude climate","biome latitude","climate zone basic"]}]},Energy:{color:"var(--orange)",icon:"☢️",items:[{term:"Conservation of Energy",def:"First Law of Thermodynamics: energy cannot be created or destroyed — only converted between forms. Total energy of an isolated system is constant. Forms include kinetic, gravitational potential, elastic potential, thermal, chemical, electrical, radiant, and nuclear energy.",keywords:["conservation of energy","first law","energy conversion","isolated system"]},{term:"Nuclear Fission",def:"Heavy nucleus (U-235, Pu-239) absorbs a neutron and splits into lighter nuclei + 2–3 neutrons + energy. Released neutrons can trigger more fissions (chain reaction). Requires critical mass. Used in nuclear reactors (controlled, moderated by water or graphite) and atomic bombs (uncontrolled).",keywords:["fission","nuclear","uranium","plutonium","chain reaction","neutron","reactor"]},{term:"Nuclear Fusion",def:"Light nuclei (deuterium + tritium, hydrogen isotopes) combine to form helium-4 + a neutron + enormous energy. Releases ~3–4× more energy per mass than fission. Powers stars via the proton-proton chain. Requires extreme temperatures (>10⁷ K) to overcome Coulomb repulsion. Tokamak reactors pursue controlled fusion.",keywords:["fusion","deuterium","tritium","tokamak","plasma","thermonuclear","proton-proton"]},{term:"Fossil Fuels",def:"Coal (compressed ancient plants, highest carbon content, most CO₂/energy), petroleum (marine organisms; refined to gasoline, diesel, jet fuel), natural gas (mainly CH₄, cleanest-burning). All release CO₂ and other pollutants on combustion, driving the enhanced greenhouse effect. Non-renewable on human timescales.",keywords:["fossil fuel","coal","petroleum","natural gas","methane","combustion","carbon dioxide","greenhouse"]},{term:"Photovoltaic Effect",def:"Photons strike a silicon p-n junction semiconductor, exciting electrons across the band gap and producing direct current (DC). Inverters convert DC to AC. Typical panel efficiency: 15–22%. The photoelectric effect (Einstein, 1905) is the quantum basis. Output scales with light intensity and angle.",keywords:["photovoltaic","solar cell","solar panel","semiconductor","silicon","pv cell","direct current"]},{term:"Wind Energy",def:"Wind turbines convert kinetic energy of wind to rotational energy via blades, then to electricity via generator. Betz limit: maximum theoretical efficiency = 59.3% (can never capture all wind energy). Offshore wind is stronger and more consistent. Power output scales with the cube of wind speed (P ∝ v³).",keywords:["wind turbine","wind energy","betz","wind power","generator","rotor blade"]},{term:"Thermodynamic Efficiency",def:"No heat engine can be 100% efficient (2nd Law). Carnot efficiency (maximum theoretical): η = 1 − Tc/Th (temperatures in Kelvin). Real engines are always less than Carnot. COP (coefficient of performance) for refrigerators: COP = Qc/W. For heat pumps: COP = Qh/W.",keywords:["carnot","efficiency","heat engine","cop","thermal efficiency","second law"]},{term:"Hydropower",def:"Converts gravitational PE of water to electricity via turbines and generators. Power P = ρghQ. Pumped-storage: pump water uphill when energy is cheap; release to generate on demand — acts as a grid-scale battery. Run-of-river vs reservoir (dam) types. Largest renewable electricity source globally.",keywords:["hydropower","dam","turbine","water power","pumped storage","hydroelectric","potential energy"]},{term:"Second Law of Thermodynamics",def:"Entropy of an isolated system always increases (or stays the same). Heat flows spontaneously from hot to cold. No process is 100% efficient — some energy is always lost as waste heat. Clausius statement: heat cannot spontaneously flow from cold to hot. Arrow of time is defined by entropy increase.",keywords:["second law","entropy increase","heat flow","irreversible","clausius","disorder"]},{term:"Heat Transfer",def:"Conduction: heat transfer through direct contact; rate depends on thermal conductivity, area, temperature difference, and thickness (Fourier's Law). Convection: heat carried by fluid movement; drives ocean circulation and weather. Radiation: electromagnetic waves (infrared); requires no medium; described by Stefan-Boltzmann Law (P = σεAT⁴).",keywords:["conduction","convection","radiation heat","thermal conductivity","heat transfer","infrared radiation","stefan boltzmann"]},{term:"Geothermal Energy",def:"Heat from Earth's interior (radioactive decay + residual heat from formation). Used directly for heating or to generate electricity (steam drives turbines). Geothermal power plants require high-temperature geothermal reservoirs (e.g., Iceland, Kenya, Geysers in California). Baseload renewable — consistent output unlike solar/wind.",keywords:["geothermal","earth heat","geothermal energy","geothermal power","radioactive decay heat","baseload"]},{term:"Tidal Energy",def:"Harnesses energy from tidal changes in sea level. Tidal barrages: dam-like structures capture potential energy of tidal range. Tidal stream generators: underwater turbines in tidal currents (like underwater wind turbines). Predictable unlike solar/wind. Limited to coastal regions with large tidal ranges (e.g., Bay of Fundy).",keywords:["tidal energy","tidal barrage","tidal stream","tide energy","tidal power","bay of fundy"]},{term:"Biomass & Biofuels",def:"Biomass: organic material (wood, crop waste, animal waste) burned directly or converted to biogas/biofuels. Ethanol: fermented from sugars/starches (corn, sugarcane). Biodiesel: made from vegetable oils/animal fats via transesterification. Biogas (mostly CH₄) from anaerobic digestion. Carbon-neutral if sustainably sourced.",keywords:["biomass","biofuel","ethanol","biodiesel","biogas","fermentation","anaerobic digestion"]},{term:"Hydrogen Fuel Cells",def:"Electrochemical device that converts H₂ and O₂ directly to electricity + water (2H₂ + O₂ → 2H₂O + electricity). Anode: H₂ oxidized, releases electrons. Cathode: O₂ reduced with electrons + H⁺. Efficiency ~40–60%, higher than combustion. Zero emissions at point of use. Hydrogen must be produced (electrolysis or steam reforming).",keywords:["fuel cell","hydrogen","electrochemical","electrolysis","proton exchange membrane","clean energy"]},{term:"Energy Storage & Batteries",def:"Lithium-ion batteries: Li⁺ ions move between anode (graphite) and cathode (LiCoO₂) through electrolyte. High energy density. Pumped hydro: largest grid storage. Flow batteries: electrolyte stored in tanks (scalable). Supercapacitors: fast charge/discharge, lower energy density. Storage critical for intermittent renewables.",keywords:["battery","lithium ion","energy storage","pumped hydro","supercapacitor","grid storage","rechargeable"]},{term:"Greenhouse Effect",def:"Solar radiation (shortwave) passes through atmosphere and warms Earth's surface. Earth re-radiates longwave infrared radiation, which is absorbed and re-emitted by greenhouse gases (CO₂, CH₄, H₂O, N₂O, ozone). Enhanced greenhouse effect: human-emitted CO₂ from fossil fuels increases warming above natural levels.",keywords:["greenhouse effect","greenhouse gas","co2","global warming","infrared","climate change","carbon dioxide"]},{term:"Carbon Capture & Sequestration",def:"CCS captures CO₂ from power plants or atmosphere and stores it underground in geological formations, depleted oil/gas fields, or mineralizes it. Direct air capture (DAC): pulls CO₂ directly from ambient air. Bioenergy with CCS (BECCS) could achieve negative emissions. High cost limits widespread deployment.",keywords:["carbon capture","ccs","sequestration","direct air capture","dac","negative emissions","co2 storage"]},{term:"Radioactive Decay",def:"Unstable nuclei emit particles/energy spontaneously. Alpha (α): emits ²He nucleus (A−4, Z−2); stopped by paper. Beta-minus (β⁻): neutron → proton + electron; stopped by metal foil. Gamma (γ): high-energy photon; requires lead shielding. Half-life (t½): time for half the nuclei to decay; used in radiometric dating.",keywords:["radioactive decay","alpha decay","beta decay","gamma radiation","half-life decay","decay constant"]},{term:"Energy Units & Conversions",def:"Joule (J): SI unit of energy. 1 calorie = 4.184 J. 1 kWh = 3.6×10⁶ J. 1 BTU ≈ 1055 J. 1 eV = 1.6×10⁻¹⁹ J. Power: 1 Watt = 1 J/s; 1 horsepower = 746 W. Energy content of fuels measured in MJ/kg (hydrogen: 142 MJ/kg; gasoline: 46 MJ/kg; coal: ~30 MJ/kg).",keywords:["joule","kilowatt hour","btu","energy unit","calorie","electron volt","energy conversion unit"]},{term:"Power Transmission & Grid",def:"Power is transmitted at high voltage to minimize resistive losses (P_loss = I²R; high V → low I for same power). Step-up transformers increase voltage for transmission; step-down at substations reduce for consumers. AC (alternating current) used because transformers only work with AC. DC transmission used for some long-distance high-voltage links.",keywords:["power grid","transformer","transmission","ac current","dc current","high voltage","power loss","substation"]},{term:"Nuclear Waste",def:"High-level waste (HLW): spent nuclear fuel; highly radioactive, requires deep geological disposal (stable for 10,000+ years). Low-level waste: contaminated tools/clothing. Spent fuel rods cooled in water pools first, then dry cask storage. Reprocessing extracts remaining fissile material (France, Russia) but creates proliferation concerns.",keywords:["nuclear waste","spent fuel","high-level waste","radioactive waste","dry cask","geological disposal"]},{term:"Energy Efficiency",def:"Efficiency = useful energy output / total energy input × 100%. LED bulbs: ~90% efficient (vs ~5% for incandescent). Electric vehicles: ~77% tank-to-wheel vs ~20% for gasoline. Insulation reduces conduction heat losses in buildings. ENERGY STAR ratings. Cogeneration (CHP): captures waste heat for useful heating.",keywords:["energy efficiency","led","insulation","cogeneration","heat pump efficiency","energy star","waste heat"]},{term:"Entropy",def:"Measure of disorder or randomness in a system (S, units: J/K). 2nd Law: ΔS_universe ≥ 0 for any process. Entropy increases when: ice melts, gas expands, heat flows from hot to cold. Mixing increases entropy. Boltzmann's definition: S = k·ln(W) where W is the number of microstates. Low entropy states are less probable.",keywords:["entropy","disorder","boltzmann","microstates","second law entropy","entropy increase","thermodynamic entropy"]},{term:"Renewable vs Non-Renewable",def:"Renewables replenish on human timescales: solar, wind, hydro, geothermal, tidal, biomass. Non-renewables: fossil fuels (coal, oil, gas) and nuclear (uranium is finite). Renewables have near-zero marginal fuel cost but high capital cost. Wind and solar have intermittency challenges requiring storage or backup. Global energy still ~80% from fossil fuels.",keywords:["renewable energy","non-renewable","solar wind hydro","energy source","sustainable energy","fossil fuel vs renewable"]},{term:"Ocean Thermal Energy Conversion",def:"OTEC exploits temperature differences between warm surface water (~25°C) and cold deep water (~5°C) to run a heat engine. Low Carnot efficiency (~3–5%) but uses a continuous, renewable resource. Three types: closed-cycle (ammonia as working fluid), open-cycle (flash steam), hybrid. Best near tropical coastlines.",keywords:["otec","ocean thermal","ocean energy","temperature difference","heat engine ocean","tropical energy"]},{term:"Nuclear Reactor Design",def:"Nuclear reactors convert fission energy to electricity. Core components: fuel rods (enriched U-235 or Pu-239 pellets), moderator (slows neutrons to thermal energies; water, heavy water, or graphite), control rods (absorb neutrons; boron or cadmium; adjust reaction rate), coolant (removes heat; water, CO₂, or liquid sodium). Pressurized Water Reactor (PWR): most common; primary loop heats secondary loop via heat exchanger. Boiling Water Reactor (BWR): steam generated directly in core.",keywords:["nuclear reactor","fuel rod","moderator","control rod","coolant","pwr","bwr","fission reactor","enriched uranium","nuclear power plant"]},{term:"Electric Vehicles & Energy",def:"EVs use electric motors powered by lithium-ion battery packs (typically 40–100 kWh). Regenerative braking recovers kinetic energy as electricity. Energy efficiency: ~77% tank-to-wheel vs ~20% for gasoline ICE. Well-to-wheel emissions depend on electricity grid mix. Range anxiety: addressed by expanding charging infrastructure (Level 1/2 AC and Level 3 DC fast charging). Battery degradation: ~2% capacity loss per year. Solid-state batteries promise higher energy density.",keywords:["electric vehicle","ev","battery pack","regenerative braking","lithium ion ev","charging","range anxiety","energy efficiency ev","solid state battery"]},{term:"Smart Grid & Demand Response",def:"Smart grid: modernized electricity network using digital communication to improve reliability and efficiency. Two-way communication between utilities and consumers. Advanced metering infrastructure (AMI): real-time usage monitoring and dynamic pricing. Demand response: consumers reduce load during peak periods in exchange for incentives. Enables integration of distributed renewables and EVs. Microgrids: self-sufficient local grids that can disconnect from main grid (island mode) during outages.",keywords:["smart grid","demand response","advanced metering","microgrid","distributed energy","peak demand","grid modernization","two-way grid"]},{term:"Internal Combustion Engine",def:"Four-stroke cycle (Otto cycle): intake (piston down, fuel-air mixture in), compression (piston up, mixture compressed), power (spark ignites mixture, piston driven down), exhaust (piston up, combustion gases expelled). Diesel cycle: fuel ignites by compression heat (no spark plug); higher compression ratio → higher efficiency (~45% vs ~25% for gasoline). Engine efficiency limited by Carnot theorem. Emissions: CO, NOₓ, hydrocarbons, CO₂, particulates. Catalytic converter reduces CO and NOₓ.",keywords:["internal combustion engine","otto cycle","diesel cycle","four stroke","compression ratio","catalytic converter","combustion engine","spark plug"]},{term:"Thermoelectric Generators",def:"Seebeck effect: when two dissimilar conductors are joined and junction temperatures differ, a voltage is produced. V = S·ΔT where S = Seebeck coefficient. Peltier effect (reverse): current through junction creates temperature difference (used in cooling modules). Figure of merit ZT = S²σT/κ (σ = electrical conductivity; κ = thermal conductivity); high ZT materials are good thermoelectrics. Applications: spacecraft radioisotope thermoelectric generators (RTGs), waste heat recovery, wearable electronics.",keywords:["seebeck effect","peltier effect","thermoelectric","rtg","figure of merit","waste heat recovery","temperature gradient voltage"]},{term:"Wave Energy & Tidal Power",def:"Wave energy converters (WECs): oscillating water column (OWC) traps air above water surface; wave compresses air through turbine. Point absorbers: floating buoy drives hydraulic pump. Overtopping devices: wave runs up ramp into reservoir, water falls through turbine. Tidal stream generators: underwater turbines (like wind turbines) in tidal currents; predictable energy output. Tidal barrage: dam across estuary captures tidal range; generates electricity on ebb and flow. Limited by suitable sites.",keywords:["wave energy","tidal stream","tidal barrage","oscillating water column","point absorber","marine energy","tidal current","wave converter"]},{term:"Carbon Footprint & Life Cycle",def:"Carbon footprint: total GHG emissions caused by an individual, organization, event, or product (measured in CO₂-equivalent). Life cycle assessment (LCA): cradle-to-grave analysis of environmental impacts, including manufacturing, use, and disposal. Scope 1: direct emissions. Scope 2: purchased electricity. Scope 3: value chain (supply chain, product use). GWP (Global Warming Potential): compares warming effect of GHGs over 100 years relative to CO₂ (CH₄ = 28 GWP; N₂O = 265 GWP).",keywords:["carbon footprint","life cycle assessment","lca","scope emissions","co2 equivalent","gwp","global warming potential","methane gwp"]},{term:"Levelized Cost of Energy (LCOE)",def:"LCOE = total lifetime costs / total lifetime energy produced ($/MWh). Accounts for capital costs (CAPEX), operating costs (OPEX), fuel costs, and financing. Allows comparison across technologies. Solar PV and onshore wind now have LCOE competitive with or below fossil fuels in many regions (~$30–50/MWh). Nuclear: high capital costs despite low fuel costs (~$90–130/MWh). Natural gas: low capital, variable fuel costs. Discount rate strongly affects LCOE of capital-intensive technologies.",keywords:["lcoe","levelized cost","capex","opex","energy cost comparison","cost of electricity","solar lcoe","wind lcoe"]},{term:"Net Zero & Carbon Neutrality",def:"Net zero: achieving a balance between GHG emissions produced and removed from the atmosphere. Requires: deep decarbonization of energy, transport, and industry; carbon removal (forests, BECCS, direct air capture). Carbon neutrality: offsetting remaining emissions with carbon credits or removals. Paris Agreement (2015): limit warming to 1.5–2°C above pre-industrial levels; 195+ countries. IPCC reports summarize climate science and mitigation pathways. Carbon trading: cap-and-trade systems put a price on emissions.",keywords:["net zero","carbon neutral","paris agreement","ipcc","decarbonization","carbon removal","carbon trading","cap and trade","1.5 degrees"]},{term:"Fuel Cell Types",def:"PEM (proton exchange membrane): uses solid polymer electrolyte; operates at ~80°C; used in vehicles and portable power. SOFC (solid oxide fuel cell): operates at 700–1000°C; high efficiency; used in stationary power; can use various fuels (H₂, methane). Alkaline fuel cell (AFC): used in spacecraft (Apollo); uses KOH electrolyte. Phosphoric acid fuel cell (PAFC): first commercial fuel cell. MCFC (molten carbonate): high temperature; suitable for industrial use. Efficiency typically 40–60%.",keywords:["fuel cell","pem fuel cell","sofc","alkaline fuel cell","proton exchange membrane","solid oxide","hydrogen fuel cell","fuel cell types"]},{term:"Energy Storage: Pumped Hydro & Flywheels",def:"Pumped hydro storage (PHS): 90% of global grid storage capacity; pumps water uphill during low-demand periods, releases through turbines when needed. Round-trip efficiency ~70–85%. Flywheel energy storage: kinetic energy stored in rotating mass; charge/discharge in seconds; high power density, low energy density; used for frequency regulation. Compressed air energy storage (CAES): stores air in underground caverns under pressure; efficiency ~70%. All address intermittency of solar and wind.",keywords:["pumped hydro","flywheel","compressed air","grid storage","caes","energy storage pumped","round trip efficiency","frequency regulation"]},{term:"Photovoltaic Technology",def:"First-generation PV: monocrystalline silicon (highest efficiency, ~22–26%), polycrystalline silicon (~17–20%). Second-generation thin films: CdTe (cadmium telluride, ~18%), CIGS (copper indium gallium selenide, ~23%). Third-generation: perovskite solar cells (rapidly improving, >29% in lab); multi-junction concentrator cells (>47% in lab). Shockley-Queisser limit: theoretical max efficiency for single-junction solar cell ~33%. Agrivoltaics: combining solar panels with agriculture.",keywords:["photovoltaic","monocrystalline","polycrystalline","thin film","perovskite","cdte","cigs","solar efficiency","shockley queisser","pv technology"]},{term:"First Law of Thermodynamics",def:"Energy conservation for thermodynamic systems: ΔU = Q − W. ΔU = change in internal energy; Q = heat added to system (positive when absorbed); W = work done by system (positive when system expands). For ideal gas: U depends only on temperature (ΔU = nCᵥΔT). Isothermal process: ΔT = 0, ΔU = 0 → Q = W. Adiabatic: Q = 0 → ΔU = −W. Isochoric (constant volume): W = 0 → ΔU = Q. Isobaric (constant pressure): W = PΔV.",keywords:["first law thermodynamics","internal energy","heat work","isothermal","adiabatic","isochoric","isobaric","delta u","thermodynamic process"]},{term:"Piezoelectric & Magnetohydrodynamic Energy",def:"Piezoelectric effect: certain crystals (quartz, PZT) generate voltage when mechanically stressed; used in sensors, lighters, ultrasound, and energy harvesting from vibrations/footsteps. Magnetohydrodynamic (MHD) generators: conducting fluid (plasma or liquid metal) flows through magnetic field → induces EMF (no moving parts). Used experimentally in nuclear fusion containment and propulsion. Triboelectric nanogenerators: harvest energy from friction between surfaces.",keywords:["piezoelectric","pzt","quartz","magnetohydrodynamic","mhd","energy harvesting","triboelectric","vibration energy","fluid conductor"]},{term:"Zeroth Law & Temperature Scales",def:"Zeroth Law: if system A is in thermal equilibrium with B, and B is in equilibrium with C, then A is in equilibrium with C — establishes temperature as a measurable property. Celsius (°C): 0 = ice point, 100 = steam point at 1 atm. Kelvin (K): absolute scale, 0 K = absolute zero (−273.15°C); no negative values. Fahrenheit (°F): °F = (°C × 9/5) + 32. Rankine (°R): absolute Fahrenheit scale. Triple point of water: 273.16 K = 0.01°C (defines kelvin).",keywords:["zeroth law","thermal equilibrium","kelvin","celsius","fahrenheit","absolute zero","temperature scale","triple point water"]},{level:"MS",term:"Forms of Energy",def:"Energy exists in many forms: kinetic (motion), gravitational potential (stored due to height), elastic potential (stored in springs/rubber), thermal (heat, related to temperature), chemical (stored in chemical bonds; released by combustion or metabolism), electrical (moving charges), radiant/light (electromagnetic waves), sound (mechanical vibrations), nuclear (stored in atomic nuclei).",keywords:["kinetic energy","potential energy","thermal energy","chemical energy","electrical energy","radiant energy","nuclear energy","energy forms"]},{level:"MS",term:"Energy Transformations",def:"Energy can change from one form to another but is never created or destroyed (Law of Conservation of Energy). Examples: a light bulb converts electrical energy to light and heat; a car engine converts chemical energy to kinetic energy and heat; a solar panel converts radiant energy to electrical energy. Some energy is always lost as heat in any transformation.",keywords:["energy transformation","conservation of energy","conversion","heat","light bulb","solar panel","engine","efficiency"]},{level:"MS",term:"Renewable vs Non-Renewable (Basic)",def:"Renewable energy sources can be replenished naturally in a short time: solar (sunlight), wind, hydroelectric (flowing water), geothermal (Earth's heat), biomass (organic matter). Non-renewable sources form over millions of years and will eventually run out: coal, oil, natural gas (fossil fuels), and nuclear (uranium). Fossil fuels release CO₂ when burned, contributing to climate change.",keywords:["renewable","non-renewable","fossil fuel","solar","wind","hydroelectric","coal","oil","natural gas","climate change"]},{level:"MS",term:"Fossil Fuels (Basic)",def:"Fossil fuels — coal, oil (petroleum), and natural gas — formed from the remains of ancient plants and animals over millions of years under heat and pressure. Coal is burned in power plants to generate electricity. Oil is refined into gasoline, diesel, and other fuels. Natural gas (mostly methane, CH₄) is the cleanest-burning fossil fuel. All release CO₂ when burned.",keywords:["fossil fuel","coal","oil","petroleum","natural gas","methane","combustion","co2","carbon dioxide"]},{level:"MS",term:"Solar & Wind Energy (Basic)",def:"Solar energy comes from the Sun as light and heat. Solar panels (photovoltaic cells) convert sunlight directly to electricity. Solar water heaters use sunlight to heat water. Wind energy: wind turbines use blades to capture wind's kinetic energy and drive a generator to produce electricity. Both are renewable, produce no direct emissions, and are increasingly cost-competitive.",keywords:["solar energy","solar panel","wind energy","wind turbine","photovoltaic","renewable","generator","clean energy"]},{level:"MS",term:"Heat Transfer (Basic)",def:"Conduction: heat transfers through direct contact between molecules (metal rod in a flame). Convection: heat transfers through the movement of fluids (warm air rises, cool air sinks; boiling water). Radiation: heat transfers as electromagnetic waves without needing matter (heat from the Sun, warmth from a campfire). Insulators slow conduction; reflectors reduce radiation absorption.",keywords:["conduction","convection","radiation","heat transfer","insulator","conductor","thermal energy","temperature"]},{level:"MS",term:"Electricity Generation",def:"Most electricity is generated by spinning a turbine connected to a generator. Turbines can be spun by steam (heated by burning fossil fuels, nuclear fission, or geothermal heat) or by moving water (hydroelectric) or wind. Generators work by electromagnetic induction — rotating a coil in a magnetic field induces a current. The electricity is then transmitted over power lines.",keywords:["electricity generation","turbine","generator","electromagnetic induction","hydroelectric","steam","power plant","fossil fuel"]},{level:"MS",term:"Greenhouse Effect & Climate",def:"The greenhouse effect: sunlight warms Earth's surface; Earth radiates heat (infrared) back upward; greenhouse gases (CO₂, water vapor, methane) absorb and re-radiate this heat, warming the lower atmosphere. The natural greenhouse effect makes Earth habitable. Human activities (burning fossil fuels, deforestation) increase CO₂ levels, enhancing the greenhouse effect and raising global temperatures.",keywords:["greenhouse effect","greenhouse gas","co2","climate change","global warming","carbon dioxide","methane","fossil fuel","atmosphere"]},{level:"MS",term:"Energy in Living Systems",def:"All living things need energy to survive. Producers (plants, algae) capture sunlight energy via photosynthesis and store it as chemical energy in glucose. When organisms eat food, cellular respiration breaks down glucose to release ATP (energy that cells can use). Energy flows through ecosystems in a food chain: sun → producers → primary consumers → secondary consumers → tertiary consumers. Only about 10% of energy transfers between each trophic level (the rest is lost as heat). Energy cannot be recycled — unlike matter, it flows in one direction through ecosystems.",keywords:["energy living systems","atp basic","food chain energy","trophic level energy","10 percent rule","energy flow","chemical energy food","producer energy"]},{level:"MS",term:"Coal Formation & Uses",def:"Coal formed from ancient swamp plants (mainly ferns and mosses) that were buried under sediment ~300 million years ago during the Carboniferous period; heat and pressure transformed them over millions of years. Types by carbon content: lignite (lowest, 'brown coal'), sub-bituminous, bituminous (most common), anthracite (highest, hardest). Used mainly for electricity generation and steel production (coke from coal is used in blast furnaces). Burning coal releases CO₂, SO₂ (acid rain), NOₓ, mercury, and particulate matter. World's largest coal reserves: USA, Russia, Australia, China.",keywords:["coal formation","carboniferous","lignite","bituminous","anthracite","coal burning","electricity coal","so2 coal","fossil fuel formation","coal type"]},{level:"MS",term:"Oil & Natural Gas (Basic)",def:"Oil (petroleum) and natural gas formed from marine organisms (plankton, algae) buried under ocean sediments millions of years ago; heat and pressure converted organic matter to hydrocarbons. Trapped in porous rock beneath impermeable cap rock (petroleum traps). Extracted by drilling; offshore oil rigs drill under the ocean. Oil refining: crude oil is heated and separated by boiling point (fractional distillation) into gasoline, diesel, jet fuel, kerosene, lubricants, plastics. Natural gas (mainly methane, CH₄) is the cleanest-burning fossil fuel but is a potent greenhouse gas if released unburned (methane leaks).",keywords:["oil formation","petroleum","natural gas basic","marine organism","fractional distillation","crude oil","oil refining","methane basic","petroleum trap","offshore drilling"]},{level:"MS",term:"Solar Energy (Detailed Basic)",def:"The Sun releases energy through nuclear fusion (hydrogen → helium). Solar energy reaches Earth as electromagnetic radiation (mainly visible light and infrared). Passive solar: designing buildings to capture sunlight for heating (south-facing windows, thermal mass). Active solar: solar water heaters use the Sun to heat water in panels. Photovoltaic (PV) cells: semiconductor materials convert sunlight directly into electricity; no moving parts; produce DC current (inverter converts to AC). Solar farms: large arrays of panels; increasingly cost-competitive. Concentrated solar power (CSP): mirrors focus sunlight to heat fluid and drive a steam turbine.",keywords:["solar energy basic","passive solar","active solar","photovoltaic basic","pv panel","solar farm","concentrated solar","solar water heater","dc to ac inverter"]},{level:"MS",term:"Wind Energy (Basic)",def:"Wind is caused by uneven heating of Earth's surface by the Sun → creates pressure differences → air flows from high to low pressure. Wind turbines: three blades (aerodynamic design — similar to airplane wings) capture wind's kinetic energy; blades spin a shaft connected to a generator; produces electricity. Onshore vs offshore wind (stronger, more consistent offshore but more expensive to build). A typical large wind turbine can power ~500 homes. Wind farms: many turbines in an area with consistently strong winds. Wind does not produce any air or water pollution during operation. Intermittent — doesn't blow all the time.",keywords:["wind energy basic","wind turbine basic","wind farm","onshore offshore wind","aerodynamic blade","intermittent energy","kinetic energy wind","wind generator"]},{level:"MS",term:"Hydroelectric Power (Basic)",def:"Hydroelectric power uses the energy of falling or flowing water to generate electricity. A dam stores water in a reservoir (creating potential energy). Water flows through intake pipes → spins turbine → drives generator → produces electricity. The height the water falls (head) and the flow rate determine power output. Largest renewable electricity source globally (~16% of world electricity). Advantages: no fuel costs, no air emissions, long-lasting, can store energy (pumped storage). Disadvantages: floods habitats, blocks fish migration, displaces communities, dependent on rainfall. Three Gorges Dam (China) is the world's largest hydroelectric station.",keywords:["hydroelectric basic","dam","reservoir","water turbine","head","pumped storage basic","three gorges dam","fish migration dam","renewable electricity source"]},{level:"MS",term:"Energy Conservation at Home",def:"Reducing energy use saves money and reduces environmental impact. Lighting: LED bulbs use ~75% less electricity than incandescent bulbs and last much longer. Insulation: prevents heat loss in winter and heat gain in summer (walls, attic, double-glazed windows). Thermostat: programmable thermostats reduce heating/cooling when not needed. Appliances: ENERGY STAR-rated appliances are more efficient. Phantom load/standby power: electronics use electricity even when 'off' — unplugging reduces waste. Transportation: walking, cycling, carpooling, public transit reduce fuel consumption. Renewable energy: rooftop solar panels can supply home electricity.",keywords:["energy conservation home","led bulb","insulation energy","thermostat energy","energy star","phantom load","standby power","renewable home","energy efficiency home"]},{level:"MS",term:"Geothermal Energy (Basic)",def:"Geothermal energy comes from heat inside Earth, generated by radioactive decay of elements and residual heat from Earth's formation. In geothermal hot spots (Iceland, Yellowstone, Kenya), hot water or steam can be accessed by drilling. Geothermal power plants: steam from hot water underground drives turbines to generate electricity. Geothermal heat pumps: even in non-volcanic areas, ground temperature stays ~10–15°C year-round; heat pumps use this to heat buildings in winter and cool in summer. Advantages: reliable (baseload — produces power 24/7), low emissions, small land footprint. Disadvantages: location-specific.",keywords:["geothermal basic","earth heat basic","geothermal power plant","geothermal heat pump","hot spring","drilling geothermal","baseload renewable","iceland geothermal","radioactive decay heat basic"]},{level:"MS",term:"Biomass Energy (Basic)",def:"Biomass: organic material from plants and animals that can be burned or converted to fuel. Direct combustion: burning wood, crop waste, or animal dung for heat or electricity (oldest energy source). Biogas: decomposition of organic waste (manure, food scraps) by bacteria without oxygen (anaerobic digestion) produces methane → can be burned for heat/electricity. Ethanol: fermented from sugars/starches (sugarcane, corn) → blended with gasoline (E10, E85). Biodiesel: made from vegetable oils or animal fats → used in diesel engines. Biomass is considered renewable but still releases CO₂ when burned (net neutral if sustainably managed).",keywords:["biomass basic","biofuel basic","ethanol basic","biodiesel basic","biogas basic","anaerobic digestion basic","fermentation fuel","wood burning","crop waste energy"]},{level:"MS",term:"Batteries (Basic)",def:"A battery converts chemical energy to electrical energy. Consists of one or more electrochemical cells, each with: anode (negative terminal, where oxidation occurs), cathode (positive terminal, where reduction occurs), and electrolyte (allows ions to flow between electrodes). Primary batteries: not rechargeable (alkaline, zinc-carbon — used in TV remotes, flashlights). Secondary batteries: rechargeable — chemical reaction reversed by applying current (lithium-ion used in phones/laptops/EVs; lead-acid used in cars; nickel-metal hydride). Voltage: energy per unit charge; larger batteries don't have higher voltage — they have more capacity (amp-hours).",keywords:["battery basic","anode cathode basic","primary battery","secondary battery","rechargeable","lithium ion basic","lead acid","alkaline battery","electrochemical cell basic"]},{level:"MS",term:"Energy Units & Measurement (Basic)",def:"Energy is measured in Joules (J) in the SI system. 1 calorie (cal) = 4.18 J (amount of heat to raise 1 g of water by 1°C). Food energy uses Calories (Cal) = kilocalories (kcal) = 1000 cal. Electricity is billed in kilowatt-hours (kWh): 1 kWh = 3,600,000 J. Power (rate of energy use) measured in Watts (W): 1 W = 1 J/s. A 60W light bulb uses 60 J every second. 1 kilowatt (kW) = 1,000 W. 1 megawatt (MW) = 1,000,000 W. Example: a typical home uses about 900 kWh per month. Horsepower (hp): 1 hp = 746 W.",keywords:["joule","calorie energy","kilowatt hour","watt basic","energy unit basic","kWh","power unit","horsepower basic","megawatt","food calorie"]},{level:"MS",term:"Electric Motors & Generators",def:"Electric motor: converts electrical energy to mechanical (kinetic) energy. Works because current-carrying wire in a magnetic field experiences a force (motor effect). Used in fans, washing machines, electric vehicles, tools. Generator: converts mechanical energy to electrical energy. Works by electromagnetic induction — rotating a coil of wire in a magnetic field induces a current (Faraday's Law). Power plants use generators. Dynamo: simple DC generator. AC generators (alternators) produce alternating current used in homes. Motors and generators are essentially the same device working in reverse.",keywords:["electric motor basic","generator basic","motor effect","electromagnetic induction basic","faraday basic","mechanical to electrical","electrical to mechanical","ac generator","dynamo"]},{level:"MS",term:"Transformers & Power Transmission (Basic)",def:"Transformers change the voltage of alternating current (AC). Step-up transformer: increases voltage, decreases current (used at power plants before long-distance transmission). Step-down transformer: decreases voltage, increases current (used at substations before homes). Electricity is transmitted at high voltage (e.g., 230,000 V) to minimize energy loss in wires (P_loss = I²R; high voltage → low current → less heat loss). Home voltage: typically 120 V (USA) or 230 V (Europe). Transformers only work with AC, not DC. Ratio of coil turns determines voltage change: Vp/Vs = Np/Ns.",keywords:["transformer basic","step up transformer","step down transformer","power transmission basic","high voltage transmission","energy loss wire","ac transformer","home voltage","coil turns ratio basic"]},{level:"MS",term:"Energy & Transportation",def:"Transportation uses about 28% of energy in developed countries. Cars: internal combustion engines (gasoline, diesel) are ~20-25% efficient — most energy lost as heat. Electric vehicles: ~77% efficient; zero direct emissions but depend on electricity grid. Hybrid vehicles: combine gasoline engine and electric motor; use regenerative braking. Fuel efficiency measured in miles per gallon (mpg) or liters per 100 km. Airplanes are very fuel-intensive per trip but similar per passenger-kilometer to driving alone. Trains are most energy-efficient for passengers and freight. Shipping large quantities by sea is very efficient per ton-km.",keywords:["energy transportation","gasoline engine efficiency","electric vehicle efficiency","hybrid vehicle","fuel efficiency mpg","train efficiency","airplane energy","regenerative braking basic"]},{level:"MS",term:"Insulators & Conductors (Energy)",def:"Thermal conductors: materials that allow heat to transfer easily; high thermal conductivity; metals (copper, aluminum, iron) are good conductors (loosely bound electrons carry heat). Thermal insulators: materials that resist heat transfer; low conductivity; wood, plastic, fiberglass, air gaps, wool, styrofoam. Air is an excellent insulator (low thermal conductivity) — this is why double-paned windows and down jackets work well. Electrical conductors: metals. Electrical insulators: rubber, plastic, glass. Semiconductors: conduct under some conditions (silicon) — used in solar cells and electronics. R-value: measures insulation effectiveness (higher = better).",keywords:["thermal conductor","thermal insulator","electrical conductor","electrical insulator","r-value","semiconductor basic","double pane window","metal conductor","air insulator","fiberglass insulation"]},{level:"MS",term:"Photosynthesis as Energy Storage",def:"Photosynthesis is the process by which plants, algae, and cyanobacteria convert light energy into chemical energy stored as glucose. The Sun's energy drives the reaction: 6CO₂ + 6H₂O + light → C₆H₁₂O₆ + 6O₂. Glucose stores chemical energy that can be released later by cellular respiration (in the same plant) or by the animals that eat the plant. Fossil fuels are essentially ancient photosynthesis energy — they are the compressed remains of organisms that stored solar energy millions of years ago. This makes fossil fuels a form of stored solar energy.",keywords:["photosynthesis energy storage","glucose chemical energy","light energy stored","fossil fuel ancient solar","cellular respiration releases","solar energy stored food","chemical energy plants"]},{level:"MS",term:"Carbon Cycle & Energy",def:"Carbon cycles through the atmosphere, biosphere, hydrosphere, and lithosphere. In terms of energy: plants absorb CO₂ and store carbon as organic compounds (powered by sunlight). Animals eat plants, releasing some carbon as CO₂ through respiration. Decomposers break down dead matter, releasing CO₂. Combustion of fossil fuels releases carbon stored millions of years ago rapidly into the atmosphere. Oceans absorb about 25% of human CO₂ emissions (becoming more acidic). The carbon cycle is closely linked to energy flow because almost all organic energy-rich molecules contain carbon.",keywords:["carbon cycle energy","fossil fuel carbon release","respiration co2","photosynthesis co2 absorbed","ocean carbon sink basic","carbon energy link","organic molecule carbon","decomposer carbon"]},{level:"MS",term:"Heating & Cooling Systems",def:"Heating systems: furnaces (burn natural gas, oil, or propane to heat air); heat pumps (move heat from outside to inside, even in cold weather — very efficient); electric resistance heating (least efficient); radiant floor heating (hot water pipes in floor). Cooling systems (air conditioning): use a refrigeration cycle — refrigerant absorbs heat inside the building, compressed and cooled outside, releasing heat outside; fans circulate cooled air. COP (coefficient of performance): heat pumps and AC efficiency measure — higher COP = more heat moved per unit electricity. Proper insulation reduces both heating and cooling energy needs.",keywords:["heating system","cooling system","heat pump basic","air conditioning basic","furnace","refrigeration cycle","cop basic","radiant heating","insulation energy basic"]},{level:"MS",term:"Light Bulbs & Lighting Efficiency",def:"Incandescent bulbs: heat tungsten filament until it glows; only ~5% of energy becomes light, 95% is heat — very inefficient. CFL (compact fluorescent lamp): uses mercury vapor and phosphor coating to produce light; ~4× more efficient than incandescent. LED (light-emitting diode): semiconductors emit light when current flows through a p-n junction; ~7–10× more efficient than incandescent, lasts 15–25× longer; contains no mercury. Lumens measure light output; watts measure power consumption. Switching all incandescent bulbs to LEDs could reduce global electricity use for lighting by ~50%.",keywords:["led bulb efficiency","incandescent bulb","cfl bulb","lumens","lighting efficiency","energy saving bulb","light emitting diode basic","filament bulb","mercury cfl"]},{level:"MS",term:"Nuclear Power (Basic)",def:"Nuclear power plants use nuclear fission to generate electricity. Uranium-235 atoms split when struck by neutrons, releasing enormous energy and 2–3 more neutrons (chain reaction). In a reactor, the chain reaction is controlled (moderator and control rods). Heat produced boils water → steam → spins turbine → generates electricity. Nuclear power produces no CO₂ during operation (low-carbon electricity source). Concerns: nuclear waste (radioactive for thousands of years), risk of meltdown (Chernobyl 1986, Fukushima 2011), high cost of construction, uranium mining impacts. Provides about 10% of world's electricity.",keywords:["nuclear power basic","fission basic","chain reaction simple","uranium 235 basic","nuclear waste basic","meltdown","chernobyl","low carbon nuclear","nuclear electricity"]},{level:"MS",term:"Energy & the Environment",def:"Energy production and use have major environmental impacts. Burning fossil fuels: releases CO₂ (climate change), SO₂ (acid rain), NOₓ, mercury, and particulates (health impacts). Oil spills: damage marine ecosystems. Coal mining: strip mining destroys landscapes; mountaintop removal. Natural gas: methane leaks (powerful greenhouse gas). Renewable energy impacts: wind turbines (bird/bat strikes, noise, visual impact), solar panels (land use, manufacturing emissions), hydroelectric dams (habitat flooding, fish migration). Nuclear waste: long-term radioactive storage. Energy efficiency and renewables are key to reducing environmental damage.",keywords:["energy environment","fossil fuel impact","oil spill","coal mining","wind turbine bird","solar land use","nuclear waste environment","renewable impact","co2 energy","energy pollution"]},{level:"MS",term:"Electricity Generation Mix",def:"A country's electricity generation mix describes the sources used to produce electricity. Globally: coal (~36%), natural gas (~23%), hydroelectric (~16%), nuclear (~10%), wind (~7%), solar (~4%), other renewables and oil. Countries with high renewable shares: Iceland (nearly 100% geothermal + hydro), Norway (nearly 100% hydro), Denmark (>50% wind). USA mix: natural gas (~40%), coal (~20%), nuclear (~19%), renewables (~21%). Transitioning to cleaner sources reduces emissions. Grid reliability requires matching supply and demand at all times; storage and diverse sources help.",keywords:["electricity mix","generation mix","coal share","natural gas electricity","renewable share","nuclear share","grid reliability","energy transition","country electricity source"]},{level:"MS",term:"Conservation of Energy (Basic)",def:"The Law of Conservation of Energy states that energy cannot be created or destroyed — it can only be converted from one form to another or transferred between objects. The total energy in a closed system always remains constant. Examples: a falling ball converts PE to KE (total stays constant); burning wood converts chemical energy to heat and light; food energy converts to kinetic energy when you run. In all real processes, some energy is converted to thermal energy (heat) that is hard to use further. This is why perpetual motion machines are impossible — they would violate conservation of energy.",keywords:["conservation of energy basic","energy cannot be created","energy conversion basic","total energy constant","perpetual motion impossible","chemical to kinetic","pe to ke basic"]},{level:"MS",term:"Tidal & Wave Energy (Basic)",def:"Tides are caused by the gravitational pull of the Moon (and Sun) on Earth's oceans, creating predictable rises and falls in sea level twice a day. Tidal energy: harness this movement using tidal barrages (dam across an estuary; water flows through turbines as tide rises and falls) or tidal stream generators (underwater turbines in fast-moving tidal currents). Wave energy: ocean waves carry kinetic and potential energy from wind; wave energy converters (buoys, oscillating columns) capture this energy. Both are renewable and predictable. Limited by suitable geographic locations. Currently a small fraction of global energy.",keywords:["tidal energy basic","wave energy basic","tidal barrage basic","tidal stream basic","moon gravity tides","wave converter basic","renewable ocean energy","predictable tidal"]}]},Math:{color:"var(--cyan)",icon:"∑",items:[{term:"Quadratic Equations",def:"Form ax² + bx + c = 0. Quadratic formula: x = (−b ± √(b²−4ac)) / 2a. Discriminant Δ = b²−4ac: Δ > 0 → two real roots; Δ = 0 → one real root; Δ < 0 → two complex roots. Vertex at x = −b/2a. Sum of roots = −b/a; product of roots = c/a.",keywords:["quadratic","discriminant","quadratic formula","parabola","vertex","roots of"]},{term:"Logarithms",def:"log_b(x) = y ↔ bʸ = x. ln(x) = log_e(x). Rules: log(ab) = log a + log b; log(a/b) = log a − log b; log(aⁿ) = n·log a; log_b(1) = 0; log_b(b) = 1. Change of base: log_b(x) = ln(x)/ln(b). Inverse of exponential: b^(log_b(x)) = x.",keywords:["logarithm","log","natural log","ln","log rule","change of base"]},{term:"Trigonometry",def:"SOH-CAH-TOA: sin = opp/hyp, cos = adj/hyp, tan = opp/adj. Pythagorean identity: sin²θ + cos²θ = 1. Other identities: 1 + tan²θ = sec²θ; 1 + cot²θ = csc²θ. Law of Sines: a/sinA = b/sinB. Law of Cosines: c² = a² + b² − 2ab·cosC. Radians: 180° = π rad.",keywords:["trigonometry","sine","cosine","tangent","unit circle","radian","pythagorean identity","law of sines"]},{term:"Derivatives",def:"Instantaneous rate of change. Power rule: d/dx[xⁿ] = nxⁿ⁻¹. Product: (uv)' = u'v + uv'. Quotient: (u/v)' = (u'v − uv')/v². Chain rule: d/dx[f(g(x))] = f'(g(x))·g'(x). d/dx[sin x] = cos x; d/dx[eˣ] = eˣ; d/dx[ln x] = 1/x. Critical points where f'(x) = 0 or undefined.",keywords:["derivative","differentiation","power rule","chain rule","product rule","calculus","slope","critical point"]},{term:"Integrals",def:"Antiderivative / area under curve. Power rule: ∫xⁿdx = xⁿ⁺¹/(n+1) + C (n ≠ −1). Fundamental Theorem: ∫[a,b] f(x)dx = F(b) − F(a). Key: ∫eˣdx = eˣ + C; ∫(1/x)dx = ln|x| + C; ∫cos x dx = sin x + C; ∫sin x dx = −cos x + C. Integration by substitution and by parts.",keywords:["integral","antiderivative","integration","fundamental theorem","definite integral","area under"]},{term:"Probability & Combinations",def:"P(A) = favorable / total. P(A and B) = P(A)·P(B) for independent events. P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B) − P(A∩B). Combinations C(n,r) = n!/[r!(n−r)!] — order doesn't matter. Permutations P(n,r) = n!/(n−r)! — order matters. Conditional: P(A|B) = P(A∩B)/P(B).",keywords:["probability","combination","permutation","factorial","conditional probability","binomial"]},{term:"Sequences & Series",def:"Arithmetic: aₙ = a₁ + (n−1)d; sum Sₙ = n(a₁+aₙ)/2. Geometric: aₙ = a₁·rⁿ⁻¹; sum Sₙ = a₁(1−rⁿ)/(1−r). Infinite geometric series: S = a₁/(1−r) if |r| < 1. Fibonacci: aₙ = aₙ₋₁ + aₙ₋₂ (1,1,2,3,5,8,13,…). Telescoping series: most terms cancel.",keywords:["sequence","series","arithmetic","geometric","fibonacci","convergent","common ratio"]},{term:"Complex Numbers",def:"i = √(−1); i² = −1; i³ = −i; i⁴ = 1. Form z = a + bi. Addition: add real and imaginary parts. Multiplication: FOIL (use i² = −1). Modulus |z| = √(a²+b²). Conjugate: z̄ = a − bi; z·z̄ = |z|². Euler: e^(iθ) = cosθ + i sinθ. Division: multiply by conjugate over conjugate.",keywords:["complex number","imaginary","modulus","conjugate","euler","i^2","polar form"]},{term:"Statistics",def:"Mean μ = Σx/n. Median: middle value. Mode: most frequent. Variance σ² = Σ(x−μ)²/n. Standard deviation σ = √(variance). Normal distribution: 68–95–99.7 rule (1σ, 2σ, 3σ). Correlation r ∈ [−1, +1]. Linear regression: line of best fit. Outliers can skew mean but not median.",keywords:["mean","median","mode","standard deviation","variance","normal distribution","correlation","regression"]},{term:"Matrices",def:"Rectangular arrays of numbers. Matrix multiplication: rows × columns (NOT commutative). det of 2×2 [a b; c d] = ad − bc. Inverse A⁻¹ exists iff det ≠ 0. Identity matrix I: A·I = A. Solve systems via Gaussian elimination or Cramer's Rule. Eigenvalue λ: Av = λv (eigenvector v).",keywords:["matrix","determinant","inverse","eigenvalue","gaussian elimination","cramer","transpose"]},{term:"Vectors",def:"Quantities with magnitude and direction. Component form: v = ⟨a, b, c⟩. Magnitude |v| = √(a²+b²+c²). Dot product: u·v = |u||v|cosθ = Σuᵢvᵢ (scalar; zero if perpendicular). Cross product: u×v is perpendicular to both; |u×v| = |u||v|sinθ. Unit vector: v/|v|.",keywords:["vector","dot product","cross product","magnitude","unit vector","component","perpendicular vector"]},{term:"Limits & Continuity",def:"lim_{x→a} f(x) = L if f(x) approaches L as x → a (from both sides). L'Hôpital's Rule: for 0/0 or ∞/∞ indeterminate forms, lim f/g = lim f'/g'. Continuity at a: f(a) defined, limit exists, and lim_{x→a} f(x) = f(a). Squeeze theorem: if g(x) ≤ f(x) ≤ h(x) and g,h → L, then f → L.",keywords:["limit","continuity","l'hopital","indeterminate form","squeeze theorem","one-sided limit"]},{term:"Number Theory",def:"Prime numbers have exactly two factors: 1 and themselves. Fundamental Theorem of Arithmetic: every integer > 1 has a unique prime factorization. GCD: greatest common divisor; LCM: least common multiple; GCD × LCM = product of two numbers. Modular arithmetic: a ≡ b (mod n) means n divides (a−b). Euler's totient function φ(n).",keywords:["prime","factor","gcd","lcm","modular arithmetic","number theory","prime factorization","divisibility"]},{term:"Conic Sections",def:"Circle: (x−h)² + (y−k)² = r². Ellipse: x²/a² + y²/b² = 1 (a > b; foci at ±c where c² = a²−b²). Parabola: y = ax² + bx + c; focus/directrix definition. Hyperbola: x²/a² − y²/b² = 1; asymptotes y = ±(b/a)x. All are cross-sections of a double cone.",keywords:["conic section","ellipse","parabola","hyperbola","circle equation","focus","directrix"]},{term:"Polynomial Division",def:"Long division of polynomials mirrors long division of integers. Synthetic division: shortcut when dividing by (x − c). Remainder Theorem: dividing f(x) by (x − c) gives remainder f(c). Factor Theorem: (x − c) is a factor of f(x) iff f(c) = 0. Rational Root Theorem: rational roots of aₙxⁿ + … + a₀ are ±(factors of a₀)/(factors of aₙ).",keywords:["polynomial","synthetic division","remainder theorem","factor theorem","rational root","polynomial division"]},{term:"Functions & Transformations",def:"Domain: set of valid inputs. Range: set of outputs. Composition: (f∘g)(x) = f(g(x)). Inverse: f⁻¹ exists if f is one-to-one (passes horizontal line test); f(f⁻¹(x)) = x. Transformations: f(x) + k (vertical shift), f(x + h) (horizontal shift), af(x) (vertical stretch), f(bx) (horizontal compression).",keywords:["function","domain","range","composition","inverse function","transformation","horizontal shift","vertical shift"]},{term:"Binomial Theorem",def:"(a + b)ⁿ = Σ C(n,k) aⁿ⁻ᵏ bᵏ for k = 0 to n. The kth term (starting from 1) = C(n,k−1)·aⁿ⁻⁽ᵏ⁻¹⁾·bᵏ⁻¹. Pascal's triangle rows give the coefficients. C(n,k) = n!/[k!(n−k)!]. Used in probability distributions (binomial distribution) and approximations.",keywords:["binomial theorem","pascal triangle","binomial expansion","binomial coefficient","combination binomial"]},{term:"Set Theory",def:"Set: unordered collection of distinct elements. Union A ∪ B: elements in A or B. Intersection A ∩ B: elements in both. Complement Aᶜ: elements not in A. Empty set ∅. Subset: A ⊆ B if every element of A is in B. |A ∪ B| = |A| + |B| − |A ∩ B| (inclusion-exclusion). Venn diagrams visualize set relationships.",keywords:["set theory","union","intersection","complement","subset","empty set","venn diagram","inclusion exclusion"]},{term:"Linear Programming",def:"Optimize a linear objective function subject to linear inequality constraints. Feasible region: all points satisfying all constraints (convex polygon). Optimal solution always occurs at a vertex (corner point) of the feasible region. Used in operations research, resource allocation, and supply chain optimization.",keywords:["linear programming","objective function","constraint","feasible region","corner point","optimization","simplex"]},{term:"Differential Equations",def:"Equations involving a function and its derivatives. Separable ODEs: dy/dx = f(x)g(y) → separate and integrate. Exponential growth/decay: dy/dt = ky → y = y₀eᵏᵗ. Second-order linear ODEs model springs (y'' + ky = 0 → y = A cos√k·t + B sin√k·t). Initial conditions determine particular solutions.",keywords:["differential equation","ode","separable","exponential growth","initial condition","first order differential"]},{term:"Polar Coordinates",def:"Points described by (r, θ): r = distance from origin, θ = angle from positive x-axis. Conversion: x = r cosθ, y = r sinθ; r = √(x²+y²), θ = arctan(y/x). Circle r = a. Rose curves: r = a cos(nθ). Cardioid: r = a(1 + cosθ). Area in polar: A = ½∫r²dθ.",keywords:["polar coordinates","polar equation","r theta","cardioid","rose curve","polar area"]},{term:"Rational Functions",def:"f(x) = p(x)/q(x) where p, q are polynomials. Vertical asymptote where q(x) = 0 (and p(x) ≠ 0). Horizontal asymptote: if deg(p) < deg(q) → y = 0; deg(p) = deg(q) → y = ratio of leading coefficients; deg(p) > deg(q) → oblique asymptote. Holes where both p and q have a common factor.",keywords:["rational function","asymptote","vertical asymptote","horizontal asymptote","hole","partial fraction"]},{term:"Absolute Value & Inequalities",def:"|x| = x if x ≥ 0; −x if x < 0. |x| < a means −a < x < a. |x| > a means x > a or x < −a. Triangle inequality: |a + b| ≤ |a| + |b|. Solving quadratic inequalities: factor, find roots, test intervals. Sign chart method: track sign changes at roots and asymptotes.",keywords:["absolute value","inequality","triangle inequality","quadratic inequality","sign chart","interval notation"]},{term:"Parametric Equations",def:"Curve defined by x = f(t) and y = g(t) where t is a parameter. Eliminate the parameter to get Cartesian form. Derivative: dy/dx = (dy/dt)/(dx/dt). Arc length: L = ∫√[(dx/dt)²+(dy/dt)²] dt. Circle: x = r cosθ, y = r sinθ. Projectile: x = v₀cosθ·t, y = v₀sinθ·t − ½gt².",keywords:["parametric","parameter","parametric equation","eliminate parameter","arc length parametric"]},{term:"Graph Theory",def:"Graphs consist of vertices (nodes) and edges. Degree of vertex: number of edges connected. Euler path: visits every edge exactly once (exists if exactly 0 or 2 odd-degree vertices). Euler circuit: Euler path starting and ending at same vertex (0 odd-degree vertices). Trees: connected graphs with no cycles; n vertices, n−1 edges.",keywords:["graph theory","vertex","edge","euler path","degree","tree graph","adjacency matrix","directed graph"]},{term:"Taylor & Maclaurin Series",def:"Taylor series: f(x) = Σ f⁽ⁿ⁾(a)/n! · (x−a)ⁿ; approximates a function around point a. Maclaurin series: Taylor series centered at 0. Common Maclaurin series: eˣ = 1 + x + x²/2! + x³/3! + …; sin x = x − x³/3! + x⁵/5! − …; cos x = 1 − x²/2! + x⁴/4! − …; ln(1+x) = x − x²/2 + x³/3 − … (|x| ≤ 1). Radius of convergence determined by ratio test. Truncating gives polynomial approximations.",keywords:["taylor series","maclaurin series","power series","convergence","approximation","radius of convergence","polynomial approximation","infinite series"]},{term:"Integration Techniques",def:"U-substitution: reverse of chain rule; let u = g(x), du = g'(x)dx. Integration by parts: ∫u dv = uv − ∫v du (choose u by LIATE: Logarithm, Inverse trig, Algebraic, Trig, Exponential). Trigonometric substitution: for √(a²−x²) use x = a sinθ; for √(a²+x²) use x = a tanθ; for √(x²−a²) use x = a secθ. Partial fractions: decompose rational functions into simpler fractions before integrating. Tabular integration: efficient for repeated integration by parts.",keywords:["integration by parts","u-substitution","trig substitution","partial fractions","liate","tabular integration","integration technique"]},{term:"Multivariable Calculus",def:"Functions of multiple variables f(x, y, z). Partial derivatives: ∂f/∂x holds other variables constant. Gradient ∇f = (∂f/∂x, ∂f/∂y, ∂f/∂z): points in direction of steepest ascent. Directional derivative: rate of change in direction of unit vector û. Double integrals: ∫∫f(x,y) dA; can switch to polar coordinates. Triple integrals: volume and mass calculations. Line integrals: ∫F·dr along a curve. Green's, Stokes', and divergence theorems connect line/surface/volume integrals.",keywords:["partial derivative","gradient","multivariable","double integral","triple integral","directional derivative","green's theorem","stokes theorem","divergence theorem"]},{term:"Proof Techniques",def:"Direct proof: assume hypothesis, show conclusion follows logically. Proof by contrapositive: prove 'not Q → not P' instead of 'P → Q'. Proof by contradiction: assume negation of conclusion, derive contradiction. Mathematical induction: base case (n=1 true) + inductive step (if n=k true, then n=k+1 true) → true for all positive integers. Strong induction: assume all cases up to k. Proof by cases: exhaust all possible cases. Counterexample: single example that disproves a universal claim.",keywords:["proof","mathematical induction","contrapositive","contradiction","direct proof","counterexample","inductive step","base case"]},{term:"Probability Distributions",def:"Discrete distributions: Binomial P(X=k) = C(n,k)pᵏ(1−p)ⁿ⁻ᵏ; μ = np, σ² = np(1−p). Poisson P(X=k) = e^(−λ)λᵏ/k!; μ = σ² = λ (rare events in interval). Continuous distributions: Normal (bell curve; 68-95-99.7 rule). Exponential: time between Poisson events; memoryless property. Uniform: equal probability on interval. Central Limit Theorem: sample means approach normal distribution regardless of population distribution as n → ∞.",keywords:["binomial distribution","poisson distribution","normal distribution","exponential distribution","central limit theorem","probability distribution","expected value","variance distribution"]},{term:"Number Bases & Modular Arithmetic",def:"Base-2 (binary): digits 0,1; used in computers. Base-8 (octal): digits 0–7. Base-16 (hexadecimal): digits 0–9 and A–F. Conversion: repeatedly divide by base, collect remainders. Modular arithmetic: a ≡ b (mod n) means n | (a−b). Arithmetic mod n: (a+b) mod n, (ab) mod n. Fermat's Little Theorem: if p prime, aᵖ ≡ a (mod p). Chinese Remainder Theorem: system of congruences with coprime moduli has unique solution mod product. Applications: cryptography, hashing, calendar calculations.",keywords:["binary","hexadecimal","modular arithmetic","congruence","fermat's little theorem","base conversion","chinese remainder theorem","number base"]},{term:"Combinatorics (Advanced)",def:"Inclusion-exclusion principle: |A∪B∪C| = |A|+|B|+|C| − |A∩B| − |A∩C| − |B∩C| + |A∩B∩C|. Stars and bars: distributing n identical objects into k distinct bins = C(n+k−1, k−1). Derangements: permutations with no fixed point; D(n) = n!(1 − 1/1! + 1/2! − … + (−1)ⁿ/n!). Catalan numbers: Cₙ = C(2n,n)/(n+1); count valid parenthesizations and paths. Pigeonhole principle: if n+1 items in n containers, at least one container has ≥2 items.",keywords:["inclusion exclusion","stars and bars","derangement","catalan number","pigeonhole principle","combinatorics advanced","counting principle"]},{term:"Euler's Formula & Complex Analysis",def:"Euler's formula: e^(iθ) = cosθ + i sinθ. Euler's identity: e^(iπ) + 1 = 0. De Moivre's theorem: (cosθ + i sinθ)ⁿ = cos(nθ) + i sin(nθ). Polar form of complex number: z = r e^(iθ) = r(cosθ + i sinθ). Multiplication in polar form: multiply moduli, add arguments. Roots of unity: solutions to zⁿ = 1 are equally spaced on unit circle. nth roots: n solutions, spaced 2π/n apart. Fourier series uses complex exponentials as basis functions.",keywords:["euler's formula","euler's identity","de moivre","polar form complex","roots of unity","complex exponential","complex analysis"]},{term:"Linear Algebra (Eigenvalues)",def:"Eigenvalue equation: Av = λv (A is matrix, λ is eigenvalue, v is eigenvector). Find eigenvalues: solve det(A − λI) = 0 (characteristic polynomial). Eigenvectors: solve (A − λI)v = 0. Diagonalization: A = PDP⁻¹ where D is diagonal matrix of eigenvalues, P has eigenvectors as columns. Symmetric matrices have real eigenvalues and orthogonal eigenvectors. Applications: principal component analysis (PCA), differential equations, Google PageRank, quantum mechanics.",keywords:["eigenvalue","eigenvector","characteristic polynomial","diagonalization","symmetric matrix","pca","linear algebra eigenvalue"]},{term:"Recurrence Relations",def:"Equations defining sequences in terms of previous terms. Linear recurrences with constant coefficients: aₙ = c₁aₙ₋₁ + c₂aₙ₋₂ + … Characteristic equation method: substitute aₙ = rⁿ to get characteristic polynomial; roots r give solution. Fibonacci: aₙ = aₙ₋₁ + aₙ₋₂; closed form (Binet's formula): Fₙ = (φⁿ − ψⁿ)/√5 where φ = (1+√5)/2 (golden ratio). Generating functions: represent sequence as power series coefficients to solve recurrences.",keywords:["recurrence relation","characteristic equation","fibonacci recurrence","binet formula","golden ratio","generating function","linear recurrence"]},{term:"Hyperbolic Functions",def:"Defined using exponentials: sinh x = (eˣ − e⁻ˣ)/2; cosh x = (eˣ + e⁻ˣ)/2; tanh x = sinh x / cosh x. Identity: cosh²x − sinh²x = 1. Derivatives: d/dx[sinh x] = cosh x; d/dx[cosh x] = sinh x. Inverse: arcsinh x = ln(x + √(x²+1)); arccosh x = ln(x + √(x²−1)) (x ≥ 1). Applications: catenary curve (hanging chain); special relativity (rapidity); solutions to Laplace's equation.",keywords:["hyperbolic function","sinh","cosh","tanh","catenary","hyperbolic identity","inverse hyperbolic","exponential definition"]},{term:"Game Theory",def:"Mathematical study of strategic decision-making. Nash equilibrium: no player can improve their payoff by unilaterally changing strategy; can have multiple or no pure-strategy equilibria. Prisoner's dilemma: individually rational choices lead to collectively suboptimal outcomes. Dominant strategy: best regardless of opponent's choice. Zero-sum games: one player's gain = other's loss (solved by minimax theorem). Mixed strategies: probabilistic choices. Applications: economics, evolutionary biology (evolutionarily stable strategies), political science.",keywords:["nash equilibrium","prisoner's dilemma","dominant strategy","zero sum game","minimax","mixed strategy","game theory","evolutionary stable strategy"]},{term:"Improper Integrals & Convergence",def:"Improper integral: infinite limits or discontinuous integrand. Type 1 (infinite limits): ∫[a,∞) f(x)dx = lim_{t→∞} ∫[a,t] f(x)dx. Type 2 (discontinuity): ∫[a,b] f(x)dx where f is discontinuous at endpoint. Comparison test: if 0 ≤ f(x) ≤ g(x) and ∫g converges, so does ∫f. p-integral: ∫[1,∞) x^(−p)dx converges iff p > 1. Gamma function: Γ(n) = ∫[0,∞) x^(n−1)e^(−x)dx = (n−1)! for positive integers.",keywords:["improper integral","convergence integral","p-integral","gamma function","infinite limit","comparison test integral","type 1 type 2 improper"]},{term:"Boolean Algebra & Logic Gates",def:"Boolean algebra uses values 0 (false) and 1 (true). Operations: AND (A·B), OR (A+B), NOT (A'). De Morgan's Laws: (A·B)' = A'+B'; (A+B)' = A'·B'. Logic gates: AND, OR, NOT, NAND, NOR, XOR (A⊕B = A'B + AB'). Truth tables enumerate all input combinations. Sum of products (SOP) and product of sums (POS) forms. Karnaugh maps simplify Boolean expressions. Applications: digital circuit design, computer architecture, cryptography.",keywords:["boolean algebra","logic gate","and or not","de morgan","truth table","nand","xor","karnaugh map","digital logic","sum of products"]},{term:"Numerical Methods",def:"Algorithms for approximating solutions to mathematical problems. Newton-Raphson method: xₙ₊₁ = xₙ − f(xₙ)/f'(xₙ); fast convergence (quadratic) for root-finding. Bisection method: bracket root, halve interval; slower but guaranteed. Euler's method: numerical ODE solving; yₙ₊₁ = yₙ + h·f(xₙ, yₙ). Runge-Kutta (RK4): more accurate ODE solver. Trapezoidal rule and Simpson's rule: numerical integration. Error analysis: truncation error (method) vs roundoff error (finite precision).",keywords:["newton-raphson","bisection method","euler method","runge-kutta","numerical integration","trapezoidal rule","simpson's rule","root finding numerical"]},{level:"MS",term:"Fractions, Decimals & Percents",def:"Fraction: part of a whole (numerator/denominator). To convert fraction to decimal: divide numerator by denominator. Percent: parts per hundred; convert to decimal by dividing by 100 (75% = 0.75). Percent of a number: multiply (30% of 80 = 0.30 × 80 = 24). Operations with fractions: to add/subtract, find a common denominator; to multiply, multiply straight across; to divide, multiply by the reciprocal.",keywords:["fraction","decimal","percent","numerator","denominator","common denominator","reciprocal","convert fraction"]},{level:"MS",term:"Ratios & Proportions",def:"A ratio compares two quantities (3:4 or 3/4). A proportion is an equation stating two ratios are equal (3/4 = 6/8). Cross-multiplication: if a/b = c/d then ad = bc. Unit rate: ratio with denominator 1 (60 miles per hour). Scale factor: ratio used in scale drawings and similar figures. Direct variation: y = kx; as x increases, y increases proportionally.",keywords:["ratio","proportion","unit rate","cross multiplication","scale factor","direct variation","similar figures"]},{level:"MS",term:"Algebra Basics",def:"Variable: a letter representing an unknown value. Expression: combination of numbers, variables, and operations (3x + 2). Equation: two expressions set equal (3x + 2 = 11). Solving: use inverse operations to isolate the variable. Order of operations: PEMDAS (Parentheses, Exponents, Multiplication/Division, Addition/Subtraction). Distributive property: a(b + c) = ab + ac.",keywords:["variable","expression","equation","order of operations","pemdas","distributive property","solve","algebra"]},{level:"MS",term:"Geometry (Area & Perimeter)",def:"Perimeter: sum of all side lengths. Area formulas: rectangle = length × width; triangle = ½ × base × height; parallelogram = base × height; trapezoid = ½(b₁ + b₂) × h; circle = πr². Circumference of circle = 2πr = πd. Volume: rectangular prism = l × w × h; cylinder = πr²h; cone = ⅓πr²h; sphere = 4/3πr³. Surface area = sum of all face areas.",keywords:["area","perimeter","rectangle","triangle","circle","circumference","volume","cylinder","sphere","pi"]},{level:"MS",term:"Exponents & Scientific Notation",def:"Exponent rules: xᵃ × xᵇ = xᵃ⁺ᵇ; xᵃ / xᵇ = xᵃ⁻ᵇ; (xᵃ)ᵇ = xᵃᵇ; x⁰ = 1; x⁻ⁿ = 1/xⁿ. Scientific notation: a × 10ⁿ where 1 ≤ a < 10. To multiply in scientific notation: multiply the coefficients and add exponents. To add/subtract: first make the exponents equal. Examples: 3×10⁴ × 2×10³ = 6×10⁷.",keywords:["exponent","scientific notation","power","exponent rule","multiply exponents","negative exponent","powers of ten"]},{level:"MS",term:"Probability (Basic)",def:"Probability = number of favorable outcomes / total number of outcomes. Range: 0 (impossible) to 1 (certain). Complementary events: P(A) + P(not A) = 1. Independent events: P(A and B) = P(A) × P(B). Mutually exclusive events: P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B). Experimental probability: based on trials; theoretical probability: based on perfect conditions.",keywords:["probability","outcome","favorable","complementary","independent events","mutually exclusive","theoretical","experimental"]},{level:"MS",term:"Statistics & Data (Basic)",def:"Mean (average): sum of values ÷ number of values. Median: middle value when data is ordered (average of two middle values if even count). Mode: most frequently occurring value. Range: maximum − minimum. Interquartile range (IQR): Q3 − Q1. Outlier: a data point that is much higher or lower than most. Bar graphs, histograms, box plots, and scatter plots display data.",keywords:["mean","median","mode","range","interquartile range","outlier","average","data","statistics"]},{level:"MS",term:"Integers & Number Properties",def:"Integers include positive whole numbers, negative whole numbers, and zero. Adding integers: same sign → add and keep sign; different signs → subtract and keep the sign of the larger absolute value. Multiplying/dividing: same signs → positive result; different signs → negative result. Absolute value |x|: distance from zero on a number line; always non-negative.",keywords:["integer","negative number","absolute value","number line","positive","additive inverse","opposites","whole number"]},{level:"MS",term:"Linear Equations & Graphing",def:"Linear equation: y = mx + b (slope-intercept form). Slope (m) = rise/run = (y₂ − y₁)/(x₂ − x₁); represents rate of change. Y-intercept (b): where line crosses the y-axis. Positive slope: line goes up left to right. Negative slope: line goes down. Horizontal line: slope = 0. Vertical line: undefined slope. Two lines are parallel if they have equal slopes.",keywords:["linear equation","slope","y-intercept","slope-intercept form","graphing","rate of change","parallel","rise over run"]},{level:"MS",term:"Place Value & Number Systems",def:"The value of a digit depends on its position (place) in a number. In base 10: ones, tens, hundreds, thousands, … to the left of the decimal; tenths, hundredths, thousandths, … to the right. Expanded form: 3,472 = 3×1000 + 4×100 + 7×10 + 2×1. Rounding: look at the digit to the right of the rounding place; if ≥5, round up; if <5, round down. Comparing decimals: align decimal points and compare digit by digit. The number line shows all real numbers in order; negative numbers are to the left of zero.",keywords:["place value","decimal place","rounding","expanded form","base ten","digit value","number line","comparing decimals"]},{level:"MS",term:"Negative Numbers & Absolute Value",def:"Negative numbers are less than zero; used for temperatures below freezing, debt, sea level depths. On a number line, negatives are left of zero. Absolute value |x|: the distance from zero; always non-negative. |-5| = |5| = 5. Adding: same signs → add and keep sign; different signs → subtract and keep sign of larger absolute value. Subtracting: add the opposite. Multiplying/Dividing: same signs → positive; opposite signs → negative. Ordering integers: −10 < −3 < 0 < 5 < 12.",keywords:["negative number","absolute value","integer operations","adding integers","subtracting integers","multiplying integers","number line integers","opposites"]},{level:"MS",term:"Order of Operations",def:"PEMDAS (Please Excuse My Dear Aunt Sally): Parentheses first, then Exponents, then Multiplication and Division (left to right), then Addition and Subtraction (left to right). Also called BODMAS (Brackets, Orders, Division/Multiplication, Addition/Subtraction). Example: 3 + 4 × 2² − (8 ÷ 4) = 3 + 4 × 4 − 2 = 3 + 16 − 2 = 17. Common mistakes: forgetting that multiplication and division have equal priority (left to right), and same for addition and subtraction. Brackets/parentheses always evaluated first, innermost first.",keywords:["order of operations","pemdas","bodmas","parentheses first","exponent order","multiplication division","addition subtraction","mathematical priority"]},{level:"MS",term:"Factors, Multiples & Divisibility",def:"Factor: a number that divides evenly into another (factors of 12: 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 12). Multiple: result of multiplying a number by an integer (multiples of 5: 5, 10, 15, 20…). GCF (Greatest Common Factor): largest factor shared by two numbers (GCF of 12 and 18 is 6). LCM (Least Common Multiple): smallest number divisible by both (LCM of 4 and 6 is 12). GCF × LCM = product of the two numbers. Divisibility rules: divisible by 2 (even), 3 (digit sum divisible by 3), 4 (last two digits), 5 (ends in 0 or 5), 6 (divisible by 2 and 3), 9 (digit sum divisible by 9), 10 (ends in 0).",keywords:["factor","multiple","gcf","lcm","divisibility rule","greatest common factor","least common multiple","prime factorization basic"]},{level:"MS",term:"Coordinate Plane",def:"Two perpendicular number lines (x-axis horizontal, y-axis vertical) intersecting at the origin (0,0). Points written as ordered pairs (x, y). Four quadrants: I (+, +), II (−, +), III (−, −), IV (+, −). Plotting points: move x units horizontally, y units vertically from origin. Distance between two points: d = √[(x₂−x₁)² + (y₂−y₁)²]. Midpoint: ((x₁+x₂)/2, (y₁+y₂)/2). Reflections: across x-axis → (x, −y); across y-axis → (−x, y); across origin → (−x, −y). Used for graphing equations and geometric transformations.",keywords:["coordinate plane","ordered pair","quadrant","x-axis","y-axis","origin","plotting points","distance formula basic","midpoint basic","reflection coordinate"]},{level:"MS",term:"Inequalities",def:"Inequality symbols: < (less than), > (greater than), ≤ (less than or equal), ≥ (greater than or equal), ≠ (not equal). Solving: same as equations, BUT when multiplying or dividing both sides by a negative number, flip the inequality sign. Graphing on a number line: open circle for < or > (endpoint not included); closed circle for ≤ or ≥ (included). Compound inequalities: AND (intersection; 'between' — both conditions must be met); OR (union; either condition). Example: −2 < x ≤ 5 means x is greater than −2 AND less than or equal to 5.",keywords:["inequality","less than","greater than","flip inequality","compound inequality","number line inequality","open closed circle","solving inequality"]},{level:"MS",term:"Pythagorean Theorem",def:"In a right triangle, the square of the hypotenuse (longest side, opposite the right angle) equals the sum of the squares of the other two legs: a² + b² = c². Used to find the length of any side if two sides are known. Example: a=3, b=4 → c=√(9+16)=√25=5 (3-4-5 is a Pythagorean triple). Other common triples: 5-12-13, 8-15-17. Also used to determine if a triangle is right-angled: if a² + b² = c², it's a right triangle. Converse: if a² + b² ≠ c², not a right triangle. Can find distances in the coordinate plane.",keywords:["pythagorean theorem","hypotenuse","right triangle","a squared b squared","pythagorean triple","3 4 5","right angle triangle","leg hypotenuse"]},{level:"MS",term:"Angle Relationships",def:"Complementary angles: sum to 90°. Supplementary angles: sum to 180°. Vertical angles: formed by intersecting lines; they are equal. Adjacent angles: share a vertex and a side. Straight angle = 180°. Right angle = 90°. Acute angle < 90°. Obtuse angle: between 90° and 180°. Transversal crossing parallel lines creates: corresponding angles (equal), alternate interior angles (equal), alternate exterior angles (equal), co-interior/consecutive interior angles (supplementary = 180°). Triangle angle sum = 180°. Exterior angle of triangle = sum of two non-adjacent interior angles.",keywords:["complementary","supplementary","vertical angles","corresponding angles","alternate interior","parallel lines angles","triangle angle sum","exterior angle","transversal"]},{level:"MS",term:"Triangles",def:"Classified by sides: equilateral (all sides equal, all angles 60°), isosceles (two equal sides, two equal base angles), scalene (no equal sides). Classified by angles: acute (all angles < 90°), right (one 90° angle), obtuse (one angle > 90°). Triangle inequality: sum of any two sides > third side. Area = ½ × base × height. Perimeter = sum of all three sides. Similar triangles: same shape, proportional sides (AA, SAS, SSS similarity). Congruent triangles: same shape and size (SSS, SAS, ASA, AAS congruence). Largest angle opposite longest side.",keywords:["equilateral triangle","isosceles","scalene","acute triangle","right triangle type","obtuse triangle","similar triangles","congruent triangles","triangle area","triangle inequality"]},{level:"MS",term:"Proportional Relationships & Unit Rate",def:"A proportional relationship: y = kx where k is the constant of proportionality (unit rate). On a graph: a straight line through the origin. k = y/x for any point. Unit rate: ratio expressed as a quantity per one unit (speed in miles per hour, price per pound, heart beats per minute). Scale factor: ratio of corresponding measurements in similar figures. To solve proportions: cross-multiply. Direct proportion: as x increases, y increases proportionally. Inverse proportion: as x increases, y decreases (xy = k). Percent proportion: part/whole = percent/100.",keywords:["proportional relationship","constant of proportionality","unit rate","direct proportion","inverse proportion","scale factor basic","cross multiply","percent proportion","y=kx"]},{level:"MS",term:"Percent Applications",def:"Percent change = (new − old) / old × 100%. Percent increase: positive change. Percent decrease: negative change (% decrease = (old − new)/old × 100%). Simple interest: I = Prt (principal × rate × time in years). Discount: subtract percent of original price. Markup: add percent of cost to cost. Tax/tip: add percent of price. Finding original amount after percent change: original = new amount / (1 ± percent as decimal). Sales tax: total = price × (1 + tax rate). Example: item costs $80, 25% off: discount = $20, sale price = $60.",keywords:["percent change","percent increase","percent decrease","simple interest","discount","markup","sales tax","percent original","tip percent","i=prt"]},{level:"MS",term:"Geometry: Volume & Surface Area",def:"Volume: rectangular prism = l × w × h; cube = s³; cylinder = πr²h; cone = ⅓πr²h; sphere = (4/3)πr³; pyramid = ⅓ × base area × height. Surface area: rectangular prism = 2(lw + lh + wh); cube = 6s²; cylinder = 2πr² + 2πrh; sphere = 4πr². Net: a flat shape that can be folded into a 3D figure; used to visualize and calculate surface area. Cavalieri's Principle: two solids with equal height and equal cross-sectional areas at every level have equal volumes. Units of volume: cm³, m³, liters (1 L = 1000 cm³).",keywords:["volume","surface area","rectangular prism","cylinder volume","cone volume","sphere volume","net 3d shape","cavalieri","surface area formula"]},{level:"MS",term:"Transformations",def:"Translation: slides a figure along a vector (a, b) — adds a to x-coordinates, b to y-coordinates. Rotation: turns a figure around a center point by a given angle (90°, 180°, 270° CW or CCW). Reflection: flips a figure over a line of reflection. Dilation: enlarges or reduces a figure by a scale factor k (k>1 enlargement; 0<k<1 reduction). Rigid transformations (isometries): translations, rotations, reflections — preserve size and shape. Non-rigid: dilations — preserve shape but not size. Congruent figures: related by rigid transformations. Similar figures: related by dilations (and rigid transformations).",keywords:["translation","rotation","reflection","dilation","transformation","rigid transformation","isometry","scale factor dilation","congruent similar transformation","coordinate transformation"]},{level:"MS",term:"Systems of Equations",def:"Two or more equations solved simultaneously. Graphing method: find intersection point of lines. Substitution method: solve one equation for a variable, substitute into the other. Elimination (addition) method: add or subtract equations to eliminate a variable. Three possible outcomes: one solution (lines intersect at a point — consistent and independent), no solution (parallel lines — inconsistent), infinitely many solutions (same line — consistent and dependent). Applications: finding two unknown quantities simultaneously (mixture problems, age problems, distance-rate-time problems).",keywords:["system of equations","substitution method","elimination method","graphing equations","consistent inconsistent","no solution","infinite solutions","simultaneous equations"]},{level:"MS",term:"Functions (Basic)",def:"A function: a rule that assigns exactly one output (y) to each input (x). Represented as f(x). Vertical line test: if any vertical line crosses the graph more than once, it's NOT a function. Domain: set of all valid inputs (x-values). Range: set of all outputs (y-values). Ways to represent functions: tables, graphs, equations, mapping diagrams. Linear function: f(x) = mx + b. Quadratic function: f(x) = ax² + bx + c (parabola). Increasing: output increases as input increases. Decreasing: output decreases as input increases.",keywords:["function basic","input output","f(x)","vertical line test","domain range basic","linear function basic","quadratic basic","increasing decreasing function","mapping diagram"]},{level:"MS",term:"Data & Graphs",def:"Bar graph: compares categories using bars of different heights. Line graph: shows change over time; good for trends. Pie chart (circle graph): shows parts of a whole as sectors (percentages must sum to 100%). Histogram: bar chart for continuous data organized in intervals/bins; no gaps between bars. Scatter plot: shows relationship between two quantitative variables; each point represents one data pair. Line of best fit (trend line): drawn through scatter plot to show general trend. Positive correlation: both variables increase together. Negative correlation: one increases, other decreases. No correlation: no pattern.",keywords:["bar graph","line graph","pie chart","histogram","scatter plot","line of best fit","correlation","positive correlation","negative correlation","data display"]},{level:"MS",term:"Measures of Center & Spread",def:"Measures of center: mean (sum ÷ count; affected by outliers), median (middle value when ordered; resistant to outliers), mode (most frequent value; can have multiple or none). Measures of spread: range (max − min), interquartile range IQR = Q3 − Q1 (middle 50% of data; resistant to outliers), mean absolute deviation (MAD = average distance from mean). Standard deviation: average distance from the mean (larger → more spread out). Outlier: a value more than 1.5 × IQR below Q1 or above Q3. Box plot shows min, Q1, median, Q3, max.",keywords:["mean median mode","measures of center","range","interquartile range","iqr","outlier","box plot","standard deviation basic","measures of spread","mad"]},{level:"MS",term:"Scientific Notation (Detail)",def:"Scientific notation: a × 10ⁿ where 1 ≤ a < 10. Very large: 4,300,000 = 4.3 × 10⁶. Very small: 0.00057 = 5.7 × 10⁻⁴. To multiply: multiply coefficients and add exponents (3×10⁴ × 2×10³ = 6×10⁷). To divide: divide coefficients and subtract exponents. To add/subtract: must convert to same power of 10 first. Applications in science: speed of light = 3×10⁸ m/s; mass of electron = 9.11×10⁻³¹ kg; distance to Andromeda galaxy = 2.5×10⁶ light-years. Calculators display scientific notation as '6.02E23' for 6.02×10²³.",keywords:["scientific notation detail","large numbers notation","small numbers notation","multiply scientific notation","divide scientific notation","add scientific notation","10 to the power","significant figures"]},{level:"MS",term:"Simple & Compound Interest",def:"Simple interest: I = Prt; total amount A = P(1 + rt). P = principal, r = annual interest rate (decimal), t = time (years). Example: $1000 at 5% for 3 years: I = 1000 × 0.05 × 3 = $150; total = $1150. Compound interest: interest is calculated on principal AND previously earned interest. Formula: A = P(1 + r/n)^(nt) where n = number of times compounded per year. Continuously compounded: A = Pe^(rt). Compound interest grows faster than simple interest. Rule of 72: approximate years to double money = 72 / interest rate (%).",keywords:["simple interest","compound interest","principal","interest rate","i=prt","compound formula","rule of 72","annual interest","growth money"]},{level:"MS",term:"Square Roots & Cube Roots",def:"Square root: √x = y means y² = x. Perfect squares: 1, 4, 9, 16, 25, 36, 49, 64, 81, 100, 121, 144, 169, 196, 225. √72 = 6√2 (simplify by factoring out largest perfect square). Cube root: ∛x = y means y³ = x. Perfect cubes: 1, 8, 27, 64, 125, 216, 343. Irrational numbers: square roots of non-perfect squares (√2 ≈ 1.414, √3 ≈ 1.732); cannot be expressed as a fraction; non-terminating, non-repeating decimals. Estimating square roots: √50 is between √49=7 and √64=8, closer to 7 since 50 is closer to 49.",keywords:["square root","cube root","perfect square","perfect cube","irrational number","simplify radical","estimating roots","radical expression"]},{level:"MS",term:"Proportions & Similar Figures",def:"Similar figures: same shape, different size; corresponding angles are equal; corresponding sides are proportional. Scale factor: ratio of corresponding sides (e.g., scale factor of 3 means all lengths tripled, areas × 9, volumes × 27). To find missing side in similar figures: set up proportion (a/b = c/d) and cross-multiply. Scale drawings: maps, blueprints, models use a scale ratio (e.g., 1 cm = 50 km). Indirect measurement: use similar triangles to measure heights/distances you cannot measure directly (e.g., shadow method to find tree height).",keywords:["similar figures basic","scale factor basic","proportion similar","corresponding sides","indirect measurement","scale drawing","cross multiply proportion","map scale"]},{level:"MS",term:"Probability: Compound Events",def:"Compound event: involves two or more simple events. Independent events: outcome of one does not affect the other (flipping two coins). P(A and B) = P(A) × P(B) for independent events. Dependent events: outcome of one affects the other (drawing cards without replacement). P(A and B) = P(A) × P(B|A) (conditional probability). P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B) − P(A and B) (addition rule). Complementary: P(not A) = 1 − P(A). Sample space: list all possible outcomes. Tree diagrams and tables help organize compound probability problems.",keywords:["compound probability","independent events","dependent events","conditional probability","addition rule probability","complementary probability","sample space","tree diagram probability"]},{level:"MS",term:"Number Patterns & Sequences",def:"Arithmetic sequence: each term found by adding a constant (common difference d). aₙ = a₁ + (n−1)d. Example: 3, 7, 11, 15 (d=4). Sum of n terms: Sₙ = n(a₁+aₙ)/2. Geometric sequence: each term found by multiplying by a constant (common ratio r). aₙ = a₁ × r^(n−1). Example: 2, 6, 18, 54 (r=3). Sum of geometric series: Sₙ = a₁(1−rⁿ)/(1−r). Fibonacci sequence: 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13 (each term is sum of previous two). Recognizing patterns: look for common differences, ratios, or more complex rules.",keywords:["arithmetic sequence basic","geometric sequence basic","common difference","common ratio basic","sequence pattern","fibonacci basic","nth term","series sum basic"]},{level:"MS",term:"Geometry: Circles",def:"Circle: set of all points equidistant from center. Radius (r): center to edge. Diameter (d = 2r): across center. Circumference C = 2πr = πd. Area A = πr². π ≈ 3.14159. Arc: part of the circumference; arc length = (central angle/360°) × 2πr. Sector: pie-slice region; area = (central angle/360°) × πr². Chord: segment connecting two points on circle. Tangent: line touching circle at exactly one point. Inscribed angle: vertex on circle; inscribed angle = ½ × intercepted arc. Central angle = intercepted arc. Semicircle: 180°.",keywords:["circle","radius","diameter","circumference","area circle","arc length","sector area","chord","tangent","central angle","inscribed angle"]},{level:"MS",term:"Rational & Irrational Numbers",def:"Rational numbers: can be expressed as a fraction p/q where p and q are integers and q ≠ 0; includes all integers, fractions, terminating decimals (0.75), and repeating decimals (0.333… = 1/3). Irrational numbers: cannot be expressed as a fraction; non-terminating, non-repeating decimals (√2 = 1.41421…; π = 3.14159…). Real numbers: all rational and irrational numbers combined. Converting repeating decimal to fraction: let x = 0.333…; 10x = 3.333…; 10x − x = 3; 9x = 3; x = 1/3. √(perfect square) is rational; √(non-perfect square) is irrational.",keywords:["rational number","irrational number","real number","terminating decimal","repeating decimal","fraction conversion","pi irrational","square root rational"]},{level:"MS",term:"Algebra: Solving Multi-Step Equations",def:"Goal: isolate the variable using inverse operations. Steps: 1) Use distributive property to remove parentheses. 2) Combine like terms on each side. 3) Use addition/subtraction to get variable terms on one side. 4) Use multiplication/division to solve for variable. Variables on both sides: collect all variable terms on one side, constants on the other. Example: 3(x + 2) = 2x + 11 → 3x + 6 = 2x + 11 → x = 5. Always check your answer by substituting back into the original equation. Equations with no solution (0=5) or infinite solutions (5=5).",keywords:["multi-step equation","distributive property equation","like terms equation","inverse operations","variable both sides","solving for x","checking solution","linear equation solving"]},{level:"MS",term:"Scale Drawings & Measurement",def:"Scale drawing: represents a real object proportionally. Scale: written as ratio (1:100) or with units (1 cm = 10 m). To find actual size: multiply drawing measurement by scale factor. To find drawing size: divide actual size by scale factor. Unit conversions (customary): 12 inches = 1 foot; 3 feet = 1 yard; 5,280 feet = 1 mile. Unit conversions (metric): kilo (×1000), hecto (×100), deka (×10), base, deci (÷10), centi (÷100), milli (÷1000). Converting metric: move decimal point. Converting between systems: 1 inch = 2.54 cm; 1 kg ≈ 2.2 lb; 1 mile ≈ 1.61 km.",keywords:["scale drawing basic","scale ratio","unit conversion","metric conversion","customary units","measurement","actual vs drawing size","inch foot yard","meter centimeter"]},{level:"MS",term:"Sampling & Statistics",def:"Population: entire group being studied. Sample: subset of population used to make inferences. Random sample: every member has an equal chance of being selected — reduces bias. Sampling methods: simple random (lottery/random number), stratified (divide into subgroups, sample proportionally), systematic (every nth person), convenience (easiest available — most biased). Bias: systematic error that skews results. Sample size: larger samples → more accurate estimates. Margin of error: indicates how much sample results may differ from true population value. Surveys, experiments, and observational studies are different ways to collect data.",keywords:["population statistics","sample","random sample","sampling method","stratified sampling","systematic sampling","bias statistics","margin of error","survey experiment observation"]}]}};